<HTML>
<TITLE> PlantExec, September 1996</TITLE>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#005B52" VLINK="#0D50A2" ALINK="#FFFFFF">

<BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/gif/plant.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="2">AN UPDATE FOR PLANT ENVIRONMENTAL EXECUTIVES</FONT>
<BR>
September 1996
</CENTER>

<HR> 


<UL>
<H2>Contents</H2>
<UL>
     <A HREF="sept96.html#rethink"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>Waste Not, Want Not</KBD></FONT></A>
     <P>
     <A HREF="sept96.html#tech"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>Technology Update</KBD></FONT></A>
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="waste"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=20><KBD>WASTE NOT,<BR>
WANT NOT</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>The company was committed to compliance. What it needed 
was a pair of outside eyes to help do it better.</H4>
<FONT SIZE=+3>I</FONT>n October 1994 Lock & Load, Inc. (L&L), asked ERM to help "identify and characterize" solid waste generated at its 
5,100-employee, 1.5 million-square-foot facility in southern Georgia. That's where, 
in more than 200 facility departments, L&L designs, assembles and tests weapons systems for military use.
<p>	
ERM's assignment 
was to help L&L comply with federal and state regulations involving the management and disposal of solid wastes and important hazardous wastes. 
<p>
As a RCRA-permitted hazardous waste storage facility, L&L was required 
to develop and implement a Waste Analysis Plan (WAP) documenting the company's procedures for character-izing hazardous waste streams. ERM's job was to ensure that the WAP was up-to-date, and that all waste streams were being appropriately managed-
a project that required the cataloging of all generated wastes and a series of department audits.
<p>	
For L&L, the project 
was a way of ensuring that the firm was acting as a responsible employer and corporate good neighbor, 
as well as complying with regulatory requirements.		
<p>
	From the outset, however, L&L realized that it lacked the time and expertise to handle the job alone. 
<p>

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=RIGHT>
<CAPTION ALIGN=BOTTOM><B>Herin</B></CAPTION>
<TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="/gif/chris.gif">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

	"In my experience," says ERM project director Chris Herin, "this was not a 
common project. It was unique since L&L asked 
us to provide an external 
set of eyes to examine 
what it had done, and offer suggestions on how it could be improved."  
<p>	
Identifying and characterizing solid wastes is one of those routine tasks that turn out to be not routine at all. The project involved inventorying every waste stream in the huge facility -from old rocket propellant to plastic laser printer toner cartridges in office trash, and from plating sludges 
to air filters. By June 1996, ERM had identified nearly 1,200 waste streams, a 
quarter of which were 
hazardous. "One of the best things about the project," 
says Herin, "is that we developed a partnering arrangement with L&L as opposed to the standard consultant/client relationship. We had desk space 
in L&L's offices and felt comfortable going to work there. We didn't have to 
tiptoe around."  
<p>
	L&L wanted to do 
more than merely update 
its documentation. What the company needed were ideas on how to better manage its waste-related liabilities, as well as recommendations for improving training, 
waste minimization and
pollution prevention. 
<p>
	Four months before 
ERM became actively involved, L&L had circulated waste generation surveys to all its departments. Information from the surveys was used by ERM to develop a compatible database. When an L&L department reported generating no waste, ERM team members would call, fax or e-mail requesting 
verification. They asked how the department disposed 
of used toner cartridges from its copy machines or batteries from its telephones. This resulted in the identification of a number of 
"new" waste streams.
<p>
	The ERM team created a separate tracking system for each waste stream, and the resulting characterizations were reviewed by at least two members of the ERM team. Did it meet the 40 CFR 261 definition of solid waste? Was it specifically exempted from the regulations, or exempted because it was reclaimed material? 	
<p>
Was it adequately characterized for land disposal restriction purposes? ERM provided the answers. Waste streams were characterized as non-hazardous or by their EPA hazardous waste codes, as well as subclassifications specific to L&L's operations and desire to integrate GIS tracking into facility management.	
<p>
	By June 1995, ERM 
had developed recommen-dations to improve the 
management of many waste streams, including a series of waste management 
protocol memoranda for L&L's environmental affairs department to use with company departments that were delinquent in turning in reports for the waste stream tracking system and that needed improvement in waste management procedures. Beyond the recommendations, ERM met with 
the L&L environmental coordinators assigned in each department to brief them on the report and 
its implications. 
<p>
	L&L's coordinators,
after receiving the recommendations, returned to their departments empowered to communicate 
corrective actions to 
appropriate departmental staff. (Department heads 
had an extra incentive to 
listen to these coordinators: Their bonuses were tied to environmental performance.) 
<p>
Then, three months later, ERM scheduled on-site, follow-up audits with almost half of the facility's departments (those that generated the most waste) to verify that corrective actions had occurred. Departments selected for the surprise audits were ones requiring corrections that could be spot-checked visually, or that had long lists of 
suggested corrections. All corrections having to do with hazardous wastes had been addressed. But some corrections suggested for non-hazardous wastes, ERM found, had not occurred-especially in the area of 
recycling. Further follow-up was turned over to L&L's corporate environmental affairs department-which, by the way, was also audited. 
<p>	
"What's left," says Herin, "is training and information dissemination"-undertakings being managed by L&L. "This," he says, "was a very satisfying job for the ERM team. We fulfilled a very large waste management requirement for L&L, and we were able to do it by working cooperatively with 
a large number of its departments and staff."
<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

<A NAME="http"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=10><KBD>http://www.erm.com</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>


It's new, it's up-to-date, it's essential. The Environmental Resources Management Web site, which you'll find at the address above, is the new source for environmental, health and safety (EHS) management on the information superhighway.
<p>	
The site provides access to the latest information about today's important environmental issues. You can browse through timely magazines and books in the Environmental Library, connect to important regulatory alerts with the Hot Button, or link directly to the ERM Weekly Update for the latest federal and state regulatory activity. You can also explore ERM's worldwide network of offices on an interactive map, and visit other sites of environmental interest in cyberspace. So join ERM on the Webit's just a phone call away.
<p>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/gif/webguy.gif">
</CENTER>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<A NAME="tech"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=10><KBD>Technology Update</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<CENTER>
<B>If the mountain won't go to the lab,
<BR> 
this lab will go to the mountain</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
After five years and more than 200 projects, ERM's on-site field analysis ERM-FAST service (Field Analytical Services Technology) has become established as a major force at the leading edge of environmental intervention. Clients have a variety of reasons for choosing ERM-FAST. Instead of sending samples to a lab, ERM-FAST vans or trailers come to client sites to:	
<p>
<ul>
<li>Obtain real-time data
<li>Focus investigations
<li>Evaluate remediation efforts
<li>Reduce the total 
number of samples sent to the fixed laboratory
<li>Protect sampling 
personnel
<li>Reduce total project costs.
</ul>
<p>
A typical scenario: In a RCRA facility site closure action, soil and water samples need to be evaluated to determine if clean closure requirements will be met. By calling in ERM-FAST, you can pre-evaluate samples without sending samples off-site. 		
<p>	
Another example: At a prepurchase investigation at a shopping center where underground storage tanks and contaminated soils had been removed, ERM-FAST was used to screen subsurface soil samples for petroleum fraction and BTEX (benzene, toluene, ethylbenzene, xylenes) utilizing the mobile GC/MS. When field screening indicated only a low-level contamination, 
the purchaser decided to go ahead with the acquisition with a minimum of delay 
and cost.
<p>
	ERM's scientists can tailor field analyses to meet the needs of any project, or configure an appropriate system from site background or prior laboratory analysis. ERM-FAST units are equipped with portable gas chromatographs, mobile gas chromatograph/ mass spectrometers and/or energy dispersive mobile X-ray fluorescence spectrometers and can perform analyses on most environmental sample matrices for volatile organic compounds, semivolatile organic compounds, metals, pesticides and PCBs, herbicides and explosives. 	
<p>	
And ERM-FAST is fast: 
A team can begin analysis within 30 minutes of reaching a site. 
	<p>
For more information 
on ERM's field analytical 
services, call 800-544-3117.
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</BODY>
