<HTML>
<TITLE> PlantExec, June 1996</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Salman Sajid, 25-Jul-1996 -->
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#005B52" VLINK="#0D50A2" ALINK="#FFFFFF">

<BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/gif/plant.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="2">AN UPDATE FOR PLANT ENVIRONMENTAL EXECUTIVES</FONT>
<BR>
June 1996
</CENTER>

<HR> 


<UL>
<H2>Contents</H2>
<UL>
     <A HREF="june96.html#rethink"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>Rethinking the Traditional</KBD></FONT></A>
     <P>
     <A HREF="june96.html#reg"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>Regulatory Update</KBD></FONT></A>
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="rethink"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=20><KBD>RETHINKING THE<BR>
     TRADITIONAL</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H4>The client needed a solution--neither too basic nor too acidic--and with minimal sediment. Oh, and it couldn't cost too much. </H4>
<IMG SRC="/gif/178.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>
<FONT SIZE=+3>O</FONT>perating engineers 
at two dyeing and 
finishing facilities run by Spectrum, along the Okapokee River in North Carolina were, 
to put it nicely, frustrated.
<p> 
No matter what steps 
they took, they couldn't control the pH of their wastewater effluent. 
<p>
The plants were located adjacent to the town's 
publicly owned treatment works (POTW), and although Spectrum tried 
to be a good neighbor, 
the POTW had issued it violation noticestwo in a one-year periodand there seemed to be nothing the engineers could do about it. 
The notices were for 
producing caustic effluent in excess of pH 9, 
the upper discharge limit. (Spectrum also exceeded the lower 
discharge limit, pH 6.) 
<p>
So in March 1994, Spectrum asked ERM in Charlotte, North Carolina, to determine what was wrong and to come up with the most cost-efficient wastewater pretreatment system possible.
<p>
"The traditional approach to the problem," recalls ERM's Ken Pickle, senior engineer on the project, "would have been to follow the old engineering axiom 'When in doubt, make it stout'in this 
case simply building a 
large pH neutralization basin." At the time, Spectrum's effluent was 1.6 
million gallons per day; 
the firm anticipated an expansion of production that would result in a 
3.0 mgd discharge. 
<p> 

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=RIGHT>
<CAPTION ALIGN=BOTTOM><B>Pickle</B></CAPTION>
<TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="/gif/pickle.gif">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

The POTW (and tradition) suggested construction of a 3 million-gallon, 24-hour retention basinto which appropriate acids and caustics would be added to maintain the desired pH range. That would have done the job, but construction costs were estimated at $2.25 million more than the client wanted to spendand that size basin would have 
used more plant property than Spectrum wanted 
to allocate. 
<p>
From the outset, 
Pickle and ERM's project engineer, Dudney Fox, 
realized that the size of the retention basin would be the key factor in holding down costs; the larger the basin, the more clearing, grubbing, grading and excavating would have to be done, and the more would have to be spent on concrete liner, PVC liner and floating aerators. 
<p>
"We decided to reduce the doubt part of the 'When in doubt, make it stout' equation," says Pickle, and ERM started doing research to help  characterize Spectrum's wastewater.
<p>
Facility records were useful but not sufficient. So ERM conducted a field study. Project team members collected effluent 
measurements for the two 
facilities every two minutes for five days. The pH range for one plant ran from 
1.8 to 12.6; the other
ranged from 4.2 to 11.7. 
<p>
Ninety percent of the flow was basicwith a mean pH of more than 9.0so the team surmised that all they had to do was modify the existing sulfuric acid feed system to add acid in an amount that would offset the basic pH. However, since the lower pH discharge limit was 6, they would also have to have a sufficient basin volume to provide bulk neutralization of the ten percent of the wastewater flows that were acidicwhere the pH ran as low as 1.8. And more volume was what they were trying to avoid.
<p>
The team members decided to examine the chemical mechanisms that controlled the wastewater's pH values. The most important of these, they determined, was the carbonate systemthe set of equations that describe how acids and bases commingle in a closed system to yield one pH value or another. 
<p>
For the sake of developing a model, they made the major assumption that the neutralization basin could be represented as a closed carbonate species system. They knew it would be subject to error, but it was a starting point. Says Pickle, "The testing and modeling was particularly exciting for us, because although the theory behind it is widely accepted, it's not that often applied
at least not in our experience. So it was fun to get down to manipulating the equations and seeing where we could go with it." 
<p>

<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT>
<CAPTION ALIGN=BOTTOM><B>Fox</B></CAPTION>
<TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="/gif/dudney.gif">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>


They developed the model and then, to test it, took grab samples over four days. The actual acid volumes required for each wastewater titration, they found, were only 57% of their model's predictions. They recalibrated the model, developed a worst-case scenario for acid flow and presented Spectrum with a 20-page preliminary engineering report arguing for a system that could treat 3 mgd: a 320,000-
gallon basin that would hold wastewater for only 21/2 hoursmore than nine times smaller than tradition had suggested.
<p>
At first, Spectrum was skeptical. Then they upped the basin's proposed size to 375,000 gallons and the detention time to three hours and began working to convince the POTW 
that the approach was 
feasible. That was when ERM's second task for Spectrum emerged.
<p> 
During their conversations with Spectrum, the POTW engineers brought up another issue that had concerned them. Over time, Spectrum had also been cited for discharging total suspended solids (TSS) in excess of their permit limits. Not true, Spectrum contended. Then why, the POTW engineers asked, did the POTW so often have to clear out 
settled solids from their own settling basin? 
<p>
ERM was asked to investigate. The plant team from Spectrum discovered that settled solids from Spectrum's flocculation basin and rapid flow sand filtersused to clean incoming Okapokee River water for use in the 
plantswere periodically being discharged into 
the plant's wastewater effluent, carrying heavy loads of TSS.
<p>
The team came up with an economical solution: segregate the floc basin sludge and sand 
filter backwash flows 
from the dyehouse effluent, and route the segregated flow to a million-gallon alum sludge settling basin instead of discharging it 
to the POTW. After settling, the water carrying the solids could be recycled to the water plant instead 
of being discharged into the effluent sewer.
That solution resulted in a cessation of citations and annual savings in sewer charges of some $30,000effectively amortizing the construction and engineering costs of the basin within five years.
<p>
Meanwhile, the POTW agreed to the non-traditional approach suggested by ERM. Within 18 months the project was completed. Cost of the extra engineering required to develop the calibrated predictive model of the carbonate species buffering action amounted to $12,000. Capital investment savings for construction of the 375,000-gallon  pH neutralization basincompared to the cost of the traditional 3 million-gallon basinwere  in the neighborhood of $1.78 million. 
<p>
Pickle and Fox's 
creativity and their willingness to buck tradition to meet their client's needs saved Spectrum's capital improvement budget 
nearly $2 million, and 
their operating engineers 
a lot of headaches and
frustration.
<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

<A NAME="reg"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=10><KBD>Regulatory Update</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B> ISO 14001 Environmental Management System Standard to Become Final</B>
<P>
<IMG SRC="/gif/flam.gif" ALIGN=LEFT> The International Organization for Standardization 
(ISO) is expected to finalize the draft ISO 14001 standard for Environmental Management Systems (EMS) early this summer. ISO 14001 is one of a series of voluntary environmental standards.
<p>
It is the only standard in the ISO 14000 series 
for which ISO certification can be achieved. 
<p>
The other ISO 14000 standards are considered 
to be guidance documents for implementing and maintaining environmental performance. They can be used to enhance implementation of an organizations EMS. They cover environmental auditing, environmental performance evaluation, 
eco-labeling, life cycle assessment and the 
environmental aspects of product standards. They are in various stages of development. 
<p>
Why be interested? The decision for any organization to seek ISO certification or self-declaration will ultimately be unique to that entity. Motives for adoption might include enhancing environmental performance and compliance, increasing market share/competitive advantage and/or improving public image. When the standard becomes final, how these factors and others can affect your decision to adopt the standard should become clear.
<p> 
The draft ISO 14001 standard emphasizes the establishment and maintenance of an 
EMS in order to improve protection of human 
welfare and the environment. The standard 
contains five elements for a management system. These elements address environmental policy, planning, implementation and operation, checking and corrective action, and management review. 
<p> 
The standard does 
not prescribe performance expectations of an organization. For example, it does not specify the 
number of years an EMS annual audit must be 
conducted. Rather, the organization must specify the performance requirements based upon the goals of the organization and the environmental aspects and impacts associated with its activities, products, and services.
For more information on ISO 14001, contact Deborah Tansey at ERM,
610-524-3500.
<p>
<center> <font size=2>Copyright&copy; 1996 ERM</font><br>
<img SRC="/gif/logo_erm.gif"><br>

