<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>

ERM NAMES LAWRENCE B. CAHILL PRINCIPAL<P>

</H3>


EXTON, Pa. -- October 30, 1996 -- Lawrence B. Cahill has been named
a principal by Environmental Resources Management (ERM), an international
environmental, health and safety consulting firm.  Cahill, a senior program
director in ERM's Management Consulting Group located in Exton, is an
internationally recognized environmental auditing expert.  <p>
"Larry Cahill has more than 20 years of environmental experience with
industry, mainly working for numerous <I>Fortune 500</I> companies," remarks Kent
E. Patterson, ERM president.  "He has developed, evaluated and certified
environmental, health and safety (EH&S) auditing programs, conducted
hundreds of audits, and trained literally thousands of people worldwide in
auditing skills."  <p>
Cahill also has prepared an auditor's opinion letter for major companies
that formally certifies the effectiveness of their EH&S audit programs and
appears in their annual environmental reports.  <p>
Since 1983, he has taught an Environmental Audits course for the
Government Institutes (GI), in Rockville, Md., a publisher and continuing
education organization specializing in EH&S concerns, and has been designated a
<I>"Distinguished Instructor"</I> by GI.  Cahill has edited and authored a number of
books in his area of expertise.  His latest book, <I>Environmental Audits - 7th
Edition</I>, which was edited for and published by the Government Institutes in
March 1996, provides a comprehensive overview of EH&S auditing, legal issues
and staff development.  
<p>
Recently, Cahill published an insightful, humorous article, entitled
<I>Environmental Audit Training in the Far East: A Wok on the Wild Side</I>, that
recounts his trip last year to conduct EH&S audit training for a major company in
Singapore and Japan.  He discusses cultural differences, such as his perception
that the Japanese do not appear to be as probing as U.S. auditors because it is not
considered proper in their culture.  <p>
Additionally, Cahill serves as co-chairperson of the Auditor Qualifications
Workgroup of the Environmental Auditing Roundtable, and he was a member of
the Standards Conformance Registration Advisory Group (SCRAG)
commissioned by the U.S. Technical Advisory Group to develop a
recommendation on the organization(s) that would meet the objectives for
company registrations and auditor certification under ISO 14000 in the United
States.  <p>
Cahill holds a B.S. in Mechanical Engineering from Northeastern
University, an M.S. in Environmental Health Engineering from Northwestern
University, and an M.B.A. in Public Management from the Wharton School of
the University of Pennsylvania.  Before joining ERM, he was a project engineer
with Exxon Research and Engineering where he audited plants in the United
States, Canada and Europe.  <p>

</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
