<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>

<!-- heading -->
ERM ADVANCES TO 25TH PLACE
IN ENR TOP 500 DESIGN FIRM RANKINGS

</H3>

<!-- text -->
EXTON, Pa. -- May 3, 1996 -- The Environmental Resources Management (ERM) Group advanced to 25th place among U.S. engineering firms in the Engineering News Record Top 500 Design Firms listing recently released for 1995, compared to 27th place in the previous year.  In the international design category, ERM continued in 23rd place for the 1995 ENR rankings.  
<p>	In the hazardous waste area, ERM ranked fourth among the top 20 firms for 1995.  According to ENR, billings remained flat at $3.3-billion for the top 20 players in the hazardous waste field.  For the top 500 firms, though, 1995 hazardous waste billings dropped to $5.3-billion from $5.45-billion in 1994.  The rankings are based on total billings.  
<p>	Industry observers attributed last year's decline to cuts in federal agency cleanup contracting and enforcement budgets, along with a slowdown in enacting environmental legislation.  "Despite the overall business dropoff among hazardous waste firms, ERM's revenues increased to $283-million for the fiscal year ending March 31, 1996, compared to $275-million for the previous year," according to Jack C. Newell, an ERM principal.  
<p>	"ERM continues to grow worldwide," said Newell.  "During 1995, we opened eight new offices in North America and overseas to meet the expanding global needs of our industrial client base."

</BLOCKQUOTE>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<H6>
ERM Group is a global consulting organization of 2,400 environmental, health and safety specialists at more than 90 locations in 24 countries.  The firm is one of the world's largest providers of environmental consulting and engineering services to industry, and offers air quality, wastewater, hazardous and solid waste management; site assessment and remediation; human health and ecological risk assessment; process safety; management consulting; information management; analytical laboratory services and turnkey construction.
</H6>
