</KBD>
</TD><TD>
<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>

EMERGING ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES CONFRONTING
INDUSTRY IN LATIN AMERICA AIRED <P>

</H3>

MIAMI  -- October 25, 1996 -- Increasing trade and foreign investment in
Latin America mean that companies doing business there will need to meet
developing local environmental regulations and challenges, according to experts
on Latin America.  Businessmen attending an all-day conference here learned
from the experts what the current environmental issues are in Latin America. 
<P>
Environmental Resources Management (ERM), a global environmental,
health and safety consulting firm, presented the conference, an international
seminar involving all its offices in one region of the world.  <P>
"The major Latin American countries have an environmental regulatory
framework in place, but the political will to enforce the regulations has not
matured," remarked Arnon E. Garonzik, managing director of ERM-Latin
America in Exton, Pa.  <P>
According to Paul Gruber, principal of ERM in Tampa, Florida, "The
main driving force in environmental management in Latin America is the concern
of multinational companies to maintain a high level of environmental integrity." 
Other speakers described the environmental regulatory picture in different Latin
American countries.  <P>
Brazil has had national environmental legislation since 1981 which
requires environmental licensing of potential pollution sources and environmental
impact assessments, according to Eugenio Singer, principal of SEMCO-ERM do
Brasil Ltda. in Sao Paulo, Brazil.  He pointed out, "State governments have
historically played a much larger role in environmental protection than the federal government, and trends for new federal standards and
regulations can be anticipated by new regulations in the states of Sao Paulo, Rio
de Janeiro and Minas Gerais.       <P>
In Chile, a new copper and gold rush are driving the economy.  The
environmental framework is characterized by a multiplicity of environmental
agencies, obsolete laws and regulations, an increasing level of penalties and the
principle that the polluter must pay, explained Jorge A. David, executive director
of ERM-Chile S.A. in Santiago, Chile, formed earlier this year.  <P>
David noted that proposed legislation, which would update Chile's
environmental laws and regulations, has been postponed four times and was
rejected in October 1996.  He described the results of the Environmental
Pollution Prevention Program (EP3) in Chile, which he managed for U.S. AID
to promote industrial eco-efficiency, waste minimization and source reduction. 
Pedro J. Panzardi, principal of Panzardi-ERM, Inc. in San Juan, Puerto
Rico, the newest ERM location, talked about the impact of the repeal of Section
936 of the U.S. tax code by the U.S. Congress.  Section 936 provided a tax
exemption to U.S. companies operating in Puerto Rico since 1976.  "We expect
new tax incentives to be proposed by the U.S. Congress depending on the
outcome of the U.S. presidential election.  Additionally, many 936 corporations
will continue to operate in Puerto Rico for at least 10 years and longer.  They all
will continue to build environmental infrastructure and need environmental
services," he said.  <p>
In Bolivia, new environmental regulations were issued in 1995 that
establish discharge limits for air and water as well as guidelines for solid
waste/dangerous substances management.  The regulations also define who is the
appropriate environmental authority and the requirements for new and existing
operations.
<P>
"Bolivia now has a clear environmental regulatory framework and a high
potential for growth, " said Carlos Meave, managing director of Ecologia y
Empresa S.R.L., an environmental consultant in La Paz, Bolivia.  <BR>
In Venezuela, enforcement of environmental laws has been relatively lax
in the past, but is strengthening.  The criminal courts can, however, impose
fines, arrest and sentence members of company management responsible for
environmental damage.  This means, cautioned Elisabeth E. Eljuri, senior
associate with Baker & McKenzie, an international law firm with offices in
Caracas, Venezuela, that companies operating in Venezuela should obtain the
required environmental authorizations and take no risks.  <p>
"It's clear from today's conference," added Garonzik, "that ERM has
significant resources within Latin America to handle many different types of
solutions to environmental problems without significant importation of skills
from outside the region."  He added, "ERM will continue to build on its
capabilities in Latin America to serve both our multinational and local clients with
operations in the region.  The latest addition of Panzardi-ERM to our organization
is an example of this growth."
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
<center>
<a href="/map/buttonbar.map">
<IMG SRC="/gif/button_bar.gif" WIDTH=484 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 ISMAP USEMAP="#buttonbar"></a>
</center>
