<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>

ENVIRONMENTAL ISSUES IN LATIN AMERICA DISCUSSED BY THE EXPERTS<P>
<I>Upcoming conference to cover hot environmental topics affecting industry in Latin America</I>
</H3>

MIAMI -- September 19, 1996 -- Current environmental issues affecting private industry in Latin America will be discussed at an all-day conference presented by Environmental Resources Management (ERM) on October 25 in Miami.  ERM is an international environmental, health and safety consulting firm.<p>

The conference offers business executives and environmental, health and safety (EHS) professionals who are contemplating or conducting trade and investment in Latin America the opportunity to learn what the most critical environmental issues are, according to Arnon E. Garonzik, managing director of ERM-Latin America.<p>

Topics to be covered include waste management and remediation, regulatory issues, environmental regulatory program development and hemispheric free trade.<p>

"Companies interested in developing or maintaining businesses in Latin America need to meet the local environmental challenges and comply with regulations if they wish to succeed in that market," says Paul Gruber, president of ERM-South, an ERM member with offices in Tampa, Miami and throughout Florida.<p>

Garonzik notes, "The outlook for direct foreign investment and improved trade between North America and Latin America has returned to a new level of optimism.  We think that as the local Latin American economies grow, they will generate a new middle class that will become a dynamic force in improving quality of life issues -- especially the environment." As a result, continues Garonzik, "meeting environmental challenges and regulations will become essential to business growth."<p>

Business executives attending the conference will hear experts from ERM's Latin American companies in Brazil, Chile, Mexico and Puerto Rico as well as ERM offices in Florida.  Joining ERM and offering a unique perspective on Latin
American trade will be the international law firm of Greenberg Traurig of 
Miami.  Other speakers include Jim Bacchus, former U.S. Congressman for central
Florida; Ambler H. Moss, former Ambassador to Panama; and Beatriz Merino, 
Congresswoman of the Republic of Peru.<p>

Co-sponsoring the conference with ERM is the Florida Manufacturing and Chemical
Council and Florida International University's Hemispheric Center on 
Environmental Technology.<p>

The October 25 conference on <i><b>Hot environmental Topics Affecting Private
Industry in Latin America"</b></i> will be held at the Miami Airport Hilton
Towers.  Registration is $150 per person.  For more information, contact Pam
Lepley at ERM at (610) 524-3522 or Mercedes Estrada at (813) 622-8727.<p>

ERM is a global consulting organization of 2,400 environmental, health and safety specialists at 99 locations in 24 countries.  The firm is one of the world's largest providers of environmental consulting and engineering services to industry, and offers air quality, wastewater, hazardous and solid waste management;  site assessment and remediation; human health and ecological risk assessment; process safety; management consulting; information management; analytical laboratory services and turnkey construction.<p>
