<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>

NEW CONCEPT IN CHEMICAL OUTSOURCING ADDS INNOVATIVE ENVIRONMENTAL COMPONENT<P>
<I>SCMG is a unique chemical procurement <BR>
and environmental management<BR>
service that cuts costs.</I>
</H3>


ATLANTA -- November 1, 1996 -- The Strategic Chemical
Management Group (SCMG) has been formed to provide an innovative
chemical sourcing and management service, with an environmental
management component.  SCMG is a joint venture of two companies,
Environmental Resources Management (ERM), a global environmental, health
and safety consulting firm, and EcoLink, a technology firm focusing on
alternatives for ozone-depleting substances.  SCMG has contracts with three
electric utilities.  <p>
Key benefits of the strategic sourcing service include enhanced
utilization of client personnel resources, reduced environmental liability,
significant cost savings on chemical purchases and a reduction in associated
overhead costs.  <p>
"By combining strategic environmental management with chemical
procurement, this approach takes chemical sourcing through its natural
evolution," says Paul H. Woodruff, ERM Group president and chief executive
officer.  "SCMG has developed a holistic program that views the procurement
function as a true source reduction opportunity that results in reduced chemical
emissions to the environment."  <p>
The customer outsources part or all of its chemical procurement needs
to SCMG.  SCMG then works closely with the customer to ensure timely
delivery of the best possible, environmentally preferred chemical products at
the most economical prices.  Additionally, the customer will realize savings in
staffing, material handling and inventory management, according to Anita
Neidert, SCMG cofounder and a principal in ERM's Atlanta office.  <p>
"Working as an integrated team, SCMG, the customer and suppliers
share responsibility for successful implementation of activities, such as OSHA
training, SARA reporting and waste disposal," comments Neidert.  <p>
Bill Green, SCMG cofounder, adds,  "Program success is measured
not only by cost savings, but also by successful product implementation,
environmental compliance and ultimately, customer satisfaction."  <p>
Neidert explains, "From an environmental, health and safety (EHS)
perspective, a strategic sourcing alliance will enhance the primary partner's
understanding of the chemical procurement process and its integration into
EHS management."  She adds that one of the important features of SCMG is
that the chemical user is no longer solely responsible for managing the EHS
ramifications of the purchased chemicals.  <p>
Neidert and Green believe that the strategic sourcing alliance form of
chemical management is particularly appropriate for companies grappling with
the management of hazardous chemicals.  "A well-managed strategic sourcing
program is the ultimate source reduction/pollution prevention effort which
yields verifiable cost savings," emphasize both SCMG founders.  

<p>


SCMG is working with two electric utilities, Southern California
Edison Co. and Florida Power Corp.  As a result of engaging SCMG to
manage more than 2,000 different chemicals, S. California Edison has been
able to reduce its number of chemical vendors from several hundred to eight
and expects to save about 10 percent on its chemical costs during the first year
of implementation.  Additionally, notes Neidert, the company has just signed a
contract with Public Service Electric and Gas Co. of New Jersey.  SCMG
expects to expand its work with the utility industry and plans to offer its
services to other chemical users.  <p>
For more information about SCMG, contact Anita Neidert at ERM, 300
Chastain Center Blvd, Suite 375, Kennesaw, GA 30144, or phone (770) 590
8383 or fax (770) 590-9164.  <p>

</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
