<HEAD>
<TITLE>U.S. Seminars</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Martin Schamis,  8-Nov-1996 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#3300CC" VLINK="#003B32" ALINK="#FFFFFF">


<h2>U.S. Seminars</h2>

<P>
<b>Accidental Release 112 (r)</b> - Under Title III of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990, both OSHA and EPA must regulate facilities that handle extremely hazardous substances.  OSHA is accomplishing this activity through its Process Safety Management (PSM) program, while EPA has just released its new regulations addressing Risk Management Programs (RMPs).  ERM will provide attendees with the information needed to determine their likelihood of having to comply with the RMP and then the tasks necessary to comply with the OSHA and EPA programs, including the preparation of the off-site consequence analysis.<p> 
<center>
<TABLE WIDTH=400 BORDER=0>
<TR><TD>
<b>Location</b>
</TD><TD>
<b>Date</b>
</TD><TD>
<b>Speakers</b>
</TD></TR>


<TR><TD>
Pittsburgh, PA
</TD><TD>
12/4/96
</TD><TD>
Peter Kroll<br>
Katie Klaber
</TD></TR>


<TR><TD>
Indianapolis, IN
</TD><TD>
11/12/96
</TD><TD>
Dave Jordan<br>
Peter Charrington
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<p>
</CENTER>

<b>Voluntary Protection Program (VPP)</b> - In today's business world, there has been a dramatic increase in the amount of emphasis being placed on health and safety issues.  This is due, in part, to the result of greater awareness and initiative on the part of the business leaders.  It should be noticed that corporate culture is changing from compliance driven to best business practices, such asVPP.  The presentation will provide you with and overview of the VPP and how to implement this program into your business practice.

<p>

<center>
<TABLE WIDTH=400 BORDER=0>
<TR><TD>
<b>Location</b>
</TD><TD>
<b>Date</b>
</TD><TD>
<b>Speakers</b>
</TD></TR>


<TR><TD>
Saddle Brook, NJ
</TD><TD>
12/5/96
</TD><TD>
Jim Testo<br>
Marla Cochran
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
