<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Asia/Pacific Operations</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Martin Schamis, 10-Sep-1996 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H2>Asia/Pacific Operations</H2>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/jpeg/asia1.jpg"></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE="+3">T</FONT>he breathtaking rate of economic growth in much of Asia and the environmental sophistication of mature markets such as Australia are creating tremendous opportunities for ERM to serve its clients. Revenues from the region rose briskly during the 1996 fiscal year, up 25 percent from the previous year.  Over the next three years, ERM expects revenues from Asia/Pacific to at least double.<P>

During the year, ERM added five offices in Asia and Australia and increased the total number of employees to more than 200. Today ERM is the most geographically diverse consulting group in the area, with offices in Hong Kong, Malaysia, Thailand, Singapore, Sri Lanka and Taiwan, two each in India and China, and six in Australia. <P>

ERM's services in Asia/Pacific also expanded during the year. Established consulting, engineering and project planning expertise was augmented in a number of the offices by new capabilities and products such as the company's Environmental Quality Manager (EQM) software, consulting on corporate environmental management systems that meet ISO 14000 standards, and specialized disciplines including acoustics, risk assessment and health and safety programs.<P>

In the Asia/Pacific region, ERM's strategy is to identify local requirements of major companies whom ERM already serves as a consultant elsewhere in the world, thereby "cross-selling" services to these established clients wherever they may operate. Investment  in information technology to strengthen collaboration and internal communication and to create new products for clients is another major component of ERM's strategy here. <P>
<BR>
<B><KBD>Asian Offices Expand</KBD></B><P>
ERM's extensive Asian network added offices in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia; Bangkok, Thailand; Singapore; and Madras, India, during the year.  Furthermore, the Hong Kong, China and Taiwan offices have established formal links to jointly develop and staff  business opportunities in the burgeoning Chinese market.<P>

Major new projects spanned a wide range, illustrating the breadth of services available from ERM in Asia.  The International Policy Services unit of ERM, for example, was commissioned by the Asian Development Bank and the United Nations to produce the 1995 edition of <I>State of the Environment for Asia and the Pacific.</I> It is a primary source of environmental information for the region and was used at a ministerial conference held in November 1995. Hong Kong Electric hired ERM's Hong Kong office to recommend a site for a proposed new 6000MW power station.<P>

Work undertaken in Hong Kong also included a study of marine habitats and commercial fishing operations designed to improve the management of fisheries resources, and a U.S. $1 million waste reduction study.  This study, probably the most comprehensive and detailed of its kind in the world, will form the basis of Hong Kong's waste management strategy well into the 21st century. <P>
<BR>
<B><KBD> Chinese Markets Grow</KBD></B><P>
In the People's Republic of China, ERM performed several substantial assignments for projects funded by multinational industry and foreign aid agencies: studying water quality regulations in Qingdao Municipality; analyzing market mechanisms for the control of air pollution in Jinan, Shangdong Province; and conducting training on audits and environmental management systems for the Ministry of Metallurgical Industry in Beijing and Shanghai.  For a major U.K. power company, ERM reviewed regulations and enforcement in China's power sector.  In China, international companies are far more likely to be cited for environmental liabilities than local enterprises, so ERM also published a guide called <I>Pollution Control in the People's Republic of China: Regulations and Reality.</I>  It discusses major environmental laws and how to navigate China's environmental protection bureaucracy.<P>

The third player in ERM's "greater China" triumvirate is ERM's office in Taiwan, which was founded six years ago.  Gross revenue during the 1996 fiscal year jumped 95 percent over the prior period, due primarily to two large engineering projects.  The first was to design, install and commission a waste-water treatment plant being constructed in Shanghai by a multinational building products company. The second was the remediation of a site contaminated by heavy metals in northern Taiwan for which ERM performed the site  investigation, feasibility study and remediation in only four months.
<P>
ERM's office in New Delhi, India, jumped from two to twelve employees during the year, and a new branch office was opened in Madras.  The New Delhi office worked on a plan to strengthen environmental performance at operating plants for the electricity board of the State of Maharashtra, which 
has a population of 283 million.  The company also participated in a solid waste management study for the Madras Metro-politan Development Authority, and conducted a number of environmental audits for corporate clients.
<P>
<CENTER><A HREF="letter_from_pres.html">[Previous]</A><A HREF="index.html">[Table of Contents]</A><A HREF="australia.html">[Next]</A></CENTER>

