<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Operations</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Martin Schamis,  2-Aug-1996 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H2>European Operations</H2>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/jpeg/europe1.jpg"></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE="+3">E</FONT>RM's consultancies in Europe work with clients from virtually every industrial category, international donor agencies and all levels of government on highly diverse assignments.  The European practice is founded on a broad range of environmental and risk-related services.  In addition, ERM is helping a number of large global corporations put in place environmental management systems that will enable them to participate in the voluntary international standards of ISO 14000 or Europe's Eco
Management and Audit Scheme (EMAS). <P>
Despite the maturing market in Europe, revenues from ERM operations have increased by 11 percent in the 1996 fiscal year over the previous year.<P>
ERM's network in Europe totals 18 offices, including one opened in Stuttgart, Germany, in early 1996 to strengthen the company's presence in that highly industrialized region.  There are four offices in the U.K., two each in Italy and Germany, and one each in Belgium, France, Hungary, the Netherlands, Poland, Portugal and Spain. Together they employ more than 280 people.<P>
<BR>
<B><KBD> Serving Multinationals</KBD></B><P>
The extensive European organization enables ERM to fulfill its 
commitment to serve its multinational clients wherever they 
operate.  The strength of ERM's interdependent network was demonstrated when the General Electric Company chose ERM in the U.K. for a global Master Services Agreement for all regions outside the U.S.  Similarly, a major European multinational packaging company commissioned ERM to assist with a two-year environmental health and safety compliance audit program for some 140 sites in Europe and North America.  ERM is able to provide a single point of contact to manage these multi-country assignments, which clients find very effective. <P>
ERM offices frequently carry out projects jointly.  In Mauritius, for example, professionals from the U.K. and the U.S. are developing, with World Bank funding, the island's first sanitary landfill.  Offices in India and Germany are working together on a large-scale environmental impact assessment for an automotive plant in Tamil Nadu, India.  The Spanish and U.K. offices collaborated on audits of industrial plants and gas exploration wells for two clients.  And ERM offices in France and Germany offered a joint workshop on environmental training issues in Alsace for TRW, the global automotive parts manufacturer.<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
