<HEAD>
<TITLE>North American Operations</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Martin Schamis,  2-Aug-1996 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H2>North American Operations</H2>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/jpeg/northam1.jpg"></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE="+3">E</FONT>
RM's operations in North America grew market share during fiscal year 1996, in spite of a small decrease in gross revenues, by profiting from accelerating demand in Mexico and a larger share of the relatively mature market in the U.S. and Canada.  The ranking of all U.S. consulting engineering firms by revenue published by <I>Engineering News-Record (ENR)</I> showed ERM moving from 27th to 25th place for 1995.  ERM's North American offices achieved this by focusing on serving the regulated community &#139; primarily businesses and certain federal agencies &#139; and offering a full range of high quality environmental services. <P>
During fiscal year 1996, ERM added North American offices in Bakersfield, California; Tallahassee, Florida; Davenport, Iowa; Baltimore, Maryland; Rochester, New York; and Monterrey, Mexico. By year end, there were two offices in Mexico, one in Canada and 62 in the U.S.<P>
<BR>
 <B><KBD> Growth in Mexico</KBD></B><P>
Many multinational corporations already served by ERM elsewhere increased their investments in Mexico following the peso devaluation in December 1994.  This pushed the growth rate for ERM's revenues in Mexico into double digits.  By the end of fiscal year 1996, ERM had a four-person office in Monterrey, the country's second largest industrial region, and an office in Mexico City with twelve employees. ERM also serves clients in Mexico from its offices in the U.S., particularly Texas.<P>
The bulk of ERM's current assignments in Mexico are site assessments and permit applications for new facilities being developed by multinationals and large local businesses.  During the 1996 fiscal year, ERM prepared the strategic environmental management plan, environmental impact assessment and risk studies for a new polyethylene terephthalate (PET) plastic plant, the first of five being built in Altamira by a multinational petrochemical company.  The permits were obtained in a record 35 days after applying.  ERM's offices in Mexico and London jointly conducted a market survey for hazardous waste generation in the central area of Mexico for a multinational waste management company, as part of justification for constructing a treatment plant.  The project is moving forward, and ERM in Mexico is preparing the environmental impact statement and risk assessments for the new facility.<P>
The market for environmental services in Mexico is expected to expand much faster than the U.S. market over the next decade.  As it does, ERM expects to add more offices and services in Mexico to meet the needs of industry. <P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
