<HEAD>
<TITLE>South American Operations</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Martin Schamis,  2-Aug-1996 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"> 
<H2>South American Operations</H2>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/jpeg/southam.jpg"></CENTER> 
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE="+3">T</FONT> he market for environmental services in South America has been growing by more than eight percent a year.  ERM is capitalizing on this growth through its local offices which understand the customs and economies of their countries and can apply this knowledge for multinational corporate clients. <P>
ERM has been expanding its environmental capabilities in South America to bring new services that are difficult to obtain in the region.  Typically, South American environmental consultants offer environmental impact assessments (EIAs), but not the contaminated site remediation, corrective action
or environmental management system services that ERM provides. <P>
ERM's strategy resulted in revenue growth of 21 percent in South America during the 1996 fiscal year, accompanied by a healthy increase in profitability. The firm expects revenues to increase by 30 percent in the 1997 fiscal year with the startup of a new office in Chile, and 20 percent annual revenue growth thereafter as individual national economies improve and international trade increases.<P>
<BR>
<B><KBD> Good Growth Prospects </KBD></B><P>
ERM began operating in Brazil in 1993 when it acquired an interest in a S&atilde;o Paulo environmental consulting firm that was renamed SEMCO-ERM do Brasil Ltda. ERM's office in Chile was launched at the beginning of 1996 because that country has a stable economy, healthy industrial growth and strong potential for expanding ERM's environmental services throughout Spanish-speaking South America.  ERM also has registered branch offices in Argentina, Ecuador and Peru and has worked recently in every major South American country except Paraguay.  Many of ERM's Brazilian technical staff of environmental engineers, biologists, geologists and geographers are trilingual, speaking Portuguese, Spanish and English.  <P>
ERM has completed projects in South America for large industrial concerns, national governments, and international donor agencies.  Significant projects during the past year involved environmental due diligence and transaction-related studies, including one for the acquisition of South America's largest paint manufacturer by a British company.  This project required ERM to assess seven sites in 25 days in four countries &#139; Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay and Bolivia.  Another major multinational brewery retained ERM to conduct, together with the company's audit team, due diligence studies of more than 15 facilities throughout Brazil and Argentina.  Altogether,  ERM has conducted more than 100 audits and due diligence assignments  throughout South America.<P>
<BR>
<B><KBD> Remediation Services </KBD></B><P>
Contaminated site investigation and remediation are ERM's newest services in South America and the ones with the greatest growth potential. ERM's office in Brazil was retained to conduct a site investigation and decontamination of a former asbestos manufacturing plant in S&atilde;o Paulo.  ERM's asbestos abatement plan allowed a global retailer to proceed with construction of a major new store in record time.  <P>
ERM also developed a complete decontamination program for a battery manufacturing facility in Brazil.  In the Amazon jungle region of Ecuador, a multinational petroleum exploration and development company retained ERM to act as its third-party arbitrator for any dispute that may arise with the Ecuadorian Ministry of Energy & Mines regarding site cleanups.  <P>
EIAs are a basic environmental service provided by ERM, which began work at the beginning of 1996 on an EIA for an oil and gas project in Peru.  This EIA was conducted for another multinational petroleum company.  In Brazil, ERM is assessing leaking underground storage tanks at gas stations for the same company.<P>
In the area of training in environmental management and pollution control, ERM conducted a $450,000 eight
day course for Petrobras, the state-owned oil company in Brazil.  The training included all areas of environmental management &#139; EIAs, risk management, environmental economics, emergency planning, international standards, clean technologies and waste treatment.<P>
<BR>
<B><KBD> EMS Awards </KBD></B><P>
During the 1996 fiscal year, ERM participated with <I>Gazeta Mercantil</I>, the major Brazilian financial newspaper, in a special series of articles on EMS. The articles appeared in eight weekly newspaper supplements devoted to environmental management systems.  Businesses were asked to complete a questionnaire about their EMS.  ERM evaluated the responses and selected the top 25 candidates for awards given by the newspaper.  <P>
In Chile, ERM is helping to strengthen the national environmental ministry under a contract from the British Overseas Development Administration, and is managing the Environmental Pollution Prevention Program (EP3) funded by the U.S. Agency for International Development to promote waste minimization and source reduction.  <BR>
<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
