<HTML>

<HEAD>
        <TITLE>ERM Foundation Projects</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Martin Schamis, 23-Aug-1996 -->

</HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff" LINK="#005b52" VLINK="#0d50a2" ALINK="#ffffff" BACKGROUND="/gif/ermbg5.gif">

<P>

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/jpeg/foundation.jpg" BORDER="0" HEIGHT="167" WIDTH="500" ALIGN=bottom> 
</CENTER>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE=+2>

<B>ERM Foundation Projects</B> 
<BR>
The following are summaries of projects ERM Foundation has funded and provided in-kind volunteer support.
</FONT>

<p>
<B>Water for People</B>
<p>
Support was requested for programs in six Latin American countries (Mexico, Guatemala, Honduras, Nicaragua, Ecuador and Bolivia) designed to obtain and sustain drinking water and sanitation services for local communities.  There was an opportunity for ERM employee participation through the offering of technical services connected with these and similar projects.  WFP leveraged ERM contributions by using them to obtain other donations to assist in these projects.  ERM's Mexican offices were used to help facilitate ERM staff participation.  For more information contact Project Director John McGlennon <A HREF="/alert/locate/statelist.html#Massachusetts">(ERM, Boston, MA)</A> at 617-742-8228.
<p>
<B>Rotary International for Las Animas (Mexico) Clean Water Project </B>
<p>
Las Animas, a town of approximately 6,000 people located 30 miles from Mexico City, currently obtains its drinking water from two nearby wells that are contaminated and have high bacterial counts.  In addition, the current system is only capable of providing the water to half the town on alternative days.  To address these problems, this project includes the design, procurement, installation, start-up and O & M training for a water chlorination system for the town.  The system will be designed to make maximum use of existing water system infrastructure such as existing water storage tanks (2), the existing water collection system and the existing water distribution system.  ERM and FUNDEA have completed a feasibility study  on this new system.  Currently, requested funding will go toward implementation, start-up and O&M training.  Rotary International will match the gift.  The Project Manager is Brian Flynn, <A HREF="/alert/locate/statelist.html#Colorado">(ERM, Denver, CO)</A> at 303-741-5050.
<p>
<B> National Forest Foundation Youth Camps </B>
<p>
National Forest Camps are eight week programs held at national forests, including Pike National Forest (CO), George Washington National Forest (VA),and Gifford Pinchot National Forest (WA).  During the camps, inner city young people ages 15-19, who come from unsupportive environments, work and learn practical skills related to conserving and sustaining natural resources.  They are fully supervised and counseled and receive minimum wages for their efforts.  They construct shelters, fences, trails and stone walls.  They clear trails and streams.  As a result of this program, several inner city youth are now enrolled on scholarships studying environmental fields and others who are still in high school, plan to enroll.  This program has a high potential to reshape lives.  For more information contact Project Manager Judy Hushon <A HREF="/alert/locate/statelist.html#Virginia">(ERM, McLean, VA)</A> at 703-734-9327.
<p>
<B> National Forest Foundation Urban Tree House </B>
<p>
Urban Tree Houses are wooden, porch-like decks located in a park in disadvantaged neighborhoods.  Local teachers and other offer activities on the importance of natural resources to elementary aged children at the Tree House.  The first Urban Tree House was built last year in Atlanta, GA.  Others are being added in Washington, D.C., Portland, OR, Salt Lake City, UT, Baton Rouge, LA and in Nashville and Franklin, TN.  The Project Manager is Glenn Taylor <A HREF="/alert/locate/statelist.html#Georgia">(ERM, Atlanta, GA)</A> at 770-590-8393.
<p>
<B> The Einstein Project, Brown County, Wisconsin </B>
<p>
This project requested support to help develop education materials and training for teachers in the Brown County area.  The teachers, in turn, will incorporate a hands-on educational program in the sciences at their respective schools.  We recommended that the materials developed for this program be transferred to other school systems within the state and throughout the United States.  Two educational programs proposed will fit well into the Foundation's objectivesRocks & Minerals and Water & Land.    The Project Manager is Jim Polich <A HREF="/alert/locate/statelist.html#Illinois">(ERM, Chicago, IL)</A> at 708-940-7200.
<p>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>
