<HTML>
<TITLE> PlantExec, March 1996</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Martin Schamis, 30-Jul-1996 -->
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#005B52" VLINK="#0D50A2" ALINK="#FFFFFF">

<BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/gif/plant.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="2">AN UPDATE FOR PLANT ENVIRONMENTAL EXECUTIVES</FONT>
<BR>
March 1996
</CENTER>

<HR> 


<UL>
<H2>Contents</H2>
<UL>
     <A HREF="mar96.html#canned"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>Not Exactly a Canned Solution</KBD></FONT></A>
     <P>
     <A HREF="mar96.html#reg"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>Regulatory Update</KBD></FONT></A>
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="canned">
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=20><KBD>NOT EXACTLY A<BR>
CANNED SOLUTION</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H4>
Keeping the quest for the perfect from driving out the good. </H4>

<FONT SIZE=+3>T</FONT>ypically, ERM works 
on behalf of industry, helping it comply with state or U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) rules and regulations. But when Greg Verret, a principal of ERM in St. Charles, Mo., was contacted by the Can Manufacturers' Institute (CMI) in Washington, D.C., in the fall of 
1992, he realized that the project in question would 
be a little different.
<p> 
<IMG SRC="/gif/blue.gif">
<br>
The assignment was twofold: (1) to work with CMI to find a way for the EPA to maintain its capture efficiency standards for 
surface coating lines, while (2) simultaneously getting the EPA's OK on a new, 
easier and less costly way 
for industry to comply with those standards. 		
<p>
While unusual, the assignment didn't put the regulators and the regulated into different camps. Both CMI and ERM had worked with the EPA before in situations where the goal had been to keep the quest for the perfect from driving out the good. If this was going to work, Verret knew, they would have to create a win-win situation. At issue was the phrase "capture efficiency" and how it could best be measured in the surface coating industries. There are many kinds of 
surface coating lines in U.S. industry, and all of them are subject to environmental 
regulation no matter where the finish is applieda final destination that includes virtually every kind of product from automobiles to office furnishings, appliances to cans.
<p>	
Every year, in fact, U.S. manufacturers produce 125 billion food and beverage cans. CMI represents the approximately 28 companies with 200 plants across the U.S. that make about 95 percent of those cans. To protect canned food and beverage products from interacting with the steel or aluminum 
of the cans themselves, cans receive either a solvent- or water-based coating, whichto make for even dispersalin some instances contains volatile organic compounds (VOCs) in excess of EPA-established standards, requiring the use of add-on 
controls. In addition, VOCs are often used to clean impression rollers on the line. Not all VOCs are toxic, but most contribute to the buildup of atmospheric ozone. Manufacturers, therefore, are required by the EPA to remove a significant percentage of the VOCs being released by these coating lines, and to calculate and report to the EPA the amount of VOCs being captured. 
<p>	
The method historically used to make that determination was called mass balance testing: Weigh the VOCs fed to the process; then, at the end of the process, weigh what's been captured by the 
control device. The difference between the two is fugitive emissionsescapees from the system. Typically, can manufacturers are required to keep 
fugitive emissions at around 10 to 15 percent, which means they strive for a capture efficiency ratio in excess of 85 percent.
<p>	
All well and good, except that the EPA was concerned about imprecision 
in mass balance testing (standard deviations from the mean wavered from 0.4% to 27.9%with an average of 10%) and the potential for upward bias in the results it generated (more than 40% 
of individual runs indicated capture efficiencies of more than 100%, a physical impossibility). By the mid-1980s, the EPA was working on an alternative measuring methodologytotal temporary enclosure (TTE) testing. Here, for as long as a test took, an airtight enclosure would be built around a surface coating station, different technology would be used, and greater accuracy would be achieved. In 1988, the EPA issued guidance for TTE testing for magnetic tape coatingand in 1990, as a result of the Chicago area's failure to achieve national air quality standards for ozone, the EPA's implementation plan there included TTE guidance.
	<p>
Industry was unhappy. So were some state agencies. And so were some EPA regional offices. Total temporary enclosures could do the job, but the costs would be prohibitive. These enclosures, which are a little larger than the average Winnebago, had to be custom-designed, installed, operated and then dismantled. That took time. And necessitated shutting down the production line. 
<p>
In some cases, adjacent lines would have to be shut down as well. The TTE test was two hours longer than the old mass balance method and required more equipment, like flame ionization analyzers. CMI, on behalf of its members, began searching for some way around, or between, the horns of the capture-efficiency dilemma. 
<p>	
The EPA, meanwhile, announced it would undertake a year-long study to review possible alternative capture efficiency test methods. It postponed the deadlines for TTE compliance certification. That was when CMI called ERM. Could the environmental consulting firm find a way to make mass balance testing more accurate, run a field study to demonstrate it, and then convince the EPA to change its regulations to accommodate the new methodology?
<p>	
Verret said yes. ERM 
had done similar work in 
the past. "So, basically, we had a methodology in place," he says. "All we had to do was refine itfind a combination of ways to reduce measurement errors." The old mass balance method cost about $5,800 per test series. The TTE method, ERM calculated, could cost up to $80,000. That, CMI 
calculated, amounted to 
$17 million extra for a single round of tests for the canning industry alone. 
<p>
Verret, along with ERM team members Michael Price, senior engineer, and Michael Woodbury, senior project scientist, got to work. By February 1993, they had 
a prototype of what would become known as enhanced mass balance testing in place at a CMI member 
company in Philadelphia. They used highly accurate, certified, instantaneous-measurement scales to 
measure the starting and ending weights of coating in the feed drums and draw buckets, as well as the before and after weights of the roll solvent reservoir buckets; they measured total liquid-phase VOC consumption by analyzing individual samples from the coating and roll wash solvent feed reservoirs at the start and end of each run; and they used a flame ionization analyzer to measure background VOCs captured by the coater hoods and the curing oven. 	
<p>	
All in all, they found more than half a dozen 
different ways to make the mass balance method reliable. It cost nearly twice as much as the old method ($10,200 per three-run test series), but was still about eight times less than the TTE method. By October 1993, ERM and CMI had their report ready for review by the EPA. The project was ready to move out of the field study phase and into the negotiation phase.
<p>	
Verret knew the process would be difficult. But it was what the job was all about. "I found it very challenging and a lot of fun to work 
on," he says, "because we'd come up with a potential answer and the EPA would ask for revisions and after more research, we'd come back with a better solution. It forced us to think on our feet. And eventually, they accepted the major thrust 
of our argument." Overall, he says, "we had good 
cooperation among EPA, CMI and ERM. The EPA was just as interested as we were in finding a good alternative to TTE."
<p>
In January 1995 the 
EPA issued its revised guidance for capture efficiency testing for surface coating lines. The revision did not include the ERM-developed protocol, 
but it did say manufacturers could use other testing methods than TTE as long as they met minimum 
standards of precisionwhat the EPA terms the Data Quality Objective and Lower Confidence Limit standards. The ERM-developed protocol meets those standards. And, says Verret, "We came up with some additional protocols to further enhance 
the enhanced mass balance method. This could be important from a cost-
effectiveness perspective, becausealthough what we developed with CMI and the EPA worksthese additional protocols cut down the length of individual test runs as well as the number of test runs required to get reliable results. And that translates to dollars." 

<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

<A NAME="reg"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=10><KBD>Regulatory Update</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Self-disclosure best policy, EPA says</B>
<P>

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT VSPACE=10 HSPACE=20 SRC="/gif/flam.gif">
<br>
<br>
<FONT SIZE="+3">T</FONT>he EPA has released in the form of non-binding guidance its final enforcement policy regarding disposition of voluntarily discovered and self-disclosed violations a guidance the agency is considering codifying as regulation. The policy, which went into effect January 22, reiterates the EPA's objections to the establishment of self-audit privileges.
<br clear=all>

The policy offers three benefits to self-disclosing companies:
<ul>
	<li>The EPA will not seek gravity-based penalties for self-disclosed violations discovered through an environmental audit or qualified environmental management system. Violations discovered through other means can receive a 75% reduction in gravity-based penalties.
<p>
	<li>The EPA will not recommend criminal penalties against companies that so self-disclose, provided there was no prevalent management philosophy or practice that concealed or condoned violations, and that no high-level company officials or managers were consciously involved in or willfully blind to the violations.
<p>	
	<li>The EPA will not request or use an audit report to initiate an investigation, although it may request such reports if it has independent reason to believe that a violation has occurred.
</ul>
<p>	
For a self-disclosing company to be eligible for these benefits it must meet a series of conditions, set forth here in highly abbreviated form.
<p>	
The violation must not be a repetition of the same or similar violation within the past three years, must not have caused harm or the threat of harm to humans or the environment, must not violate the terms of a court order or consent agreement, must be discovered voluntarily (that is, prior to receiving an inspection notice or information request or citizen suit notice) either through an environmental audit or other procedure reflecting due diligence; and must be disclosed in writing to the EPA within 10 days, and then certified as corrected (including any EPA-recommended remedial 
measures) within 60 days. Further, the company must agree in writing to take preventive measures, and must cooperate with the EPA. 
<p>	
For more detailed 
analysis of the policy, please 
contact Larry Cahill at 
(610) 524-3441.

<p>
<center> <font size=2>Copyright&copy; 1996 ERM</font><br>
