<HTML>
<TITLE> PlantExec, January 1996</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#005B52" VLINK="#0D50A2" ALINK="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/gif/plant.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="2">AN UPDATE FOR PLANT ENVIRONMENTAL EXECUTIVES</FONT>
<BR>
January 1996
</CENTER>

<HR> 


<UL>
<H2>Contents</H2>
<UL>
     <A HREF="jan96.html#iso1"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>ISO 14001:
Leading the Way</KBD></FONT></A>
     <P>
     <A HREF="jan96.html#tec"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>Technology Update</KBD></FONT></A>
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="iso1"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=20><KBD>ISO14001:<BR>
     LEADING THE WAY</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H4>
This company set out to improve the environment
one production team at a time.
</H4>

<FONT SIZE=+3>H</FONT>ow can a company cut costs, and improve its public image, while integrating environmental issues into its long-term planning at the earliest stage of the processwithout costly investments or operational interruptions? The Performance Materials Division 
of Schuller International, a leading manufacturer, found a way. By focusing on aggressive environmental management rather than just trying to keep in compliance, the company initiated a revolutionary 
environmental program possibly the first of its kindthat has begun 
a sweeping change in 
its operations.
<p>

<CENTER>
<TABLE CELLPADDING=5>
<TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="/gif/aim.gif">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
</CENTER>
<P>
To get the shift under way, Schuller asked Environmental Resources Management (ERM), in Denver, CO, to visit one of its plants and evaluate the environmental aspects and impacts of its manufacturing process. The benchmark portion of the study was to determine just how Schuller's management systems compared to the criteria in ISO 14000 draft standards. 
<p>
Says ERM principal Don Malotte, "They wanted us 
to engineer not just the process by which they managed and controlled the environmental aspects and impacts of their production linebut also, in effect, 
to help them change the philosophy and the attitude that their production teams brought to the job each day." 
<p>

It was an unusualmaybe uniqueassignment. "We're aware of no other project," says ERM's project leader Mick Bilney, "where a management system assessment has been combined with an environmental aspects review and impacts assessment process. The client wanted us to identify operational impacts, including exposures and risks. This may be the first time it's been done in this country, perhaps in the world. The client realized that this identification process would be crucial to future planning, and asked us to help effect a paradigm shift with regard to its 
facilities approach to 
environmental issues. We did it."
<p>
Malotte and the team took the work through four phases, starting with an exhaustive review of all the plant's historic environmental management documentation. This allowed them to get a clear idea not only of the underlying issues involving Schuller's plant operation, but also to locate gaps in the company's existing approaches to environmental issues. Here, and at every stage of the job, ERM worked closely with Schuller, sharing preliminary impressions of findings. This helped to avoid misinterpretation and, more importantly, kept communications open between the team and the client. By incorporating the input of Schuller's facility personnel into the program's design, ERM helped to ensure its success. 
<p>
Next came in-depth, guided interviews with every personfrom corporate level to facility levelwho had any sort of environmental responsibility. Team member Mark Curran, from ERM in Walnut Creek, CA, developed the initial questionnaire incorporating Federal Sentencing Guidelines and ISO 14000 draft standards. Paul Nazaryk, a regulatory 
specialist at ERM in Denver, refined the questionnaire further and made it more user-friendly.
<p>
In Phase III, ERM's team members integrated ISO 14000 standards and their own industrial experience into the program's design. In addition, the operational flow was assessed and a cross-section of plant workers was interviewed. 

<TABLE ALIGN=RIGHT>
<CAPTION ALIGN=BOTTOM><B>Mallotte</B></CAPTION>
<TR><TD>
<IMG SRC="/gif/mallotte.gif">
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>

<p>
Finally, the findings were analyzed and consolidated into a draft report that organized Schuller's environmental management systems assessment efforts around six critical issues: 
<ul>
<li> Environmental policies and goals
<li> Assignment of staff responsibilities and goals
<li> Standard operating procedures
<li> Training, record-keeping, documentation and communication
<li> Internal evaluation and reporting
<li> Environmental management systems resources.
</ul>
<p>
The immediate result? Acceptance by Schuller of nearly all management review findings and recommendations as sound and on target. ERM presented the essence of the draft report to Schuller's environmental staff in a training workshop held in conjunction with Schuller's annual environmental conference. 
<p>
Using ERM's recommendations as a starting point, Schuller then developed several standards and goals for continuous improvement, including: 
<ul>
<li> Integrating environmental goals into business planning
<li> Performing self-assessments to measure performance
<li> Constructing an annual report describing successes and new challenges in the environmental area
<li> Communicating key issues to employees and fostering new and improved communication links between employees and management to improve environmental performance
<li> Developing and improving accountability 
of employees through 
continuous training
<li> Setting goals and 
targets for continuously improving efforts at pollution prevention, waste minimization, energy efficiency and resource conservation.
<p>
In the longer term, ERM's program will be used by Schuller as a mechanism to measure and improve performance at other facilities. And the Performance Materials Division has been told that it is Schuller's new corporate leaderthe flagshipin environmental management. Observes the division's environmental manager, Kurt Bratton, "From their response to our RFP onward, ERM shared our vision. But then they developed the tools we needed to implement the vision. <p> 
Now we're getting calls from other divisions to find out what we're doing. We'll start the new year with a bang. Now, the hard work begins."

<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

<A NAME="tec"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=10><KBD>Technology Update</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Introducing the Do-It-Yourself Audit</B>
<P>

<FONT SIZE="+3">C</FONT>leaning up is one thing. Planning for 
it and keeping track of it is another. It would be ideal for plant managers to have a little help from a user-friendly source that literally becomes part of the internal team, monitoring environmental, health and safety (EHS) conditions and offering suggestions for improvement.
<p>
Unfortunately, not every company can afford a group of consultants capable of doing that.
<p> 
That is where ERM's AUDITpower program comes in. The software quickly becomes a member of the team, providing an easy-to-use, Windows-compatible solution to a variety of EHS problems. The entire auditing process is covered, from checklist development through the finished report. AUDITpower assists in the design of audit checklists, the gathering of relevant data, the formatting of information and the printing of reports. Unlike other, less flexible programs, AUDITpower allows you to create your own checklists or to customize those that come with the system. 
<p>
The checklists cover 14 topics, including hazardous materials, air emissions, OSHA manufacturing, OSHA construction, solid waste and ISO 9000. Each of the checklists helps to identify EHS management issues and provides guidance for improvement. All checklists come complete with questions, answer options, aid notes, guide notes and more. The checklists are available for individual topics or as a package.  Every quarter, those lists are updated, reflecting requirement changes. 
<p>
Once you've decided on the checklist content and organization you want, you're free to go into the field, entering data. As you walk the site, your final report is being formatted from the data that you enter. In addition, AUDITpower has its own word processing program built in, enabling users to work with the document 
on screen before printing. You're not trapped in any particular format; in fact, you can reformat for your own convenience.
<p>
Finally, AUDITpower allows you to raise and check off red flags quickly, to get to the heart of compliance issues. Print your red flags and you have a non-compliance report, the first step in a corrective action plan.
<p>
One of the most powerful aspects of AUDITpower 
is that it turns the audit process into a learning process. In fact, just reviewing the check lists as stand-alones is a great reference for any potential compliance issue. No matter how you choose to use it, AUDITpower allows you to do it yourselfand learn the easy way.
<p>
For more information about AUDITpower, con-
tact Pete Christensen, Director of Marketing for ERM-EVP, at (415) 626-8400. Fax: (415) 626-8480. email: FVS@HOOKED.NET


<p>
<center> <font size=2>Copyright&copy; 1996 ERM</font><br>
<img SRC="/gif/logo_erm.gif"><br>

