<HTML>
<TITLE> PlantExec, November 1995</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#005B52" VLINK="#0D50A2" ALINK="#FFFFFF">
<BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/gif/plant.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="2">AN UPDATE FOR PLANT ENVIRONMENTAL EXECUTIVES</FONT>
<BR>
November 1995
</CENTER>

<HR> 


<UL>
<H2>Contents</H2>
<UL>
     <A HREF="nov95.html#lead"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>Getting the 
Lead Out</KBD></FONT></A>
     <P>
     <A HREF="nov95.html#tec"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>New Technology</KBD></FONT></A>
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="lead"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=20><KBD>GETTING THE<BR> LEAD OUT</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<FONT SIZE=+3>F</FONT>or two decades Dynamic Ceramics had been spray-painting glaze on the lamps it manufactured. The glaze contained lead, which had been picked up by the plant's ventilation system and circulated throughout. Lead was everywhere; so was asbestos. When the company decided to move its operations after 20 years at the same California location, a due diligence audit revealed substantial environmental, health and safety problems at the site.
<p>
As the company closed down its operations and prepared to terminate its lease, it had to satisfy both the owner of the property and the state environmental agency that all environmental problems had been mitigated. Dynamic was obligated to continue paying rent on the now-non-income-producing property at the rate of $3,000 a day. The company's deep pockets were getting shallower with each tick of the clock, and Dynamic knew it was important to get this work done, and quickly. 
<p>
It was a huge joband one made even more formidable by its complexity. Each remedial task was interrelated, so that as one problem was tackled, it changed the nature of others. The company needed integrated solutions that could be implemented quickly and cost-effectively. 
After a number of $3,000-days went by, Dynamic decided to terminate its relationship with its then-consultant. Simultaneously, Dynamic's law firm, which had worked with ERM and knew its reputation, asked ERM in Irvine, Calif., to come in.
<p>
"The other consultant just didn't have an overall objective," says ERM's 
Wallid Kazi, project director on the Dynamic Ceramic job. "What distinguished us was that we were able to look at the big pictureto see the trees and the forest at the same time. Also, we were very clear about what our mission was because we were very clear about the client's need. The purpose of everything that 
had gone on before our involvement, and that which we were called upon to accomplish, was to get that lease exit agreement for Dynamic. It focused our thinking. We were able to ask ourselves, as we went into our planning and decision-making process, what strategy would best achieve that end."
<p>
ERM's first step was to design and install a perimeter air monitoring program for the entire facility. With lead and asbestos present, 
it was important to identify potential health hazards to the surrounding community and to the project staff. The air monitoring program gave Kazi and his team the information they needed to design the comprehensive lead and asbestos abatement programs that would be central to their mitigation efforts. They called in subcontractors and managed the work. The roof, for instance, had been sprayed with lead-based paint. It had to be removed and disposed of safely. Lead dust was everywhere inside the 200,000-square-foot building; ERM pressure-washed the walls and floors and used special vacuums to clean the air. A preliminary risk assessment showed particulate lead levels in the building's air above those allowed by California's Proposition 65. Under that law there were two choices: clean up, or post signs advising of the hazard.
<p>
Kazi knew it was 
physically impossible to eliminate the minute lead particles from the air. In this case, cleanup would mean a complete demolition and removal of the facilitya very expensive proposition. But the alternative, a Prop 65 warning, would put Dynamic at substantial risk for future claims based on the presence of airborne lead dust. To many, Prop 65 postings are nothing more than invitations to sue. 
<p>
Kazi called in Bruce Molholt, a toxicology 
specialist and a world-renowned figure in risk assessment, from ERM in Exton, Pa. Kazi and Molholt analyzed the bioavailability factors to assess risk potential. Bioavailability is based on the principle that normally harmful materials, such as lead, are not always biologically available to the human body, depending on the form in which the materials exist. The lead dust they had found was in a silicate forma form that cannot be absorbed by humans. Moreover, Kazi knew, the human lung naturally refuses particles of the size that existed in the building. Using these two criteriasize and bioavailabilityERM's team was able to convince both the regulatory agency and a risk assessment expert from 
the owner's side that the lead in the building did not pose a risk requiring a Prop 65 warning. "This was probably the first time the local agency had ever accepted such an argument," says Kazi. It meant the client wouldn't have to pay for complete demolition and removal 
of the facility.
<p>
Kazi says three things distinguished ERM in 
its efforts on behalf of Dynamic Ceramics. First was the ability to see the big picture and tackle complicated, interrelated tasks. Second, "we were able to do what needed to be done in a timely and cost-effective manner."
<p> 
And finally, Kazi says, "we have considerable depth of experience in working with regulatory agencies. You have to realize that even if another contractor had done the job and done it well, the job wouldn't be over until the regulatory agency said it was over. We recognize that. Working with the 
regulatory agency, being familiar with their procedures and having their respect going in, was just as important to this client as cleaning up the yard. 
<p>
For them, every day of delay was another $3,000, no matter whether they were waiting for the last load of contaminants to 
be hauled away or for a regulator to get to his in box. I guess what I'm 
saying is, we were able to finish the job, completely. And most important, the client is satisfied."


<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

<A NAME="tec"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=10><KBD>New Technology</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Advanced Fluidized Composting 
System Results in Lower Costs 
and 95% Less Sludge</B>
<P>

<FONT SIZE="+3">E</FONT>RM's Advanced Fluidized CompostingSM (AFC) system is a unique process technology for treating high-strength (up to 60,000 ppm and greater, Chemical Oxygen Demand) organic waste streams and sludges. Unlike traditional biological treatment systems, which produce large amounts of sludge, AFC reduces sludge by 95%, and with lower costs. Now it's online full-scale at a remediation site in New Jersey. Another installation (intended for the treatment of dairy wastes) is soon to be constructed 
in Pennsylvania, and 
two other systemsin Holland, Michigan, and Baltimore, Marylandare undergoing engineering evaluation. 
<p>
The patented technology combines thermophilic biological treatment with 
a proprietary chemical treatment step. The thermophilic biological treatment is the essence of composting: Bacteria that thrive at high temperatures (110-160 F) work to decompose the stream, creating heat (and, thus, their appropriate environment) along the way. 
<p>
What distinguishes 
the ERM approach is the chemical treatment step that breaks down any refractory elements not already broken down by the biological system. The chemically treated wastes are then recirculated through the system for biological treatment.
<p>
The process, 
says senior program director Mark J. Krupka, is "very cost- effective compared to other systems, and it generates less sludgein the range of little to none."
<p>
Waste streams on which the AFC technology has been successfully applied include:
<ul>
<li> High-strength organic acids
<li> Fermentation broths
<li> Solvents
<li> Viscose fiber sludges
<li> Waste activated sludges
<li> High-strength methanol streams
<li> High-strength nitrate streams
<li> Phenolic streams
<li> Cosmetic wastes with high fats, oils and greases (FOG)
<li> Dairy wastes with high FOG
<li> Food processing wastes.
</ul>
<p>
For more information 
on ERM's AFC technology, contact Mark J. Krupka, senior program director, 
at (610)524-3796.

<p>
<center> <font size=2>Copyright&copy; 1996 ERM</font><br>
<img SRC="/gif/logo_erm.gif"><br>

<br clear=all> 
</center>

