</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<TITLE> PlantExec, September 1995</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#005B52" VLINK="#0D50A2" ALINK="#FFFFFF">

<BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/gif/plant.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="2">AN UPDATE FOR PLANT ENVIRONMENTAL EXECUTIVES</FONT>
<BR>
September 1995
</CENTER>

<HR> 


<UL>
<H2>Contents</H2>
<UL>
     <A HREF="sep95.html#cos"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>More Than a 
Cosmetic Solution</KBD></FONT></A>
     <P>
     <A HREF="sep95.html#reg"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>Regulatory Update</KBD></FONT></A>
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="cos"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=20><KBD>MORE THAN A 
<BR>
COSMETIC SOLUTION</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<FONT SIZE=+3>W</FONT>henever ABC Products of New England conducted a health and safety audit at its cosmetic formulating and packaging facilities, it spotted problems. The same kinds of problems, over and over again. So ABC would clean up the problems, get in compliance, wait for the next audit, and then  clean up again. Meanwhile, and more importantly, it was being hit with accidents, days lost to injury and equipment problems.
<p>
For four years ABC had been working with ERM in Albany, NY, on a variety of projects, only one of them a health and safety audit. By the time ABC asked ERM's Jim Testo and Jane Whitehouse to come in prior 
to a second audit, the company's patience with being perpetually out of grace had worn very thin. 
<p>
"What they wanted," recalls Testo, director of environmental health and safety for ERM, "was to reduce accidents and injuries. I told them that another audit would just produce another list of problems because they hadn't taken any steps to change things to stop the problems from happening. That's when the meeting got interesting."
<p>
Testo and Whitehouse were fortunate to have had a client who was willing to do something beyond dotting the i's and crossing the t's of the letter of the law. The approach ERM developedlooking beyond the regulatory checklist at the entire scope of a facility's operationsworked not only for ABC Products but, over the next year and a half, for other New York and New England clientsincluding one with a major facility in India. Good ideas spread quickly, and widely.
<p>
The approach they developed began with a conference with the top management of ABCa session designed to learn exactly what the client's goals were. ERM worked with the company to develop a reporting system that would enable the company to identify and take action against the root causes of its problems, whether those causes turned out to be design-based or management-based.
<p>
This was followed by the risk assessment audits themselves, and, shortly thereafter, by a closing 
conference with facility managers. The closing conference was crucialthe forum in which ERM was able to present its findings, orally and in hard copy, 
to the people who would 
be responsible for taking corrective action. The 
hard-copy findings were presented on the specially designed task sheets the ERM team had developed at their initial meeting with management.
<p>
The task sheet was created to provide fast identification of each specific problemtwo pages maximum, one page when possible. "This way," says Jane Whitehouse, who is a manager of environmental health and safety for ERM, "managers don't have to plow through 40 or 50 sheets of prose just to find out what their issues are."
<p>
Or how to fix them. "Instead of being merely a communication of what's wrong," says Testo, "the task sheet provides a functional, systematic approach to fixing the problem. Root-cause analysis is old hat, but presenting it as we did is something new."
<p>
The task sheet encourages auditors to minimize words and get to the point concerning a number of parameters:
<ul>
<li> Type of risk: personal injury or illness/property damage
<li> Probability
<li> Severity
<li> Immediate corrective action
<li> Root cause identification
<li> Managed solution
</ul>
<p>
The Probability and Severity sections allow auditors to assess the likelihood and the consequencesincluding the financial onesshould an event occur.
<p>
Additionally, the Immediate Corrective Action box provides a space in which auditors can provide a cost estimate for initiating the action. 
<p>
The last three items on the page have accountability built in: spaces for facility managers to sign and date when they have taken the appropriate remedial steps.
ERM used a digital imaging camera to photograph each of the health 
or safety problems it identified. Digital cameras don't use film, so there are no negatives; security was ensured simply by turning the camera's digital data disk over to the client. 
The resulting photographs became powerful learning tools for those members 
of the management team who might not have recognized the risk associated with a particular finding 
or condition.
<p>
During February, March and April of 1994, ERM sent two people to each of half a dozen ABC Products facilities in several states. The ERM auditors, however, required more than a familiarity with the regulatory requirements appropriate to each facility. Since they were delving for problems beyond those covered by regulations, they had to be expert in a variety of areas. To identify risks for each facility, for instance, they had to know the appropriate life safety codes, building codes, recommended industry practices, and best management practices. 
<p>
The cost of ERM's new, comprehensive approach? Including all labor, travel and expenses, about the same, says Testo, "as a 
typical health and safety audit where we know what we're looking for and where there's no extensive travel.
"Couple that kind 
of cost efficiency," Testo continues, "with the extremely fast turnaround time we deliveredplus the closing conference where we walked them through our findings task sheet by task sheet, enabling them to pick up the ball immediatelyand we've got a happy client."
<p>
ABC Products' vice president for risk management concurs, noting that in the first half-year after the audits were completed, ABC Products experienced a 24 percent reduction in worker's compensation claims. Moreover, he 
anticipates future benefitsincluding reduced costs associated with lost work days, medical claims, worker's compensation, property damage, product loss and litigation.
<p>
The success of Whitehouse and Testo and their ERM team has not gone unnoticed at home, either. They were the winners of ERM's 1995 Excellence Award in the Health and Safety category.
<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

<A NAME="reg"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=10><KBD>Regulatory Update</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Advanced Fluidized Composting 
System Results in Lower Costs 
and 95% Less Sludge</B>
<P>

<FONT SIZE="+3">E</FONT>RM's Advanced Fluidized CompostingSM (AFC) system is a unique process technology for treating high-strength (up to 60,000 ppm and greater, Chemical Oxygen Demand) organic waste streams and sludges. Unlike traditional biological treatment systems, which produce large amounts of sludge, AFC reduces sludge by 95%, and with lower costs. Now it's online full-scale at a remediation site in New Jersey. Another installation (intended for the treatment of dairy wastes) is soon to be constructed 
in Pennsylvania, and 
two other systemsin Holland, Michigan, and Baltimore, Marylandare undergoing engineering evaluation. 
<p>
The patented technology combines thermophilic biological treatment with 
a proprietary chemical treatment step. The thermophilic biological treatment is the essence of composting: Bacteria that thrive at high temperatures (110-160 F) work to decompose the stream, creating heat (and, thus, their appropriate environment) along the way. 
<p>
What distinguishes 
the ERM approach is the chemical treatment step that breaks down any refractory elements not already broken down by the biological system. The chemically treated wastes are then recirculated through the system for biological treatment.
<p>
The process, 
says senior program director Mark J. Krupka, is "very cost- effective compared to other systems, and it generates less sludgein the range of little to none."
<p>
Waste streams on which the AFC technology has been successfully applied include:
<ul>
<li> High-strength organic acids
<li> Fermentation broths
<li> Solvents
<li> Viscose fiber sludges
<li> Waste activated sludges
<li> High-strength methanol streams
<li> High-strength nitrate streams
<li> Phenolic streams
<li> Cosmetic wastes with high fats, oils and greases (FOG)
<li> Dairy wastes with high FOG
<li> Food processing wastes.
</ul>
<p>
For more information 
on ERM's AFC technology, contact Mark J. Krupka, senior program director, 
at (610)524-3796.

<p>
<center> <font size=2>Copyright&copy; 1996 ERM</font><br>
