<HTML>
<TITLE> PlantExec, May 1995</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#005B52" VLINK="#0D50A2" ALINK="#FFFFFF">

<BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/gif/plant.gif"><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="2">AN UPDATE FOR PLANT ENVIRONMENTAL EXECUTIVES</FONT>
<BR>
May 1995
</CENTER>

<HR> 


<UL>
<H2>Contents</H2>
<UL>
     <A HREF="may95.html#mother"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>The Mother of Invention</KBD></FONT></A>
     <P>
     <A HREF="may95.html#reg"><FONT SIZE=5><KBD>Regulatory Update</KBD></FONT></A>
</UL>
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<A NAME="mother"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=20><KBD>THE MOTHER OF INVENTION</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<H4>When a manufacturing firm faced an emissions 
control evaluation that would have taken tons of time and money, it was BACT to the drawing board.</H4>

<FONT SIZE=+3>I</FONT>ll regulators have one thing in common: the power to regulate. But how they apply it may vary. A regulator, like an auditor 
for the IRS, may ask very little from a company
or enough to strain its resources for weeks.
<p>	
Take the State Environmental Protection Agency (SEPA) of a midwestern state. It wanted Anon 
Corporation (not its real name), a vehicle body manufacturer, to evaluate its surface coating (painting) processes to ensure that the best available control technology (BACT) was being used to limit emissions of volatile organic compounds (VOCs). Anon had four major coating lines in two different buildings that would require BACT analysis. 
<p>	
Typicallyas set forth in the back of the U.S. EPA's HAP manualBACT analysis is a step-by-step procedure which tracks emission flow rates, temperatures, and contaminant concentrations. It's a fill-in-the-blanks pencil-and-paper 
calculation involving the identification, quantification and processing of dozens 
of variables. Ultimately, it evaluates the cost-effectiveness of applying emission controls to a pollutant stream. Then, if a permitting authority like SEPA determines that the cost of controlling the emissions is reasonable, it has the power to require those controls. 	
<p>	
In the Anon case, however, the SEPA representative wanted more than an evaluation of VOCs in the single main exhaust header for each line. He demanded that each of the small exhaust streams feeding into those main exhaust headers be evaluated. And not just individually, but 
in every possible combinationa "what if" analysis that strained the bounds of "what if," requiring more than 50 evaluations. Using then-traditional methods, it would have cost in the neighborhood of $300,000. 
<p>	
Anon called ERM, Inc. for help.
<p>	
With engineering understatement, Steve Cox, a member of the ERM team assigned to the project, described the challenge: "It was clear that a more efficient method of performing BACT analyses was needed for this project."
<p>	
The team at ERM, Inc. (which also included Russ Zeckner) decided the best way to go forward was to go backwardto rewrite the book. "The key here," Cox recalls, "is that if you have a single source emission and a regulator you can work with, thenas antiquated as it sounds
the pencil and paper method really is the most efficient way of doing the job. But that wasn't the case with Anon Corp."
<p>	
Instead of trying to make existing approaches more cost-effective, the ERM, Inc. team decided 
to develop a completely new, high-speed, computer-based BACT analysis 
system, working both 
with EPA cost-estimating procedures and control-technology suppliers to develop cost algorithms 
for their new approach. They dubbed their finished product "Fast-BACT."
<p>	
The way Fast-BACT works, the user fills out an input sheet that includes all of the parameters and costs relevant to the construction and operation of an emissions control system. Then, using macros, Fast-BACT generates report-quality costing worksheets, tables and graphs for whichever 
of the following control technologies is appropriate: thermal incineration; catalytic thermal incineration; thermal regenerative incineration; catalytic regeneration incineration; carbon adsorption; or adsorption/
oxidation. 
<p>	
"At the push of a 
button you can select 
up to 20 different report-format outputs," says Cox. 
<p>
"Everything from the input table which contains all the defining parameters, to the calculations used for each control technology, to a summary cost table that compares the annual operating costs of the different control technologies. Or 
the same comparisons in graph format."
<p>	
Performance of 
Fast-BACT exceeded expectations and, ultimately, obtained the approval of SEPA's bureaucratic scrutiny. Says Cox: "After the regulator saw how quickly we were able to address all of his questions, he started wondering about the calculations set up by the U.S. EPA in the first place. By the time the process was over, the scientist who wrote the original manual had to write letters defending it." 
<p>	
Fast-BACT is not just fast. It greatly diminishes the possibility of a computational error, and it 
provides clear consistent 
documentation of every step of the analysis. It also comes in at about one-third the cost of traditional 
BACT analysis. 
<p>	
Just as significant, it 
is a technology that can be (and has been) duplicated and is now taking hold across the ERM Group on behalf of a wide variety of clients who need BACT analyses performed in order to be in compliance with state and federal clean air standards. One of the best testimonials to the new process: Since the development of Fast-BACT, Anon Corporation itself has 
come to ERM with some $200,000 of additional 
business. 
<p>	
And if that isn't 
testimonial enough, Cox, 
and the team received ERM's first Excellence Award in the Air Quality Category for innovation, quality improvement, cost savings to clients, and a good application of technology. Cox's reaction? As close as an engineer gets to gushing: "We were elated."


<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<BR>

<A NAME="reg"><CENTER><FONT SIZE=10><KBD>Regulatory Update</KBD></FONT></CENTER></A>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Small facilities to be judged on 
actual, not potential, emissions.</B>
<P>

<B>THE NEWS:</B>
<p>	
The EPA has issued a two-year interim policy on "Potential to Emit" that could ease the compliance burden of a significant number of U.S. facilities subject to Title V of the Clean Air Act as amended.

<p>
<B>THE BACKGROUND:</B>
<p>	
Under the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990, applicability of the Title V operating permit program and most other air quality requirements is usually determined by a facility's potential to emit air 
pollutants, not its actual emissions. Thus, a large number of relatively small facilitieseven though their actual emissions are lowwould appear to be subject to a "major source" classification, because their potential to emit pollutants is great, based on the assumption that a facility operates 8,760 hours a year at full capacity. Under these standards, standby equipment, for example, could be included in the equation, thus making an otherwise small source appear major.
<p>
<B>WHAT THE INTERIM
POLICY DOES:</B>
<p>	
The new two-year interim policy exempts sources from the standards set by the 1990 amendments. It allows sources to limit their potential emissions through state permits or through keeping records. Thus, "major source" classification under the Title V Operating Permit and Hazardous Air Pollutant programs would be avoided.
<p>	
The interim policy was issued in order to give state regulators time to extend permanent exemption from the requirements to some of these smaller source facilities.
<p>
<B>TO FIND OUT MORE:</B>
<p>	
EPA outlined their transition policy in a 
guidance memo published on January 25, 1995. Copies can be obtained from the EPA Technology Transfer Network bulletin board (919-541-5742). 
<p>
For more information 
on air permitting, call ERM at 800-544-3117.
<p>
<center> <font size=2>Copyright&copy; 1996 ERM</font><br>
<img SRC="/gif/logo_erm.gif"><br>

<br clear=all> 
</center>

