<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Alert</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H3> 
Hazardous Waste Identification Rule - Contaminated Media
40 CFR 269
</H3>
<I> Action: </I><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1"> Proposed Rule;<br>
Request for Comments<br>
Comment Deadline: <br>
 7/29/96 </FONT><BR>


<I> Date: </I><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1"> 4/29/96
61 FR 18780 </FONT><BR>

<I> For More Information
Contact: </I><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1"> Rich Dulcey<bt>
(610) 524-3610<br>
John Hazard<br>
(610) 524-3752 </FONT><BR>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD>Introduction</KBD></FONT></B>
<P>

The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has issued a proposed rule that is intended to minimize remediation disincentives by creating more flexible management standards for contaminated media and wastes generated during site cleanups.
<p>
The proposal gives EPA and authorized states the ability to exempt low risk, contaminated media from RCRA Subtitle C regulation.  The proposal does not exempt the media from Land Disposal Restriction (LDR), but modifies requirements for higher risk media and allows for site-specific exemptions for low risk media.  The proposal also includes Subtitle C exemptions for navigational dredged sediments managed under the Clean Water Act or the Marine Protection, Research and Sanctuaries Act.
<p>
The proposal applies to excavated media regulated as hazardous waste due to a hazardous characteristic or to contamination with a listed hazardous waste.  It does not apply to debris, sludges or other non-media wastes.  The proposal does not address what should be cleaned up, "how clean is clean" or remedy selection.
<p>
The proposal sets "Bright Line" levels for soils and groundwater which differentiate between high risk and lower risk contaminated media.  Media with constituents below the "Bright Line"  could be exempted from RCRA Subtitle C if managed under approved site-specific controls.  For media with constituents at or above any "Bright Line" level, new HWIR-media treatment standards would apply.  Existing RCRA regulations pertinent to treatment, storage, and disposal would continue to apply.
<p>
To become authorized, states must certify to EPA that their base programs are equivalent to the federal program.  Until authorization, existing requirements will remain in effect.
<p>
EPA is requesting comment on other alternatives including industry's proposed Unitary Approach that exempts all cleanup wastes from Subtitle C and does not include "Bright Lines" or new treatment standards.  EPA is also requesting comment on any combination of options and believes there is enough information in the record to pursue a different approach without having to repropose the rule.
<p>
<br>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD> RELATIONSHIP TO OTHER PROGRAMS: </KBD></FONT>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Will be an integral part of the Subpart S (RCRA Sections 3004[u] and 3004[v]) rulemaking.
<p>
<li>Will replace Corrective Action Management Unit (CAMU) regulations but grandfathers existing CAMUs.
<p>
<li>Does not address the temporary exclusion from the Toxicity Characteristic (TC) rule for petroleum contaminated media and debris generated from underground storage tank (UST) cleanups.
<p>
<li>Covers the TC suspension for non-UST petroleum contaminated media.
<p>
<li>Proposed HWIR-waste exit levels are higher (less conservative) than 27% of the soil "Bright Lines" and 20% of the groundwater "Bright Lines." EPA recognizes that this inconsistency must be addressed before promulgation.
<p>
<li>Creates separate state HWIR-media authorization that can be withdrawn without endangering the entire RCRA delegation.
<p>
<li>Current RCRA scheme prevails as ARAR under Superfund until a state is authorized under HWIR-media.
</ul>
<p>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD> ERM Can Help </KBD></FONT>
<P>
<ul>

<li>Environmental Resources Management, Inc. (ERM) believes that this proposal has potentially major implications for any industry involved in a site remediation project.
<p>

<li>ERM can put our expertise to work for you by assisting you in the following areas:
<ul>	
<li> ERM can provide support to evaluate cost,
   schedule, and liability issues from this proposal.
	<li>ERM can advise clients on how to comment on, or 
   plan on integrating this proposal into their projects.
</ul>
</ul>
If you need assistance in any of these areas, or with other environmental challenges, use the attached fax form or call Rick Dulcey at (610) 524-3610 in Exton, PA.
<p>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD> Key Features: </KBD></FONT>
<p>

<ul>
<li>Sets 202 "Bright Line" limits for hazardous constituents in ground water and 100 in soils and sediments based on residential exposure scenarios.
<p>
<li>Sets new LDR treatment standards for contaminated soils at the higher of 90%, or 10 times the Universal Treatment Standard and removal of the characteristic.
<p>
<li>Establishes new HWIR-media specific treatment variances.
<p>
<li>Creates a new unit a remediation pile used only for temporary treatment or storage of remediation wastes.
<p>
<li>Deems a site-specific 	Remediation Management Plan (RMP) to be a RCRA permit.

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
<center>
<a href="/map/buttonbar.map">
<IMG SRC="/gif/button_bar.gif" WIDTH=484 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 ISMAP USEMAP="#buttonbar"></a>
</center>
<br>



