<HEAD>
<TITLE>Alert</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H3> 
Phase III Land Disposal Restriction (LDR) Rule 
</H3>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD>Introduction</KBD></FONT>
<P>


In their continuing effort to develop and implement the RCRA land disposal restrictions (LDR), the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) proposed the Phase III rule which covers a wide array of topics that were not addressed in previous LDR rulemakings or have since been modified.  
<p>
A primary focus of the rulemaking was to establish concentration-based treatment standards for underlying hazardous constituents in ignitable, corrosive, reactive, and toxicity characteristic wastes (other than D004-D011) managed in CWA, CWA-equivalent, and Class I underground injection well (SDWA/UIC)) systems.  However, EPA recognized that by allowing dilution to be used to "decharacterize" ignitable, corrosive, and reactive characteristic wastes, the requirements and intent of the LDR program could be circumvented.  Specifically, the treatment of underlying hazardous constituents in characteristic wastes by means of dilution does not remove the hazardous constituents, as intended by the LDR program, but simply lowers the concentration.  Therefore, EPA proposed that underlying hazardous constituents in characteristic wastes at the point of generation must be treated (not diluted) to universal treatment standards (UTS) or existing CWA standards/limitations prior to being land disposed.  (Note that EPA is recognizing existing CWA limitations and standards as RCRA-equivalent standards).
<p>
EPA also established treatment standards for 67 newly listed wastes including: spent aluminum pot liners (K088); organobromine wastes (K140 and U408); and carbamate wastes (K156-K161, and 58 RPS and RUS listed wastes).  In addition, the UTS promulgated under Phase II was modified to include 43 additional hazardous constituents associated with the newly listed wastes, 1 wastewater and 12 non-wastewater standards that were not established previously in Phase II, and concentration-based standards for two waste codes (P003, P056) that were previously treatment method standards.
<p>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD> ERM Can Help </KBD></FONT>
<P>


Environmental Resources Management (ERM), Inc. can put our expertise to work for you by assisting you in the following areas:
<p>
<ul>
<li>Prepare plans to sample and analyze points of generation and assess source treatment or end-of-pipe treatment options.
<p>
<li>Assess options to exempt your facility out of LDR Phase III by modifying operations or waste management practices.
<p>
If you need assistance in any of these areas or with other environmental challenges, call Rich Dulcey at (610) 524-3610 in Exton, Pennsylvania.
</ul>
<p>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD> Key Features: </KBD></FONT>
<p>

<ul>
<li>Provides a two-year capacity variance for certain decharacterized wastes managed in CWA/SDWA systems, and a three-month variance for other applicable wastes to allow facilities to make the necessary operation and permit modifications.
<p>
<li>Specifies reporting and monitoring requirements for CWA/SDWA systems that manage characteristic or decharacterized wastes.
<p>
<li>Eliminates the exceptions for spent solvents (F001-F005), acrylonitrile production wastes (K011, K013, and K014), and aniline/nitrobenzene production wastes (K103 and K104) from the wastewater definition in 40 CFR 268.2(f) (i.e., <1% TOC and <1% total suspended solids).
<p>
<li>Modifies the requirements which apply to the de minimis losses of D001 and D002 wastes (e.g., commercial chemical products, laboratory wastes) to wastewater treatment systems provided in 40 CFR 268.1(e).
<p>
<li>Clarifies regulatory language which prohibits the use of hazardous waste as fill material.
(continued over)
Key Features: (cont.)
<p>
<li>Prohibits dilution through combustion of inorganic metal-bearing waste which do not contain a significant organic or cyanide concentration.  
<p>
<li>Expands the combustion treatment method (CMBST) established in Phase II to apply to wastes that specified only incineration (INCIN). 
<p>
<li>Raised the treatment standard for acetonitrile to be consistent with similar organonitrogen compounds.
<p>
<li>Addresses future rulemaking considerations that will involve the LDR program, including: cross-media transfer; point-of-generation definition; and prohibition of nonamenable wastes from biological treatment systems.
</ul>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
