<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H3> 
NJDEP DER 
Open Market 
Trading Program
</H3>

<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD>Introduction</KBD></FONT>
<P>
On 1 July 1996 the New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection (NJDEP) promulgated a new VOC and NOx air pollution control program (Subchapter 30) which embraces the concepts contained in the USEPA model open market trading rule.  The new program provides facilities with the opportunity to implement pollution prevention, mobile source or conventional air pollution controls to generate discrete emissions reduction (DER) credits for sale or cost-effectively use in meeting emission control requirements on other emission sources.  A DER represents a 
tradeable/saleable quantity of actual emissions reductions that occurs at a source during a specific generation period which are below its lowest allowable emission rate.  The smallest quantity 
of a DER is one-twentieth of a ton (0.05 tons).  Subchapter 30 describes, in detail, requirements 
for the generation, use, transfer, verification, notification and certification of DERs. NJDEP's open market trading rule is a chance to add value to your air pollution control program.
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD> Key Features of the DER Program</KBD></FONT>
<p>
<ul>
<li>A unique environmental regulatory program to provide facilities with an opportunity to meet ongoing VOC and NOx control requirements more cost- effectively.<p>
<li>Implementation of the program is through generation of  discrete 
emissions reduction (DER) credits.<p>
<li>A DER represents a tradable/salable quantity of actual emissions reductions below a source's allowable emission rate.<p>
<li>DERs can be used to:  generate savings/revenues,  meet existing air pollution control requirements and satisfy emission "offset" requirements.<p>
</ul>

<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD>Generation and Use of DERs</KBD></FONT>
<p>
NJDEP has not prescribed DER generation strategies, anticipating new and innovative approaches. However, the following types of activitie, might be used to generate DERs:
<ul>
<li>reduce mobile source activity<p>
<li>implement energy conservation activities<p>
<li>carry out pollution prevention activities<p>
<li"over-control" existing sources of emissions<p>
</ul>
DERs can be used for:
<ul>
<li>sale (any other facility within New Jersey)<p>
<li>meeting emission limitations for a source at the same facility<p>
<li>meeting emission limitations for a source at a different facility<p>
</ul>
Upon use, 10% of DERs must be retired.
<P>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD>Benefits to DER Participants</KBD></FONT>
<p>
Although facilities are not required to participate in the open market trading program, this is an unique strategic compliance opportunity. Participation in the program can provide:
<ul>
<li>an opportunity to meet on-going VOC and/or NOx control requirements while reducing compliance cost;<p>
<li>a facility or company-wide air pollution control program which allows for the most cost-effective air pollution control solutions to address growth and process changes; and<p>
<li>the most cost-effective emission reduction strategy(s) across several operations and locations.<p>
</ul>
<p>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD>DER Cost Saving Examples</KBD></FONT>
<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="/gif/tree.gif">
</CENTER>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD>Source/Date of DER Program</KBD></FONT>
<P>
Codified in New Jersey Administrative Code, 
Title 7, Chapter 27, Subchapter 30 (NJAC 7:27-30)
<p>
Promulgated New Jersey Register, 1 July 1996, 
pp. 3414-3462 (28 NJR 3414-3462)
<p>
Effective Date - 1 July 1996
<p>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD>ERM'S Approach to the DER Program</KBD></FONT>
<p>
Environmental Resources Management (ERM) has the strategic management expertise to help facilities implement this profound new regulatory program to minimize air pollution control costs.  We can assist with the computation, generation, verification, registration, use, notification, and certification of DERs.  ERM's scope of services for implementing a DER program include:
<ul>
Strategic Planning<BR>
	Economic Evaluation of Options
<BR>	Development of Plans for Facilities, 
   Departments, or Corporations
<BR>	Development of Guidance Manuals 
   and Awareness Seminars
<BR> Process and Operational Modifications
<BR>	Opportunity Assessment
<BR>	Permitting Support
<BR>	Agency Report Preparation
<BR>	Tracking Systems
</ul>
<p>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD>About ERM</KBD></FONT>
<p>
ERM is a global organization of engineers, scientists and health and safety professionals with 2,400 employees at more than 95 locations around the world.  Contact Ron Harkov or Alan Shimada in ERM's Ewing, NJ office to learn how we can help your company achieve cost-effective VOC and NOxcompliance by utilizing the NJDEP DER program.
<ul> <B>Environmental Resources Management</B><BR>
Princeton Crossroads Corporate Center<BR>
300 Phillips Boulevard, Suite 200 <BR>
Ewing, New Jersey 08618 <BR>
(609) 895-0050 <BR>
(609) 895-0111 (fax)<BR>
mkt_info@erm.com (email)<BR>
www.erm.com <BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
