<TITLE>Alert</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H3> 

UPDATE: EPA's Accidental Release Prevention Requirements:
Risk Management Programs Under Clean Air Act Section 112(r)(7)

</H3>


<I>Action:</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1">Proposed Rule</FONT><BR>
<I>Date:</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1">Expected publication<BR>
24 March 1996 </FONT><BR>
<I>For More Information Contact:</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1"> Peter Charrington<BR>
(610) 524-3431 </FONT><BR>
<I>Compliance Date:</I><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1"> Three years from publication </FONT>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD>Introduction</KBD></FONT>
<P>
Under Title III of the Clean Air Act Amendments of 1990, both OSHA and EPA must regulate facilities that handle extremely hazardous substances.  OSHA is accomplishing this activity through its Process Safety Management (PSM) program, while EPA will soon release its new regulation addressing Risk Management Programs (RMPs).  While details of EPA's program are still emerging (Federal Register notice of 31 January 1994 details the applicability requirements), with a final rule scheduled for 24 March 1996, the time to determine applicability and develop cost-effective compliance strategies is now.  Environmental Resources Management (ERM), Inc. has developed a manual that can assist your facility in determining the likelihood of having to comply with the RMP and then "walks" you through the tasks necessary to comply with the OSHA and EPA programs, including the preparation of the off-site consequence analysis.
<P>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD> ERM Can Help </KBD></FONT>
<P>
ERM, Inc. can put our expertise to work for you by assisting you the following areas:
<p>
<ul>
<li>Provide a customized program and manual to ensure that your response to the OSHA and EPA programs is cost-effective and integrated.
<p>
<li>Assist you in developing the hazard assessments under different release scenarios for your facility.
<p>
<li>Perform screening level hazard assessments and an off-site consequence analysis to identify the need for early community presentations, and then develop a "public awareness" campaign for you.
<p>
<li>Develop modeling scenarios that can be applied to multiple facilities in different locations within the same corporation.
<p>
<li>Develop strategies and use your Title V permit, if possible, to avoid the new EPA RMP program.
If you need assistance in any of these areas or with other environmental challenges, use the attached fax sheet or call Pete Charrington at 
(610) 524-3431 in Exton, PA.
<p>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD> Key Features: </KBD></FONT>
<p>
<li>Affected facilities will have to prepare a hazard assessment which evaluates the potential effects of an accidental release of any of 140 regulated substances.
<p>
<li>Facilities will need to conduct worst-case release scenario analyses (based on a 10-minute release of the largest quantity of a regulated substance from a vessel or process failure under worst case meteorological conditions) in order to prepare an off-site consequence analysis.  The results/impacts must be disclosed to the public.
<p>
<li>EPA is evaluating the applicability determination based on phased, or tiered approach. Facilities will be subject to RMP requirements based upon such things as the number of employees, whether or not a release would have any impact on the public, five-year accident history, etc.
</ul>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
<center>
<a href="/map/buttonbar.map">
<IMG SRC="/gif/button_bar.gif" WIDTH=484 HEIGHT=34 BORDER=0 ISMAP USEMAP="#buttonbar"></a>
</center>
