<TITLE>Alert</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H3> 

UPDATE: 
Delaware's Title V Program Impacts Hospitals
</H3>
<I> Action: </I><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1"> Promulgated Rule </FONT><BR>

<I> Date: </I><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1"> 3 January 1996 </FONT><BR>

<I> For More Information Contact: </I><BR>
<FONT SIZE="-1"> Peter Charrington
ERM, Inc.
Exton, Pennsylvania
(610) 524-3431 </FONT><BR>
<HR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD>Introduction</KBD></FONT>
<P>

Many hospitals in Delaware will be required to file an application for a new operating permit with the Delaware Department of Natural Resources and Environmental Control (DNREC).  DNREC's new permit program, adopted in response to the 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments, became effective on 
3 January 1996 and is designed to better control atmospheric emissions from institutional and industrial facilities in Delaware.  Any facility/hospital which has potential emissions of regulated pollutants greater than the "major source" thresholds will be required to submit a new operating permit application.  Institutions, including hospitals, are often major sources as a result of  their boiler or incinerator emissions.
<p>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD> ERM Can Help </KBD></FONT>
<P>

Environmental Resources Management (ERM), Inc. is currently involved in operating permit projects for numerous clients in Delaware and across the nation.  We can put our expertise to work for you by assisting you in the following areas:
<p>
<li>Assess your hospital to formulate an approach that will lead to compliance with Title V in a cost-effective and rapid manner.  
<p>
<li>Perform a turnkey Title V project, or we can be involved selectively in those areas where you specifically need assistance (emissions inventory, application review, etc.). 
If you need assistance with Title V or other environmental issues, either use the attached fax sheet or call Peter Charrington (610) 524-3431, or Julie Ross at (610) 524-3414 with ERM in Exton, PA.
<p>
<FONT SIZE="+1"><KBD> Key Features: </KBD></FONT>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Facilities located in New Castle and Kent Counties must file for a permit if their emissions of a regulated pollutant potentially exceeds 25 tons per year or approximately 5 pounds per hour.  Facilities located in Sussex County must file a permit application if their emissions of a regulated pollutant exceeds 100 tons per year (the regulated pollutant of concern is oxides of nitrogen [NOx] generated by all combustion sources).
<p>
<li>DNREC has indicated that facilities which emit less than 150 tons per year (tpy) of regulated pollutants, which includes most hospitals, are required to submit a permit application no later than 3 July, 1996 while those emitting more than 150 tpy has to submit an operating permit by 3 January, 1997.  
</ul>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
<center>
<a href="/map/buttonbar.map">
