<TITLE>Alert</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<H3>

UPDATE: Ohio's Title V Program

</H3>
<P>

The Ohio Environmental Protection Agency (OEPA) Title V Operating Permit Program is nearing its first "<B>call date</B>" of 30 November 1995.  Have you determined your facility's status?  If you have filed an Emissions Fee Report during 1995, you should have received a copy of the OEPA Title V software, STARShip, during September 1995.  If you did not receive a copy of the STARShip and you are a major source, your Title V application is still due by 1 October 1996 at the very latest and may be due by the end of this month.  Environmental Resources Management (ERM), Inc. has the staff available now to assist you in meeting your obligations.
<P><I><B> 
Summary of Significant Highlights of OEPA's Title V Operating Permit Program
</B></I><P>
<ul>
<li> OEPA received full final approval of its Title V Operating Permit Program (OAC 3745-77) on 1 October, 1995.  This starts the clock for the 90 day, 180 day, and one year submittal deadlines.
<p>
<li> OEPA is continuing to evaluate the United States Environmental Protection Agency's (USEPA) 10 July 1995 memorandum titled "White Paper for Streamlined Development of Part 70 Permit Applications".  This important document provides guidance from USEPA to the state regulators on ways to simplify and streamline the Title V permit application package.  OEPA has attempted to implement much of the USEPA guidance into Ohio's Title V program in order to make the Title V permit application process less burdensome to industry.
<p>
<li> OEPA has developed a list of Trivial Sources (as defined in OEPA Engineering Guide #62) by incorporating the guidance in the USEPA "White Paper" and input received from the regulated community.  A cautionary note - if an applicable requirement exists for an emissions unit, then that emissions unit can not be classified as an insignificant or trivial source.
<p>
<li> OEPA has made available the final version of the Title V permit application software, STARShip.  Copies have been mailed to facilities filing Title V Emission Fee Reports in 1995.  Additionally, two-day hands-on computer training is available on a first-come, first-serve basis.
<p>
</ul>
<B><I>How Can ERM Help at this Late Date?</I></B>
<ul>
<li> ERM is currently managing Title V projects for numerous clients in a wide variety of industries in Ohio and across the country.  We can help you assess your facility to formulate an approach that will lead to compliance with Title V in a cost effective and expedient manner.
<p>
<li> ERM has the capabilities to perform a turnkey Title V project, or we can be involved only in those areas where you specifically need assistance.  If you need assistance with Title V or other environmental challenges, either use the attached fax sheet or call Jeff Ferg or Todd Trowbridge at (614) 433-7900 in Columbus, Ohio.

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>
