Philadelphia, PA 19137</CENTER>
</H4>
<H4><A NAME="introduction"></A><a name="introduction"><BR>
INTRODUCTION<HR></H2> The Title V/Part 70 Operating Permit program currently
being implemented by permitting agencies nationwide has made facility compliance
with air pollution regulations more challenging and information-intensive
than ever before. The structure and content of Title V permit applications
demands much more than an emissions inventory-focused view of facility air
emissions. Electronic information management for Title V permit development
and management now requires access to complex information, addressing aspects
such as: actual and potential emissions for regulated and state pollutants;
multiple Operating Scenarios for operational flexibility; tracking of operational
and emissions limitations; Applicable Requirements (and non-applicable requirements)
and methods of compliance; detailed operational and materials usage information;
and compliance demonstrations and reporting. In addition, the information
management system needs the ability to generate custom reports to match
the format and content of the state Title V application; and of convenient
report modification to meet changes in the application forms.<BR>
<BR>
This paper describes the implementation of a facility-customizable electronic
air information management system for Title V permit development and management.
The information management system, named A*I*M*S-Title V, is an electronic
database developed by ERM-Northeast and customized in this work to support
Title V permit development efforts for two separate Rohm and Haas Company
chemical manufacturing facilities located in Bristol, Pennsylvania (Bristol
Plant) and Philadelphia, Pennsylvania (Philadelphia Plant). The two facilities
had Title V permit application submission dates in November 1995, with the
application content for both facilities governed by the Commonwealth of
Pennsylvania's Title V Operating Permit Program. The A*I*M*S-Title V database
was customized for the Pennsylvania (PA) Title V program by ERM-Northeast
over the period June through August, 1995, following which the database
was implemented by the two facilities and supported the successful completion
and timely submission in November 1995 of their individual Title V applications.<BR>
<BR>
Subsequent sections of this paper provide a discussion of: the requirements
of an electronic information management system in order to adequately address
Title V permit development and management; the key aspects of the design
and development of the A*I*M*S-Title V database as a facility-customizable
permit development and management tool; and the customization of the database
to meet the PA Title V program structure. The implementation of the database
at the two Rohm and Haas facilities is then discussed, particularly with
regard to its contributions through the permit development process. The
facility commitment and investments required and the key experiences from
using an electronic database as a critical tool in the permit development
process and then subsequently as a &quot;permit manager&quot; are highlighted.
Finally, the continued development of the A*I*M*S-Title V database for other
facilities in several different states and some of the challenges currently
being addressed in that work are presented. <BR>
</H4>
<H4><CENTER><A HREF="#top"><IMG SRC="top.jpg" BORDER="0" WIDTH="34" HEIGHT=
"37" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER>
</H4>
<H4></BLOCKQUOTE><A NAME="requirements"></A>REQUIREMENTS OF A TITLE V DATABASE<HR></H2> An electronic information management system for Title V must meet a number of requirements dictated by the potentially broad scope of the Title V air permitting program. Firstly, it must be recognized that no single/static database design can directly match all of the various individual state and local implementations of the Federal Part 70 Operating Permit program. The significant differences that exist between the structure and content of the over 100 different Title V programs implemented (or being implemented) throughout the U.S. pose the single most challenging requirement of a Title V database, that of having a universally applicable, and yet flexible enough structure that can readily accommodate each of the different Title V programs. Perhaps more important is the need for the database design to be able to readily respond to the seemingly unavoidable changes in structure and content of almost every state's Title V program as it evolves in time.

Content Requirements
<HR>Although each of the individual Title V programs is in a sense unique, there are a number of common content requirements that can be identified and highlighted. These content requirements for an electronic Title V database are categorized and discussed below.

Facility Data and Application Description. Facility-related information, including ownership, location, SIC codes, other identifying features and details regarding the facility is universally required, although in varying degrees, in all Title V permit applications. The type of Title V permit application constituting each submission by the facility, such as initial application, administrative amendment, revision, or renewal, is also universally required and must consequently be tracked and logged by the database.

Air Equipment Data. A variety of potentially detailed information on individual air equipment within the facility may be required to be compiled and reported in the Title V permit including, but not limited to, air emission source equipment, control devices and exhaust points. The information required addresses areas such as current air permit numbers and details; attributes such as location, equipment make and model, stack height and building heights, and installation and operation dates; operational and maintenance information, and the relationship (pollutant flow stream) between individual air equipment. In addition to the commonly recognized air equipment types, some Title V programs also introduce other types of &quot;air equipment&quot; such as production areas, process lines, and fuel storage locations. These other &quot;air equipment&quot; types must then be integrated with the commonly recognized air equipment to address the Title V program structure. For example, an emissions-producing reactor in a process line may be required to be grouped with other emissions-producing equipment such as a storage tank and a distillation unit into the process line and then reported as emission units within this emission group, although emissions/operational limitations and applicable requirements may apply to individual emissions-producing equipment and must be reported in that context.

Materials Usage and Non-Air Waste Disposal. The characteristics of the raw materials used and their usage rates within the facility are frequently an integral component of the Title V program in many states. The relevance of materials characteristics and usage rates comes into the picture through routes such as VOC content limits on process materials (e.g., surface coatings), fuel parameter specifications (e.g., Sulfur content), and limitations on hourly or annual fuel usage. The presence of Federally-regulated Hazardous Air Pollutants (HAPs), as well as state-defined toxic air contaminants as constituents of process input materials may also need to be identified for the purposes of the Title V application in some states. Although, the need to report non-air waste disposal mechanisms in the Title V permit is relatively uncommon, the need for such a waste tracking mechanism may be necessary for pollutant mass balances and emissions estimation.

Air Emissions Data. Air emissions data are an obviously critical component of the Title V permit application, with the need to track and report actual and potential emissions on an hourly and an annual basis (generally) from each emissions-producing source equipment. These emissions from individual sources also frequently need to be summed for facility-wide emissions reporting. Further, some Title V programs require the grouping and reporting of emissions from source equipment by production areas or process lines. In addition, some Title V programs additionally require reporting of emissions by stack or fugitive exhaust (emission) point. The various types of potential reporting requirements imply that the database design for storing emissions data must be sufficiently robust to handle the manipulations necessary to meet the requisite reporting formats. 

Operational Flexibility. Most states' Title V programs attempt to alleviate the potentially severe restrictions on a facility's operational flexibility imposed in a Title V permit through the use of Alternative Operational Scenarios (AOS). These AOS introduce a hierarchical, pyramid-like structure quality into the Title V application, since each emissions-producing source must have the ability to have any number of operational modes defined as individual AOS. Each AOS will have its own unique emissions estimates; pollutant flow streams in terms of the control devices and exhaust points involved; operational limitations; applicable requirements; and compliance terms.

Applicable Requirements (ARs) and Compliance Terms. The ability to comprehensively, and at the same time, flexibly address applicable requirements and compliance terms is undoubtedly the most critical aspect of electronic information management for Title V permit development and management. Applicable requirements must be capable of being defined, tracked, and reported by the database in a number of different variations. Examples of different types of ARs include numerical emission limits from individual regulations or existing permit conditions, that must then be integrated with the emissions compilation and reporting modules; ARs that apply to individual pollutants; ARs with facility-wide applicability; ARs with a number of different components, such as recordkeeping, testing and monitoring (e.g., sections within sub-parts of NSPS regulations); and ARs that involve non-numerical emissions limitations such as limits on materials characteristics (e.g., VOC content limits), usage rates or operational restrictions. Applicable requirements must be intimately integrated with compliance methods or terms that the facility is required to or will otherwise use to demonstrate compliance with each AR. Both the ARs and compliance terms have timelines and other related compliance dates among their key characteristics. Finally, some ARs must be tracked as non-applicable requirements.

Compliance Status and Plans. For each AR, the compliance status must be compiled and reported in the Title V application, and plans must be provided for achieving compliance with each individual AR currently in non-compliance. The Title V permit also involves the submission of periodic reports to demonstrate compliance with individual ARs, and the submission of these reports must occur according at a frequency and timetable established by each AR. The electronic database must therefore, at a minimum, be capable of compiling the information required to prepare the corresponding components of the application. The ability to prepare compliance plan schedules based on inputs to the plans would be additionally beneficial as a permit management tool. 

Other Permitting Components. Many Title V applications also includes provisions for other air permitting components such as &quot;capping&quot; or synthetic minor status; emissions trading and &quot;bubbles&quot;; Emissions Reductions Credits (ERCs); and Discrete Emissions Reductions (DERs). The ability to integrate all of these components into the electronic database design would add to the versatility of the database. 

Output Requirements
<HR>A fundamental output requirement of the electronic Title V database is that it have the ability to be readily customized to generate hard-copy paper outputs, and in some cases, electronic data file outputs that match the content and format of the state's Title V application forms. This requirement is particularly challenging because each Title V program has a unique set of application forms, and to make it even more of a challenge, the forms in many states have changed several times (sometimes quite substantially) as the program has evolved and/or was finalized. 

Facility/User Requirements
<HR>An electronic database for Title V permit development and management must be responsive to the needs of the environmental management and operational users at a facility. A key to ensuring responsiveness is a database design and program flow that is intuitive to a user with an air permitting background and perspective. This implies that the database design and functions must be based on an air permitting framework and must not be centered around either the software or any particular state's Title V program structure. The air permitting needs and thought-process of the facility environmental staff should be the key driver in the design of the database - not the pre-conceptions of the database programmer or the limitations of individual database software. In other words, the facility users should drive the database design and not the other way around.

A good Title V database design will avoid having the user jump through hoops to implement the database at the facility. Since Title V permitting is typically one of many responsibilities of environmental staff at most facilities, the database design must recognize that users have a limited amount of time and resources that they can commit to making the database a productive tool. Thus, minimizing the learning curve required for the database must be a primary design goal. Cumbersome user interfaces and repetitive data entry situations must be avoided. A modular design that allows users to selectively use and tap the segments of the database that best suit their individual needs and responsibilities is also important. The more complex the database is or is perceived to be, the less the likelihood that environmental staff at typical facilities will commit the requisite investment to make it function effectively. A Title V database must be focused and goal-oriented - a database that attempts to do too much and is as a result overly complex will not be accepted and assimilated as it must be in order to meet its goal of electronically developing a Title V permit.

The electronic Title V database must also allow the facility with maximum flexibility in developing its Title V permit. Examples of facility flexibility options include provisions for tracking emissions-producing equipment while expressly excluding them from the Title V permit application; as well as hypothetical operating scenarios for &quot;what-if&quot; evaluations that are not to be reported in the Title V permit.

The ability to connect with and share data from other electronic databases already existing at a facility, such as a materials safety data sheet (MSDS) database or operational logs will additionally aid the acceptance of a Title V database. The database must also have the inherent ability to address, even if only partially in some cases, environmental requirements additional to Title V permitting, such as SARA reporting, annual air emissions statements, etc. Closely related to these goals is the ability of the database to function as a Title V permit management tool, from generating compliance schedules, to watching for New Source Review triggers, to assisting with the semi-annual compliance statements required in the Title V permit.

Perhaps most important from a facility perspective, the Title V database cannot be a static tool - it must be a living, dynamic entity just as the Title V permit. This requirement implies that the database must be capable of significant modifications and additions that can be made at the facility-level without necessarily requiring the services of a specialist software programmer. 

Finally, the database must provide the ability to assign varying levels of user privileges to the database, with security mechanisms to prevent inadvertent modifications to data and program components, as well as tampering by unauthorized users. 
</H4><H4><CENTER><A HREF="#top"><IMG SRC="top.jpg" BORDER="0" WIDTH="34"
HEIGHT="37" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALIGN=bottom></A><a name="design"></CENTER></H4><H4></BLOCKQUOTE><A
NAME="design"></A>A*I*M*S-Title V DATABASE DESIGN AND IMPLEMENTATION<HR></H2>The A*I*M*S-Title V database was developed by ERM-Northeast in response to the need for a facility-customized, electronic Title V permit development and management tool. The initial design of the database was driven by the key requirements discussed in the previous section of this paper, including the need for an air permitting based perspective to the database flow; responsiveness to facility and user needs; and the need for a universal yet flexible approach to address variations in Title V program structures and content requirements. The A*I*M*S-Title V database has some of its design origins in information management tools developed by ERM-Northeast over the last several years for site remediation, analytical information management, waste management, and storage tanks management. All of these tools have roots in facilitating facility environmental compliance and have undergone extensive facility exposure and testing. Additionally, these tools are characterized by their open architecture and their delivery to the facility as non-compiled software applications within their respective database software platforms. Each of these tools also emphasizes connectivity with other facility databases, and the site remediation database includes integration with a Geographic Information System (GIS) for graphical display and manipulations of database objects. Initial A*I*M*S-Title V database development was based on these databases through work conducted in-house and in customized applications for a U.S. Air Force base in Oklahoma and a large primary metals manufacturer in upstate New York. The A*I*M*S-Title V database has been designed as a application native to Microsoft Access( (Version 2.0), with an open architecture and relational database structure that is compatible with client-server database software such as Oracle, Microsoft SQL Server, and Sybase. Key database features include its delivery to a facility as a non-compiled application within Microsoft Access, providing maximum flexibility and opportunity for modifications to suit individual facility requirements. Microsoft Access( is a powerful, full-featured, and user-friendly PC-based database software package, and a member of the Microsoft Office( suite of applications for Windows 3.11 and Windows 95 operating systems. The Access environment permits import/export, connectivity, and cut-and-paste data transfer across multiple file formats and database engines including Excel, Lotus, ASCII text, dBase, FoxPro, Paradox, and other ODBC-databases. The A*I*M*S-Title V database can be customized with data tables, data entry forms and a suite of requisite output report templates that meet the initial needs of a facility and its Title V program requirements. As an non-compiled application within the Access( software environment, users can then readily add new tables, create new queries, and generate new custom reports to suit their evolving needs. Intimate knowledge of Access( is not, however, necessary for users to activate the customized database functions for which an intuitive user interface is provided. This approach to the database design addresses the key requirement of a user-friendly and dynamic database that is capable of evolving in time to meet changing user needs and requirements. Database Structure <HR>The A*I*M*S-Title V database utilizes a relational database design based on defining various types of database objects. These objects, named &quot;Air Objects&quot;, represent unique air permitting-related entities of relevance within the facility. Air Objects are typically those that are physically present at the facility, such as the Facility itself, Source Equipment; Control Equipment; and Emission Points. Air Objects are, however, not restricted to these types of commonly recognized objects and can include other physical and non-physical entities, as well as new user-defined objects. Each Air Object is uniquely characterized by several identifiers, including an Object Identifier Name; Object Type; and Inventory Year, and by its owner which is typically a Facility type Air Object for a particular Inventory Year. Through this structure, Title V information for multiple facilities and inventory years can be compiled within one database, although typically only one facility and inventory year may need to be stored in one copy of the database with other years archived or stored in different copies of the database. This design based on Air Objects in a relational database structure allows for universal applicability in a way that is not tied to any specific Title V program and can be readily adapted to a target Title V program. In a relational database, database records in individual tables are characterized by unique identifiers or &quot;keys&quot;. Based on these keys, different types of relationships, such as one-to-one and one-to-many, can be defined between corresponding fields in the records in different pairs of tables. These relationships then govern the order and nature of the data that can be placed in the various tables, and changes and deletions in one table can be easily updated throughout all tables containing related records. More importantly, using a relational database design allows information on individual Air Objects stored in different tables throughout the database to be easily found (queried) and reported. Thus, in the A*I*M*S-Title V database, information on the Applicable Requirements for an Air Object is stored in an Applicable Requirements table and is readily identified through the keys or identifiers of the Air Object which are used to tag each record in the table. Similarly, each record in the Compliance Methods table associated with a specific Applicable Requirement for a particular Air Object is tagged with not only the identifiers of the Air Object, but also the keys used to uniquely characterize each Applicable Requirement. This progression of relationships means that if a Compliance Methods report is required for the Air Object, it can be readily generated through a query of the Compliance Methods table by supplying the approach search criteria. This capability allows the database design to be universally compatible with different Title V programs (with minor modifications), and to be readily able to generate outputs that meet the layout and content of the various Title V application forms. Database Components <HR>Using the Air Object-based structure discussed previously, the database components address the following principal aspects: </BLOCKQUOTE>Descriptive Attributes of Air Objects, such as details of relevant facility characteristics; source equipment parameters; control device details; emission point information; as well as multiple record-type attributes such as control device efficiencies; Operating Conditions to represent multiple operational modes (scenarios) of individual source equipment Air Objects, tracking whether it is a primary or alternative operating scenario, the hours of operations, nature of operations, product or output generated, and materials usage rates; Emissions Streams linking the pollutant flow from source equipment through control devices to stack and fugitive emission points, that can be differentiated if necessary by a source's Operating Condition; Emissions Estimation module to estimate actual and potential, hourly and annual emissions by pollutant and by Operating Condition. Calculation methods include emission factors, operating and production parameters, materials usage and user-defined variables, and links to calculations in spreadsheets, together with information on calculation basis for each estimate; Applicable Requirements of Air Objects, tracked by Air Object and Operating Condition (for source equipment), and including the ability to track sub-sections of individual applicable requirements and their type (e.g., monitoring, recordkeeping, numerical emissions limitation, etc.), as well as rationale for determining applicability or non-applicability, and current compliance status. Numerical emissions limitations can also be viewed and entered through the Emissions Estimation module; Compliance Methods for each Air Object's defined Applicable Requirements, including detailed definitions of the type of compliance method, such as recordkeeping, reporting, workpractice, monitoring and testing, and their required schedules and frequency; Action Items for each Air Object, providing a means to track compliance-related and other needs and to enter compliance plans for non-compliant applicable requirements; Object Documents for each Air Object, providing a means of creating and embedding or linking to existing word processing, spreadsheets, CAD drawings, or other electronic files associated with the object. </UL>Data entry into these components is addressed using customized menus, intuitive forms, and event-driven functions. The database also includes the following lookup resource modules to assist in the data entry phase of Title V permit development: </BLOCKQUOTE>Chemicals reference list of over 600 pollutants, including names, regulatory applicability by Clean Air Act section and EPCRA/SARA, and limited chemical and physical property data; Materials Composition, for defining materials used and created (blended on-site) and characterizing their composition, either by direct input of composition data or through calculations based on blend fractions; Applicable Requirements, including descriptive information that is not specific to a particular source or emissions unit; Other lookup resource modules, including facility contacts, locations, and standard and alternative units of measure </UL>Information stored in lookup tables or resources is available for use throughout other parts of the database during data entry and can be continually updated to minimize repetitive data entry. Database Outputs <HR>Database outputs include a suite of template reports, including: </BLOCKQUOTE>Air Object Reports, which serve to mimic the data entry forms, and report information that has been input for each Air Object; Emission Inventory reports, providing tabulated emissions by pollutant, HAPs pollutants, and Title V fee pollutants, by facility and inventory year; &quot;What-If&quot; emissions comparisons, across Operating Conditions to determine maximum emission operating scenarios by pollutant; Applicable Requirements, Compliance, and Action Item reports of information entered by Air Object in the database; Permit Reports, which are customized to the particular state's Title V application forms. The Permit Reports can be accessed through a menu which lists the Title V application forms by section in accordance with the state's requirements. </UL>In addition to these template reports, the non-compiled nature of the database allows facility users to create new reports based on database tables and customized queries. Existing template queries can also be readily modified by users (with the requisite privileges assigned by the facility database administrator) to address circumstances such as minor (or even major) changes in the state Title V application forms. 
</H4><H4><CENTER><A HREF="#top"><IMG SRC="top.jpg" BORDER="0" WIDTH="34"
HEIGHT="37" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALIGN=bottom></A><a name="customization"></CENTER></H4><H4></BLOCKQUOTE><A
NAME="customization"></A>PA CUSTOMIZATION AND FACILITY IMPLEMENTATION<HR></H2>The Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection's (PA DEP) Title V Permit Application forms follow the general outline of Title V topics discussed previously, with a few key differences and additions. The PA program retained its existing new point source permit-to-construct structure (called &quot;Plan Approval&quot;) separate from the Title V application forms. Customization of the A*I*M*S-Title V database for the Rohm and Haas, Pennsylvania facilities consisted of three parts: (1) Structural changes and additions to meet the PA program and the unique air permitting needs of the two Rohm and Haas facilities; (2) Information content additions; and (3) Template reports to match each requisite section of the PA Title V application. In general, the PA Title V program structure was readily compatible with the Air Object-based structure of the database discussed previously. Several aspects of the PA Title V program structure of relevance to the customization included: </BLOCKQUOTE>Differentiation between Combustion and Process type emissions sources, with a somewhat different set of information requirements for each type; Tracking of Processing Steps for Process type emissions sources; Applicable Requirements reporting forms that did not need to be specifically &quot;speciated&quot;, by type of requirement (i.e., monitoring, emissions limit, etc.); &quot;Fuel Material Location&quot; module to track storage locations of fuel materials; &quot;Source Group&quot; module to track the grouping of emissions sources with common applicable requirements </UL>Several structural and content changes were also made to the database to reflect facility-specific needs. These changes included an option to disallow specific emission sources from being reported on the permit application; changes in data field types to allow greater flexibility in data inputs allowed; and provision of additional comment fields for internal facility purposes. Options to maximize flexibility in the facility's Title V permit were also included. For example, the Raw Materials Used information requirement for a Process type emissions sources can be filled either from materials usage data supplied for the source or entered generically by the user to preserve maximum permit flexibility. Facility Backgrounds and Title V Planning <HR>The Rohm and Haas Bristol Site is a diverse chemical manufacturing plant with a variety of continuous and batch type processes. Annual production is approximately 750 million pounds and is represented by over 800 products. In general, the plant specializes in various acrylate polymerization reactions to produce products such as emulsions, plastics, coatings, and resins. Adding to the complexity of the Bristol site, the facility contains three production areas, a utilities area (Powerhouse and Waste Water Treatment), a Research and Development facility, and a contiguous plant (also owned by Rohm and Haas). The Pennsylvania Title V regulations exempt R&amp;D facilities from Title V permitting, but its potential emissions must be aggregated with manufacturing to determine applicability. By comparison, the Rohm and Haas Philadelphia Site is smaller than the Bristol Site. The Philadelphia facility manufactures specialty chemicals for industry, water treatment, and agricultural use with an annual production of approximately one-tenth that of the Bristol plant. The Philadelphia facility contains seven diverse production buildings, a Powerhouse and a Wastewater Neutralization facility. Each facility formed a Title V team which had a team leader and a technical representative from each operating area of the plant as well as from Bristol's contiguous plant. The team worked on compiling the emission inventory, developing compliance strategies, performing compliance audits, and completing the Title V application forms. A consultant was hired to compile the list of applicable requirements for the site. The two team leaders worked closely so that strategies and methodologies were consistent between the two facilities. In 1994, each facility was subject to Pennsylvania's Reasonably Available Control Technology (RACT) rules for VOCs and NOx. In preparation for submitting a RACT proposal, the plant developed a complete emissions inventory for VOCs and NOx. When it came time for Title V, the emission inventory used for RACT was expanded to include all other Title V regulated compounds. All of the RACT work was done using Excel(r) spreadsheets. The Bristol plant has on the order of 300 emission units, control devices and emission points and has 25 operating permits for those sources. The Philadelphia Plant has approximately 100 emission points with 10 operating permits for those sources. The Bristol Plant also has approximately 150 applicable requirements; the Philadelphia Plant has approximately 100 applicable requirements. The Philadelphia plant's regulatory requirements do not, however, reduce proportionately with size because the site has additional regulatory requirements from a local county agency, Air Management Services. Although both facilities had made use of the database features of the Excel spreadsheets for the RACT work, it became evident that a relational database was needed for Title V. Rohm and Haas reviewed a variety of commercially-available candidate databases for air compliance purposes, as well as the possibility of in-house database development. The criteria for the database selection included: </BLOCKQUOTE>Ability to fill out Title V Application forms directly from database; Compatibility with existing emission inventory and applicable requirement spreadsheets; Ability to act as the foundation for all air compliance issues, including Title V, SARA 313, Annual Air Emission Reporting, Annual Air Emission Fees, New Source Review, Plan Approval Program, and RACT; Cost and intuitiveness of use. </UL>A*I*M*S-Title V Database Implementation<HR>The Philadelphia and Bristol Plants jointly decided to implement a customized version of the A*I*M*S-Title V database because it met the first two selection criteria and had the potential to aid in the management of all air compliance programs. In preparation for implementation, all of the potential Rohm and Haas users of the database completed an 8-hour Microsoft Access training class and were trained on the actual A*I*M*S-Title V database for 4 hours. At the Bristol Plant, the database was populated by the team leader and corrections and modifications were made by all of the team members. This led to value-added application generation since the completed Title V Application numbered a total of 1,500 pages. Technical personnel's time was spent collecting, estimating, and documenting pertinent air compliance data without having to proof-read typed application forms. At the Philadelphia Plant, the database was populated, corrected, and modified by all team members including the team leader. The Philadelphia Plant's Title V application was approximately 750 pages in length. Experiences<HR>The implementation of a database for Title V and for future air compliance made the task of filling out the voluminous application forms a breeze. The database allowed our Title V effort to become more focused on our compliance strategies and operational flexibility. It has also paved the way for time and cost savings in preparing annual emission inventories, SARA 313 air emission compilation, and annual emission fees for reporting year 1995. When it comes time to update and amend our Title V application, the database will be invaluable again. Also, the Bristol Title V team will continue working through 1996 with the objectives of utilizing the database for compliance tracking, New Source Review, and the Pennsylvania Plan Approval process. At the Philadelphia Plant, the database was implemented in time to provide an audit tool for Compliance Certification. Audit forms including all applicable requirements, and their related Methods of Compliance were easily generated from the flexible A*I*M*S-Title V database. Certification of compliance was therefore completed by the facility with a high degree of confidence. 
</H4><H4><CENTER><A HREF="#top"><IMG SRC="top.jpg" BORDER="0" WIDTH="34"
HEIGHT="37" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALIGN=bottom></A><a name="challenges"></CENTER></H4><H4></BLOCKQUOTE><A
NAME="challenges"></A>ONGOING WORK AND CHALLENGES<HR></H2>The A*I*M*S-Title V database is a dynamic entity which is continuing to evolve through continued development by ERM, as well as within the two Rohm and Haas facilities. Ongoing work at ERM on the database is focused on the enhancement of its capabilities and customization for facilities located in several other states, and addressing the Title V programs of the Jefferson County Air Pollution Control District in Kentucky, the State of Oklahoma, and the State of New York. There are a number of challenges being addressed currently in ongoing work: </BLOCKQUOTE>Enhancing the Applicable Requirements module to create as close an electronic equivalent as possible to a human air permitting thought-process; Establishing an automated link between the database's Emission Calculations module and calculations performed in spreadsheets external to the database; Creating a fully-featured Permit Manager module that allows expanded access to compliance schedules, action items and other permit management-related functions during the life of the Title V permit; and Integrating the database with other electronic environmental and air quality management tools, such as dispersion modeling programs, GIS-based visualization tools, and environmental compliance software such as ERM's Lotus Notes-based Environmental Quality Manager (EQM). </H4><H4><CENTER><A HREF="#top"><IMG SRC=
"top.jpg" BORDER="0" WIDTH="34" HEIGHT="37" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALIGN=bottom></A><a name="conclusion"></CENTER></H4><H4></UL></BLOCKQUOTE><A
NAME="conclusion"></A>CONCLUSIONS<HR></H2>A truly functional facility-based, electronic Title V permit development and management tool must meet a number of requirements, including a flexible and adaptable structure, air permitting-based intuitiveness of use, and the ability to be easily customized and modified at the facility level. The A*I*M*S-Title V database has been developed to address these requirements, and its implementation at two Rohm and Haas facilities is described in this paper. As the experiences described in this paper demonstrate, the database has provided significant benefits to the facilities during the course of permit development, with respect to both time and expense as well as in decreasing the tediousness of the associated tasks. The dynamic nature of the Title V permit also enhances the value of the database as a permit management tool through the life of the permit. Considering the net benefits, the implementation of the database has been well-worth both facilities' investments in time and resources. </BLOCKQUOTE><b>ACKNOWLEDGMENTS</b><HR></H2>The authors wish to acknowledge the contributions of Mr. C. Rozumalski and Mr. D. Sidorenko of ERM-Northeast in the development of the database, as well as in the prior work conducted for other facilities and projects that cumulatively benefited this project. A*I*M*S-Title V is a trademark of ERM-Northeast, Inc., and the A*I*M*S-Title V database is copyrighted by ERM-Northeast, with all rights reserved. All other trademarks referred to in this paper are the property of their respective owners. 96-TA33A.07 
</H4><H4><CENTER><A HREF="#top"><IMG SRC="top.jpg" BORDER="0" WIDTH="34"
HEIGHT="37" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3" ALIGN=bottom></A></CENTER></H4><H4></BLOCKQUOTE></H4></BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
