<TITLE>Asia/Pacific Operations continued</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Martin Schamis,  2-Aug-1996 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<H2>Asia/Pacific Operations</H2>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/jpeg/asia2.jpg"></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><KBD> Australia Posts Gains</KBD></B><P>

In Australia, ERM Mitchell McCotter has a very strong position in the market and posted a 28 percent increase in revenues for the 1996 fiscal year over the prior year.  It opened an office in Melbourne, bringing the total to six locations across the continent.  ERM's Australian staff of approximately 100 handles not only traditional environmental consulting and engineering, but also archeological surveys, community relations, traffic and transport studies, town planning, rail studies, acoustics, even investigations of flora and fauna.  The client base is similarly broad.  In addition to local and multinational industry,  ERM Mitchell McCotter performs assignments for Australia's coal, steel, mining and forestry industries as well as for national, state and local governments.<P>
During the 1996 fiscal year, concerns for the safety of tens of thousands of people led to ERM being asked to study a plan to minimize flooding associated with the Warragamba Dam, which supplies Sydney's water.  ERM's groundbreaking environmental impact statement used innovative public consultation strategies and new kinds of analyses which related intangible ecological impacts to tangible economic benefits offered by flood mitigation.<P>
Another assignment initiated during the year examined the effects of an expansion of one of the largest coal loading terminals in the world, located north of Sydney in the city of Newcastle.  The study evaluated many factors: contaminated land, harbor dredging, acoustics, air quality, traffic patterns and community relations. For Australia's Federal Airports Corporation, ERM was asked to estimate future noise levels and recommend flight planning guidelines at the Brisbane International Airport, which is surrounded by heavily populated residential neighborhoods.<P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
