<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>European Operations continued</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Martin Schamis,  2-Aug-1996 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/jpeg/europe2.jpg"></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B><KBD> EMAS Certification</KBD></B><P>
The exact nature of assignments varies from country to country.  In Germany, corporate clients are eager to institute environmental management systems.  Of the 200 companies that had applied for EMAS certification by early 1996, about 180 were from Germany.  To meet this demand, ERM created "Dynamic Certification",  a service which offers companies the support required to obtain EMAS certification in only six months, compared to the average time in Germany of nine months.<P>
In Italy, health and safety concerns have been highlighted by a new law that requires companies to have long
term plans in place to protect workers.  ERM's Italian offices are working with industrial clients on these plans, as well as on typical due diligence and compliance audits.  The company has a number of substantial contracts for soil and groundwater remediation, and three site assessments for the U.S. Navy.  During fiscal year 1996, ERM Italy, which has offices in Rome and Milan, also was asked to verify the environmental annual reports of Montedison &#139; the largest private Italian chemical company &#139; and AGIP Petroli.<P>
ERM has grown steadily in France since the Paris office was established in early 1994.  It now supplies a full range of auditing, planning, permitting and waste management services.  Through the ERM network and its own local contacts, the Paris office has attracted as clients some of the world's most prestigious corporations &#139; Procter and Gamble, Kimberly-Clark,  Schlumberger and Conoco, among others. <P>
In the U.K., ERM was cited as the top multi-service environmental consultancy in an independent market survey carried out by Environmental Data Services Ltd., a respected independent publishing company.  ERM's U.K. offices handle a full range of environmental assessments and planning, environmental health and safety (EHS) property transfer audits, site investigations and remediation, and pollution control work.  They now also have assignments developing health and safety management systems, training packages and installation of environmental software for clients in the U.K. and overseas, often working with other ERM offices.  The U.K. practice is very active with the developers of environmental policy, bringing the needs of industry and commerce firmly into the picture so that pragmatic and workable solutions can be found to environmental problems.<P><BR>
<B><KBD> Technical Studies</KBD></B><P>
The growing emphasis on economic factors in the environmental arena generated many contracts during the 1996 fiscal year for studies involving life cycle analysis, cost-benefit evaluations, project appraisals, and assessments of value anticipated from environmental investments.  The U.K. Department of Trade and Industry, for instance, commissioned a study that evaluated the potential effects of proposed legislation concerning volatile organic compounds (VOCs) on various industries.  For a lighting manufacturer, ERM performed detailed technical work and life cycle analyses to define which products qualified for special labeling under the European Union's eco-labeling directive.  At the end of the fiscal year, a new practice dedicated to Life Cycle Analysis was formed in the U.K.<P>
In recent years, severe droughts have created a water shortage of crisis proportions for much of the industry in the U.K.  ERM was hired during the year by several companies to find ways of recycling, reducing water use, and improving treatment of wastewater in order to gain relief from escalating water prices and plummeting supply.  In the north of England, ERM's EnviroClean group tackled the remediation of a former landfill at Sun Lane, introducing a reed bed filtration system to treat the leachate prior to discharge to the adjacent watercourse.  Recent legislation governing contaminated land is expected to boost remedial work throughout the U.K.<P><BR>
<B><KBD> EMS Breakthrough </KBD></B><P>
Fiscal year 1996 was a breakthrough year for environmental management systems (EMS).  With EMAS taking effect during 1995 and ISO 14000 in 1996, clients began devoting serious resources to implementing EMS throughout their organizations.  During the year, ERM carried out a detailed analysis of existing management systems compared to the requirements of EMAS at four facilities owned by a global petrochemical company in Europe. The resulting action plan enabled the company's plant in the Netherlands to become one of the first sites in Europe to be registered under EMAS. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
