<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>North American Operations continued</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Martin Schamis,  2-Aug-1996 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/jpeg/northam3.jpg"></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE> 
<B><KBD> Changing Market</KBD></B><P>
The environmental engineering and consulting field in the U.S. has changed substantially over the last five years, with the explosive growth rates of the 1980s slowing to less than three percent a year.  The market drivers are shifting from regulations to economic considerations.  This means that ERM's success in the U.S. will depend on its ability to deliver targeted services that improve a company's bottom line.<P>
Traditional services such as site remediation and air and water quality remain strong.  ERM also is very active in a number of emerging specialties, including risk-based corrective action, brownfields, and development of environmental management systems.  Other new products and services, such as patented technology, RCRA Part B Permit renewals, EHS training and litigation support also are making significant contributions.  For instance, ERM opened a 15,000-square foot safety training center in Alsip, Illinois, which offers hands-on training in emergency response, confined space entry and technical rescue training under controlled, simulated conditions &#139; a highly effective alternative to classroom sessions.<P>
During the 1996 fiscal year, the remediation market moved further away from studies to actual cleanups, generating substantial revenues.  In Houston, Texas, for instance, quick response was needed when old oil was discovered bubbling up under a school just before the school was scheduled to reopen for the fall semester.  ERM was brought in to investigate and recommend a remedial plan under the Texas Risk Reduction Rules, which attempts to link cleanup standards to a site's future use.  In the Rocky Mountain region, ERM serves many clients in the transportation sector, helping them achieve cost-effective remediation at major airports, including Denver's Stapleton International Airport.<P>
Several brownfields projects took shape during the year.  ERM's Boston office is working with  others to transform an abandoned petroleum refinery into a liquefied natural gas distribution facility employing hundreds of workers in Trinidad, West Indies. In California, ERM is working with Southern Pacific Railroad on a long-term project to turn 240 acres of contaminated land into a mixed use extension of downtown Sacramento.  ERM's  Houston office helped the city of Houston win a grant from the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (USEPA) to assess how to handle the city's large number of brownfields sites.<P>
ERM also is completing major remediation of a Superfund site in Denver.  While this effort started before the formal announcement of the brownfields program by USEPA, site activities are following the approach of the brownfields initiative and site agreements include the only known covenant "not to sue" at any brownfields project in the U.S.<P>
A major beneficiary of brownfields initiatives and of the trend toward risk-based cleanups is ERM Enviro
Clean, which has ten offices throughout the U.S. and posted a 13 percent increase in revenues in FY96. It specializes in environmental construction and in operations and maintenance projects such as industrial wastewater treatment plants. <P>
EnviroClean designed and installed a unique vacuum sewer system; completed a $2 million landfill cap repair in four months under a design/build contract with a major waste disposal company; and constructed a groundwater treatment system with a 4,800-foot deep well at a Superfund site in Gary, Indiana.<P>
ERM Program Management Company (PMC), which represents one of the largest segments of ERM revenues in the U.S., solves hazardous or radioactive waste problems for federal agencies.  Established in 1990, PMC earned a place as number 260 on <I>Inc.</I> magazine's list of America's 500 fastest-growing companies last year.  Also, PMC won a five-year, $20 million contract from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers to provide remedial investigation, permitting and installation for the Army's environmental restoration program in seven states. <P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
