<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>North American Operations continued</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Martin Schamis,  2-Aug-1996 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<CENTER><IMG SRC="/jpeg/northam2.jpg"></CENTER>
<BLOCKQUOTE> 

PMC focuses exclusively on federal agencies, but they are served by other offices, too. ERM's Walnut Creek, California, office, for example, won a five-year, $50 million contract last
year from the Department of Defense to provide technical services to the National Guard in nine states.  ERM's Woodbury, New York, office provided more than $1.5 million worth of site remediation services to the Department of Energy's Brook-haven National Laboratory.<P>
Local government agencies can 
be members of the regulated community as well.  Hillsborough County and the city of Tampa, Florida, for instance, may realize a significant savings in closure costs on a municipal landfill Superfund site because ERM's Tampa office successfully proved to USEPA that the landfill was
not responsible for contamination nearby.  And ERM also won a 
$30 million, three-year contract in FY96 to help clean up sites owned by the Metro Dade Transit Authority in Florida.<P>
<BR>
<B><KBD>Air Services Expand</KBD></B><P>
Air quality services remained a strong business for ERM, adding risk analysis and process safety management to established services such as new source reviews and permitting.  ERM obtained Title V permits for many corporations and for major universities.  At a large chemical manufacturing plant, ERM sampled and analyzed more than 90 waste streams to determine whether existing control systems met new regulations governing air emissions from wastewater. <P>
ERM sharpened its technological 
edge considerably during the year. 
A patent was granted for the Advanced Fluidized Composting (AFCSM) system, and the first two
full-scale installations were launched in Trenton, New Jersey, and Wawa, Pennsylvania.  The AFC process transforms high-strength wastewater or organic sludge into carbon dioxide and water, reducing the volume of sludge by 95 percent and making AFC a cost-effective alternative to other types of treatment such as incineration.<P>
<BR>
<B><KBD> Meeting Goals </KBD></B><P>
ERM is working with an increasing number of clients to establish corporate environmental management systems, which can help meet the goals of environmental stewardship and regulatory compliance more cost
effectively than traditional programs.  One tool available through ERM is Environmental Quality Manager (EQM), an action-oriented software package that organizes every regulatory requirement into a series of tasks that can then be scheduled and monitored. <P>
Companies in the U.S. are always looking for ways to improve environmental performance.  The Gillette Company, for instance, worked with ERM's Boston office to win a grant from USEPA's Environmental Leadership Program during the past year.  The experiment will allow Gillette to create an auditing program that relies on independent, third-party certification and could eventually point the way toward greater self-regulation for industry. 
</BLOCKQUOTE>
