<HTML>
<TITLE>Paper Nightmare, Software FIX</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#005B52" VLINK="#0D50A2" ALINK="#FFFFFF">

<H3><i>Waste Managment</i></H3>
	<BR>
<H1><KBD>PAPER NIGHTMARE, SOFTWARE FIX</KBD></H1>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<B>Now is the time to computerize air compliance management. Or suffer. 
 </B>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
</FONT>
By Donna Engelgau
<p>

<FONT SIZE=20>I</FONT>magine a reporting program for 
air emission sources and their regulatory requirements so extensive and complex that industry officials have said there won't be enough qualified personnel in the country to implement the program once all the various reports are received.
<p>
You don't have to imagine it. You've got it. It's called Title V.
<p>
Now imagine an electronic system that keeps track of a facility's air emissions sources, automatically tabulates and compiles the information required to prepare a Title V application, and then remits a report for the regulating body to review-as close to signed, sealed and delivered as one could hope for.
<p>
Fortunately, you don't have to imagine that, either.
<p>
That was not the case just a short time ago, given that the federal Clean Air Act Amendments (CAAA) of 1990 made facility compliance with air pollution regulations more challenging and information-intensive than ever before. 
<p>
After all, Title V permits not only cover every emission source at a plant, they also set minimum compliance standards, periodic compliance certification and record-keeping and reporting requirements. This is the first time that many sites fall under the rubric of the CAAA, not to mention that many facilities that previously were grandfathered out of state and local permit requirements are now required to obtain the new CAAA permits.
<p>
The mere thought of undertaking this task, which will require the collection and maintenance of reams of emissions and compliance data, has caused many industry groups, as well as state and local agencies, to call Title V a "paperwork nightmare"-one that's tremendously time-consuming and likely to put a dent in the bottom line. Such a nightmare, 
in fact, that industry officials have often said that there aren't enough qualified professionals to handle it.
<p>
When one considers that the law regulates approximately 50,000 industrial facilities, the consequences of sheer volume seem daunting indeed. "Air used to be something you got a permit for and it was good for life," says R. Mukund, Ph.D., project manager in the air consulting practice at Environmental Resources Management (ERM) in Albany, NY. "But now that's over. Air is probably one of the most complex media in terms of regulation, especially with Title V."
<p>
While many companies have tackled the job by putting more pencils to paper, others are beginning to rely upon another workhorse altogether: software systems that track air emissions sources and their compliance requirements, tabulate the data and place them in the correct forms for federal, state and local review.
<p>
"The implementation of a database for Title V and for future air compliance has made the task of filling out the voluminous application forms fairly easy, allowing more time to devote to compliance issues and the actual permit content," reports Suzanne Verzilli, assistant environmental manager with Rohm & Haas in Bristol, PA, in a paper to be presented at the annual meeting of the Air & Waste Management Association in Nashville, TN, this month. The paper, co-written by Jennifer McIntyre, an environmental engineer with Rohm & Haas in Philadelphia, and ERM's Mukund, is titled "Implementing a Facility-Customized Air 
Information Management System for Title V Permit Development and Management (A*I*M*S-Title V): Practical Experiences."
<p>
Environmental managers increasingly will come to rely upon database systems, never to return to their old methods, predicts Verzilli. "It's a definite trend for environmental systems," she says, as companies begin to focus on compliance rather than on the mechanics of the permit. 
<p>
Of course, there's no one-size-fits-all database management system. However, from Verzilli's point of view, now is the time to computerize for air compliance management. "Even though Title V may not be the impetus for getting into the computer age, it's certainly a good starting point," she says. "Unless you use an electronic database, Title V is going to be harder to handle than in the past."
<p>
While it's premature to say how much the database will save the company-it's been in use only nine months-Verzilli says it has eliminated "the middle piece of work, where 
you're manually transferring data 
from one place to another."
<p>
McIntyre says the customized A*I*M*S-Title V database the Philadelphia and Bristol plants now use, which was developed by ERM in Albany, is "an invaluable tool for someone who's in charge of compliance. It develops reports fairly easily."
<p>
That's critical for Rohm & Haas's Philadelphia and Bristol facilities, which manufacture specialty chemicals for industry, water treatment and agricultural use. Both facilities submitted their Title V applications using the database last November.
<p>
"We have 100 or so applicable requirements, and each has to have a method of compliance tied to it," says McIntyre, who has further tailored the database to suit her facility's needs. "The problem we've had in the past is keeping track of 
all that."
<p>
Because of the success so far, McIntyre intends to expand the use of the database this year to include annual emissions reporting-a chore that previously would have required facility managers to tabulate their own data-and for permit maintenance and auditing, since the software can generate customized audit forms.
<p>
The number of off-the-shelf environmental software products has been growing at a rapid rate since the early 1990s. Today there are approximately 2,200 such programs on the market, of which perhaps as many as 500 are for air quality-relatedapplications, according to Scott M. Johnson, planning manager for the Ventura County (CA) Air Pollution Control District and the author of the 1996 Guide to Environmental Software Products, published by
the Air & Waste Management Association. Three years ago, Johnson's survey turned up only 600 environmental software programs.
<p> 
In the rapidly changing world of environmental information technology, choosing software can be frustrating and difficult. But some trends seem clear-such as the importance of sound databases. "It's tough to pin down what solution would be ideal for every company," says Johnson. "But integrated solutions are key, so you can use one core database for everything."
<p>
Tinker Air Force Base, which is one of the world's largest electroplating facilities and has more than 1,000 emissions units, has been assembling its Title V database for 18 months in preparation for the Part 70 permit application it must submit in two years. "Even though Tinker has permits on lots of things, they're starting now from ground zero," says ERM's Mukund, who is assisting the base with a customized version of A*I*M*S-Title V. "That way they can replace a motley collection of permits and information with an integrated, streamlined database." Before employing its new, more comprehensive software, Tinker had a program that monitored only health and safety emissions from the more than 10,000 chemicals and 500 different industrial processes it uses.
<p>
"The Title V permit is massive," says Geri Hart, supervisory environmental engineer with the Oklahoma City facility, which, among other things, paints and strips KC-135 and 
B-52 aircraft. "We're looking at going from 150 to 1,200 (regulated) sources. You can imagine the kinds of information that will have to be developed for those 1,200 sources. It's too much data to manage manually."
<p>
Complying with Title V is a huge undertaking for just about everyone affected, but as Rohm & Haas and Tinker Air Force Base have learned, the latest generation of electronic solutions can make the headaches just a little easier to bear. 
<P>
<center> <font size=2>Copyright&copy; 1996 ERM</font><br>
<img SRC="/gif/logo_erm.gif"><br>

<br clear=all> 
</center>

