<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace:Careers
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="../images/personal.gif">
<FONT SIZE=+1>Careers in CyberSpace are certainly no longer the stronghold of men.  Lots of women have entered -- and conquered -- this ever changing Cyber world.  Courtney Macavinta's feature story, kicking off WomenSpace's <B>Women on the Internet</B> series, highlights Camp's unique perspective on working in CyberSpace.
<center><IMG SRC="../images/ruleyl.gif" BORDER=0></center><BR>

<BR>
<P><B>by Courtney Macavinta</P></B>

<P><img align=left src="../images/scamp2.gif">Susanna Camp has opinions.  She broadcasts them because opinions are like a pulse, they prove one is alive.  Everyday Camp checks the world's vital signs via the Internet.  She listens to online conversations, puts in her two cents. She creates dialogue.  Breeding                                                                                                                                                    opinions is Camp's job.</P></FONT>
         <P>Camp is the senior producer of Piazza, the interactive soul of Hotwired, Wired magazine's online cousin. Once tucked in the back corner of Wired's San Francisco offices, Hotwired has evolved from a digital amoeba to the Bionic Woman in just over 18 months.</P>
<P>One of the most critically-claimed, sponsor-supported ezines, Hotwired was the first website to be A.C. Nielsen rated. It houses content-intensive channels such as Renaissance,  containing arts and entertainment reviews, previews and features; and, most recently Netizen, for online coverage of the 1996 election.
         <P>Having been at Hotwired for more than a year, Camp is a veteran netchick.  Hired as an editorial assistant, she now oversees Piazza, which contains Club Wired, a venue where live guests interact with Hotwired members; Rants & Raves, for consumer feedback; and Threads, a combination of bulletin board discussions and commentary.</P>
         <BLOCKQUOTE><P>Posting ideas in Threads is one of Camp's favorite diversions, but her work in Club Wired may trigger the most envy.  She coordinates guests and works with engineers to produce most of the online sessions, including real audio music performances.  Club Wired features political outlaws, authors, cybertheorists, musicians, film makers and various prophets are also featured in Club Wired. Icons of digital culture top the guest list, but there's always a variety. Cypress Hill, Laurie Anderson, Timothy Leary, Jaron Lanier, Malcolm McLaren, Douglas Coupland, Bruce Sterling and Joey Ramone have all stopped by the Club.</P>
<P>Camp, along with an assistant producer, coordinates, promotes, and moderates Piazza events. During a Club Wired session, the guest is introduced by a moderator, and interviewed by the audience. Later, the transcripts are archived.</P>
<P>Recently, real-audio sessions, such as band performances, were launched. Currently, you can enter the Club through a telnet window (the software is available from Hotwired's shareware toolkit .) According to Camp, an entirely web-based system will be implemented in about a month.</P>
         <P>Books and autographed pictures from Club Wired guests surround Camp's tiny domain, about 6 feet of Hotwired's floor space. As she sits propped up on her right foot, dangling her other leg below her, wearing jeans and sneakers 28-year-old Camp looks like a high school student. This is true of most of the company's twenty-something employees. Youth emits a sense of wisdom here. These people seem to be in the know. Camp is one of them.</P>
         <P>"They wanted someone who was smart and who knew about the Net," she says of people who interviewed her for the job.  "They wanted somebody who 'got it'- who understands that interactivity is it."</P>
        <P> She fits the criteria, but she didn't always.  After graduating in 1989 with a degree in English from a small liberal arts college in Massachusetts, Camp admits that she had little direction.  She bartended for a while, and took an eight-week publishing course at Harvard. What cost her a big chunk of change was really a Ivy League network-fest.</P>
	<P>"I had some offers in New York, but instead I came out here on a long shot," Camp says.</P>
<img align=left src="../images/camppull.gif" BORDER=0>         
<P>In San Francisco, she landed her first gig in publishing - a position in MacWorld magazine's circulation department.  Before long, she was a manager. However, spewing direct mail around the globe was not her idea of publishing. Without a job waiting in the wings, Camp left MacWorld.</P>
        <P>"I was getting promotions and rewards, but I had to ask myself 'Can I justify this?' You wake up and realize it's your life. I didn't want a career full of compromises, so I left."</P>       
<P>During her stint at a small Internet directory company,  running mail servers and configuring modems, Camp saw beyond her computer's opaque screen.  By picking engineers' brains, solving technical problems herself through trial and error, and subscribing to industry news letters, Camp broke out of her consumer role.  Turned on by her new relationship with technology, she sought a job that utilized all of her skills. She landed at Hotwired.</P>
        <P> "Now my job is something that I'm engaged in.  You have to go beyond getting involved. The whole medium is right there with you. You can think about the software, coding.. it's all transparent. All the tools are at your disposal," she says.</P>
         <P>Her favorite book to date, "Life on the Screen: Identity in the Age of the Internet," by Sherry Turkle may explain for others what she's been "getting" all along, she says. </P>
        <P>"'Life on the Screen helps you get a lot more about your relationship to computers," she says. "The interactive element (of the Internet) is how you learn."</P>
        <P> Camp breaks things down so they're simple. Her homepage is an example, "Things that make me think."  The indices are simple: words, bourbon, reading and music. Each section only contains a quote or short essay.</P>
         <P>On her site, she posted a definition of  the word "dialect."  The word seems to encompass why she  interacts on and off-line, why she thinks everyone should. She defines dialect as, "The art or practice of arriving at the truth by the exchange of logical arguments.... The contradiction between two conflicting forces viewed as the determining factor in their continuing interaction."</P>
         <P>Susanna Camp would be harvesting and offering opinions even if the Internet didn't exist.  She'd determine whether or not people were alive by what they had to say. "Conferencing is a good way to prove to yourself and everybody else that you're here and you count. It's really  important just to have an opinion."</P>
        <P>And so she does.</P></BLOCKQUOTE>

<center><IMG SRC="../images/ruleyl.gif" BORDER=0></center><BR>
<P><a href="mailto:courtney@sirius.com">Courtney Macavinta</a>, a free-lance writer based in San Francisco, currently works on the business end at Wired magazine.  Courtney has written for "The Net" magazine and NewType, an online magazine, and is a member of the California Chicano News Media Association.</P>
<center><IMG SRC="../images/ruleyl.gif" BORDER=0></center><BR>
<center>
<a href="../index.html"><IMG SRC="../images/wstool.gif" BORDER=0></a><BR>
<a href="personal.html"><IMG SRC="../images/gptool.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="../bodyshock/bodyshock.html"><IMG SRC="../images/bstool.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="../yogirls/yogirls.html"><IMG SRC="../images/ygtool.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="../grrlstore/grrlstore.html"><IMG SRC="../images/gstool.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="../hotlinx/hotlinx.html"><IMG SRC="../images/hltool.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="../archives.html"><IMG SRC="../images/arctool.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="../../twp/pharmacy.html"><IMG SRC="../images/twptool.gif" BORDER=0></center>

