<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace: Fitness
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<center><IMG SRC="../images/personal.gif" BORDER=0>
<P><FONT SIZE=+1>

<H1>Advice from Anthony</H1></center>
Kicking off WomenSpace's new fitness column, some general thoughts on working out and having fun.

<BR></FONT>
<center><IMG SRC="../images/ruleyl.gif" BORDER=0></center><BR>
<P>

<b>by Anthony Mercado
<BR><BLOCKQUOTE>
<p><img align=left src="../images/advice.gif">Why do we exercise?</b>  You can exercise to be stronger, have more endurance, train for a sport, lose weight, boost your self-esteem, or just to be healthy.  Because people exercise for different reasons, they are motivated to exercise in different ways; you can weight train at a health club, run in the park, rollerblade, or play an organized sport. But whatever you do, have fun doing it.  Exercise shouldn't be a chore; it should be part of your lifestyle. With that in mind, there are some things to think about when planning how and when you'll exercise.</p>

<p>Regular exercise reduces the risk of injury, heart disease, and osteoporosis (a disease that makes your bones thin and brittle as you get older.) It can help lift you mood and make you feel more energetic when you're not working out.</p>

<p>If you want to join a health club or gym but feel intimidated; take heart. Get a friend to join with you and become training partners.  Encourage each other to go to the gym and to work harder when you're there. Not only will a friend provide moral support, but will make your workout less boring.  And <B>never feel afraid to ask a trainer for advice</B>, whether it's to learn to use a new machine, or to find out if you're doing an exercise correctly-- that's what they're there for! It's a million times better to ask for help that to hurt yourself performing an exercise incorrectly.</p>

<p>It's very important to avoid exercising ONLY on weekends.  You can injure yourself by going all out and exercising only once or twice a week. Your body needs a day or two between intense workouts to rest and repair. Always space out your workout routine throughout the week-- that way you'll get all the benefits of exercising, and your body will thank you for it.</p><BR><BR>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<p><B>Check out next month's issue for some more advice from Anthony!</B></p>
<center><IMG SRC="../images/ruleyl.gif" BORDER=0></center><BR>
<p>Anthony Mercado, a dance choreographer and personal trainer, is A.C.E. and A.F.A.A. certified. He has taught master classes at health clubs nationwide, including Reebok, New York Sports, Equinox and Golds Gym. He can be contacted at: 189 19th Street, 1st Fl.; Brooklyn, NY 11232</p>
<p>For more on exercise and fitness in this issue, check out BodyShock's <a href="bodyshock/getfit.html">Staying Fit</a>, and WomenSpace's Sports Medicine Doc's <a href="topten.html">Top Ten</a> reasons to exercise.<BR>
<center><IMG SRC="../images/ruleyl.gif" BORDER=0></center><BR>
