<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace: Fitness
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<center><IMG SRC="../images/personal.gif" BORDER=0>
<P><FONT SIZE=+1>

<H1>Top Ten Reasons to Exercise</H1>
... that have nothing to do with "losing weight!"</center>

<BR></FONT>
<center><IMG SRC="../images/ruleyl.gif" BORDER=0></center><BR>
<P>

<b>by Dr. Joseph Bosco</b>
<BR><BLOCKQUOTE>
<p>There are plenty of reasons to exercise that have nothing to do with the typical reasons you hear  -- like "to lose weight" or "to look better."   Of course, these are great side effects from exercising -- but you may enjoy working out a little more if you felt less pressure "to lose weight."  Read my Top Ten reasons to exercise below and pat yourself on the back for doing all these other great things the next time you exercise!</p>

<p>
#1 - Exercise helps strengthen your heart muscle -- and a strong heart means it will last longer -- and so will you!</p>

<p>
#2 - Endorphins are released in your brain when you exercise which gives you a feeling of "euphoria" -- an all around great sensation that underscores the saying that "it's pretty hard to feel depressed when your exercising!"</p>

<p>
#3 - Exercise relieves mental and physical stress and tension.  Forty-five minutes of working out will relieve an entire day's worth of stress.
</p>

<p>
#4 - Your aerobic stamina increases when you exercise -- so that everyday activities like climbing stairs, shoveling snow and walking uphill become easier.
</p>

<p>
#5 - You can sink into a deeper sleep when you exercise regularly because you relieve excess tension that could otherwise make for fitful nights.
</p>

<p>
#6 - Exercise raises your base line metabolism so that you can actually eat more without worrying about putting on extra pounds.
</p>

<p>
#7 - Your peripheral muscles (in your arms and legs) strengthen with exercise so that you can easily do activities like carry groceries or kids without strain.
</p>

<p>
#8 - Exercise will help lower the levels of bad cholesterol in your body and actually increase the levels of good cholesterol -- making your chances of avoiding heart disease even better.
</p>

<p>
#9 - Your heart will beat more efficiently with regular exercise which will help you in combating high blood pressure later in life.
</p>

<p>
#10 - Exercise involving moderate and even low impact helps your bones retain calcium reserves -- which aids in preventing osteoporosis.
</p>

<P>As you can see, there are plenty of reasons to exercise that have nothing to do with  "losing weight."  Consider exercise to be a means of feeling better, preventing disease, living longer -- and, of course, having fun!</P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>
<center><IMG SRC="../images/ruleyl.gif" BORDER=0></center><BR>
<p>Dr. Joseph Bosco is Assistant Professor of Orthopaedic Surgery at the Albert Einstein College Medicine and practices at Montefiore Medical Center in New York.</p>

<center><IMG SRC="../images/ruleyl.gif" BORDER=0></center><BR>
<center>
<a href="../index.html"><IMG SRC="../images/wstool.gif" BORDER=0></a><BR>
<a href="personal.html"><IMG SRC="../images/gptool.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="../bodyshock/bodyshock.html"><IMG SRC="../images/bstool.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="../yogirls/yogirls.html"><IMG SRC="../images/ygtool.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="../grrlstore/grrlstore.html"><IMG SRC="../images/gstool.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="../hotlinx/hotlinx.html"><IMG SRC="../images/hltool.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="../archives.html"><IMG SRC="../images/arctool.gif" BORDER=0></a>
<a href="../../twp/pharmacy.html"><IMG SRC="../images/twptool.gif" BORDER=0></center>

