<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace: Opinions Needed
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF">
<center><IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="../images//yogirl.gif"></center>
<FONT SIZE=+1> <BR>Send your responses to the following questions by email to Helen Cordes, the author of the upcoming book about girls and body image. 
<a href="mailto:hcordes@igc.apc.org">Click here</a> to email Helen -- and your answers could be featured in her book!
<BR><BR><BR> </FONT>

<BR><center><IMG SRC="../images/rulepk.gif"></center><BR>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><B>Question 1</B><BR>
Do you like the way you look -- your face and body size?  If you mostly -- or totally -- like your looks, how does that make you feel?  If you mostly don't like your looks, how does that make you feel?</P>
<P><B>Question 2</B><BR>
Do you think that other people (your friends and classmates, your family and relatives) like the way you look?  If yes, how does that make you feel?  If no, how does that make you feel?</P>
<P><B>Question 3</B><BR>
When you think about ways to look good, where do you get your ideas (from yourself, from friends, from magazines, or TV)?</P>
<P><B>Question 4</B><BR>
Do you worry much about not looking nice enough? If you think you spend too much time worrying about your looks and body size, what things do you do to stop worrying so much?</P>
<P><B>Question 5</B><BR>
Do you know girls who worry about the way they look? If so, do you think they worry too much?</P>
<P><B>Question 6</B><BR>
Do you diet or have you dieted? Would you say that your ideas about the kinds of things you eat and how much you eat are fairly normal? Or not?</P>
<P><B>Question 7</B><BR>
What do you think are the advantages of being thin and pretty?  What are the advantages?</P>
<P><B>Question 8</B><BR>
Think about two females that you like and respect -- one who is near your age and one who is a grown-up.  Why did you pick them?  What part, if any, do you think their looks played in helping them become the person you like?</P>
<P><B>Question 9</B><BR>
Do you feel that you pretty much do what you want with your body -- at home, or at school, or wherever?  For example, when I was young, I was often told to "act like a lady" -- when I really wanted to play games with the boys, talk loudly and be the first to answer questions in class.  Do you think this kind of attitude  still exists?  Do you ever encounter it?  If so, what do you do?  Do the same behavior rules apply to boys?</P>
<P><B>Question 10</B><BR>
Do you do activities such as hiking, dance, self-defense classes, or sports?  If so, did the activity help your confidence in physical and mental ways?</P>
<P><B>Question 11</B><BR>
How do you feel about the changes that are happening or about to happen with your body, like menstruation, bigger breasts and hips? Some girls say they like looking more like a woman; others feel a little mixed about it.  What about you?</P>
<P><B>Question 12</B><BR>
If you feel pretty OK about the changes that are happening to your body, what advice would you have for girls who are feeling pretty mixed up or scared?  Where did you find your confidence -- from family, or friends, or where?</P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P><a href="mailto:hcordes@igc.apc.org">Click here</a> to send your responses to these questions to Helen Cordes, the author of the upcoming book about girls and body image --  and your answers could be featured in her book!
</P>

<center><IMG SRC="../images/rulepk.gif"></center><BR><BR>
