<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace: STD Guide
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="DEA7D4">

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="daisystem2.gif">


<P><BR>
It's a cruel trick of nature that when it comes to <strong>sexually transmitted diseases</strong>, women very often get the worst end of the deal ...<P>


<P>First, STDs are more easily transmitted from a man to a woman rather than the other the other way around.  It's the mechanics of it all -- when a man and woman have sexual intercourse, the man deposits fluid into the woman's vagina.  If this fluid contains an STD, the woman is very likely to get it.  <P>
<P>
Secondly, many STDs are "asymptomatic" in women -- which means that you don't really know that you have it.  But if you don't know you have it, you probably don't know to get treatment for it either!   Unfortunately, many asymptomatic STDs can cause lots of health problems for women. <P>
<P>
All of this means that it is super crucial for women to know more about STDs.   Obviously, abstinence is the absolute best way to avoid most of of them  -- but a little education on how to spot 'em certainly doesn't hurt!  Take a look at the following STD guide and learn what some of the most common STDs look like on men and on women. <P>
<A NAME="10">
<a href="std.html#1>Chlamydia</a> <BR>
<a href="std.html#2>Genital Warts (HPV)</a><BR>
<a href="std.html#3>Gonorrhea</a><BR>
<a href="std.html#4>Herpes Simplex I</a><BR>
<a href="std.html#5>Herpes Simplex II</a><BR>
<a href="std.html#6>Human Immunodefiency Virus (HIV)</a><BR>
<a href="std.html#7>Syphilis</a><BR>
<a href="std.html#8>Trichimoniasis</a>

<HR><P>
<A NAME="1"><FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Chlamydia</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b>  Discharge from the penis, painful urination, redness around the tip of the penis. <P>
<b>Women:</b>  Can be asymptomatic for long periods of time;  may cause pain and cramping in the abdomen;  can result in serious damage -- even sterility if left untreated.<P>
<b>Avoid It:</b>  Use condoms because chlamydia is passed from a man to a woman in the man's semen.<P>
<BR><center><a href="std.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR><P>
<A NAME="2"><FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Genital Warts -- Human Papiloma Virus (HPV)</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b> Fleshy wart-like "bumps", either internal (inside the urethra or anus) or external (around the genitals or anus); can obstruct the urinary tract causing bleeding during or after urination.<P>
<b>Women:</b> Fleshy wart-like "bumps", either internal (inside the vagina) or external (around the genitals or anus); can obstruct the cervical opening if left untreated. <P>
<b>Avoid It:</b>  Always use condoms and avoid coming into contact with warts that may be in other areas on the man's body (around the anus and the genital area).<P><BR><center><a href="std.html#10">Back To STD List</a></center><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME="3"><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Gonorrhea</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b>  Discharge from the penis, painful urination, can lead to arthritis (inflammation in the joints).<P>
<b>Women:</b>  Vaginal discharge, abnormal periods.<P>
<b>Avoid It:</b> Use condoms!  Gonorrhea is passed from a man to a woman in the man's semen.<P>
<BR><center><a href="std.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR>
<A NAME="4">
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Herpes -- Simplex I</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b>  Red, crusty sore on the mouth area and lips, can be painful -- a "cold sore."  <P>
<b>Women:</b>  Same as in men.<P>
<b>Avoid It:</b>  Though Simplex I is usually found on the mouth area and lips, it can be spread to the genital area.  Therefore, if you or your partner has a Herpes Simplex I sore, kissing and oral sex should be avoided.
<P><BR><center><a href="std.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR>
<A NAME="5"><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Herpes -- Simplex II</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b>  Red, crusty sore in or around the genital areas, can be painful.  <P>
<b>Women:</b>  Same as in men.  <P>
<b>Avoid It:</b> Use condoms -- but don't forget that sometimes the sores can be in areas that the condoms won't cover.  Though Simplex II is usually found on the genital areas, it can be spread to the mouth and lip areas. Therefore, if you or your partner has a Herpes Simplex II sore, do not come into contact with the sore during oral sex.<P>
<BR><center><a href="std.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR>
<A NAME="6"><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Human Immunodefiency Virus (HIV)</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b> Usually asymptomatic for many years. <P>
<b>Women:</b> Same as in men.<P>
<b>Avoid It:</b>  Always use condoms -- even during oral or anal sex.  HIV can be passed through semen, vaginal fluids or blood. <P>
<BR><center><a href="std.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR>
<A NAME="7"><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Syphilis</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b> Painless, red,  sunken or "crater-like" sore the size of a dime;  usually found in the genital region.<P>
<b>Women:</b> Same as in men.  <P>
<b>Avoid It:</b>  Always use condoms -- even during oral or anal sex -- and avoid coming into contact with sores that may not be covered by the condom.<P>
<BR><center><a href="std.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR>
<A NAME="8"><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Trichomoniasis</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b>  Can be asymptomatic; or can have inflammation of the penis, and lesions in the genital area.<P>
<b>Women:</b>  Can be asymptomatic; or may have an bad smelling discharge from the vagina; redness, swelling or itching in the vaginal area. <P>
<b>Avoid It:</b>  Always use condoms!  <P>
<BR><center><a href="std.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR>
