<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace:Osteoporosis
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="DEA7D4"><BR>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="daisystem2.gif">
<FONT SIZE =+1>
<P>

<P>
The verdict is in -- it's never too early to take care of your bones!<BR><BR><BR><P> As women age, they slowly begin to loose calcium from their bones.  Over time, this leads to a weakening of your bones -- a process called <em>osteoporosis</em> (ah-ste-o-por-o-sis).

Both men and women loose around 1% of the calcium in their bones each year after the age of 40. Unfortunately, when women go through menopause, calcium loss speeds up to as much as 3-4% per year during the 4 or 5 years around the time of menopause.<P>
</FONT>
<P>So you may say, "What does this have to do with me now?" Glad you asked! There are lots of things you can do now to prevent this condition later on. <P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Excercise</strong></FONT><BR>
For instance, routine excercise will build and maintain healthly bones both now and in the future. Bones react to "stresses" from excercise by storing up calcium which makes them stronger. The more calcium your bones have now as a result of excercise, the more you'll have left over when you're older. <P>
<P>
<strong><em>Special Note:</em></strong>  Some women athletes who excercise strenuously often have a problem with amenorrhea (a-men-or-re-ah) -- which means that they stop having their periods. This can develop into a very serious situation because amenorrhea is caused by a lack of estrogen (eh-strah-jen)-- something your body really needs. In addition to lots of other good things, estrogen helps maintain adequate levels of calcium in your bones. Therefore, women with amenorrhea have a higher likelihood of getting osteoporosis.<P>

<FONT SIZE=+1><P><strong>Diet</strong><BR></FONT>
Excercise isn't the only way to develop strong bones and to prevent osteoporosis -- what you eat is also extremely important. Many doctors say that young women and girls should take in at least 1000 mg of calcium each day to maintain healthly bones. Elderly women and pregnant women need even more -- as much as 1500 mg. Unfortunately, most young women don't take in this amount each day.<P>
<P>
Track your diet for a few days to see if you are taking in at least 1000 mg of calcium. If you suspect that you're not getting enough, you should speak with your health care provider about taking a calcium supplement. First and foremost, though, you should try getting calcium the natural way -- through your diet.<P>
<P>
<strong><em>Special Note:</em></strong>  Sometimes the foods which are rich in calcium are also rich in fat. Some examples of these foods are cheeses, milk products, yogurts and even ice cream.  One solution to this dilemma is to buy these products in the Low-Fat or No-Fat variety. In general, moderation is the key when it comes to these foods.  Also  remember that in addition to dairy products, green, leafy vegetables can provide a great source of calcium.<P>
<P>
Here are some other foods that contain respectable amounts of calcium. <BR>
<UL>1/2 cup collard greens  --      180 mg<BR>
1 lb of fresh oysters  --     426 mg<BR>
3 oz. of salmon --     167 mg<BR>
1 cup of chopped dates --     105 mg<BR>
1 cup of orange wedges --    74 mg<BR>
1 cup of raisins --     90 mg<BR>
1 cup of rhubarb --     211 mg<BR>
1 slice of pumpernickel bread --     27 mg<BR></UL>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>The Bottomline</strong></FONT><BR>
Once you've lost the calcium in your bones it is nearly impossible to regain it. Thus it is extremely important to take steps now in order to prevent osteoporosis. A healthly diet and regular excercise not only will make you feel and look great now, it will ensure that you feel and look great later in life too!<P>
<HR>
