<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace: Same Sex STD Alert
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG SRC="images/wssmall.gif" BORDER=0><BR><HR>
<a href="personal.html">Back to Getting Personal Main Page</a> <BR><a href="index.html">WomenSpace</a> | <a href="bodshk.html">BodyShock</a> | <a href="yogirls.html">Yo! Girls</a> | <a href="grrlstore.html">The Grrl Store</a> | 
<a href="extra.html">Extra! Extra!</a> | <a href="hotlinx.html">Hot Linx</a><BR>
<a href="../twp/pharmacy.html">The Women's Pharmacy</a></center>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE =+1>
<P><CENTER>
<IMG SRC="images/pers.gif"><BR><BR>

<P><FONT SIZE=+1>
We've updated the STD Guide from the first version of WomenSpace to include some things that many of you pointed out were missing. </CENTER></FONT>
<center><H2>Same Sex STD Alert</H2></center>
<BR>In particular, several of you commented that STD's can be spread not just from men to women -- but also from women to women as well.  In other words, it's really important to know about how to protect yourself from sexually transmitted diseases even if your partner is the same sex as you.
<P>
Any STD which has symptoms that affect the skin -- like sores from herpes or syphilis or genital warts from HPV (Human Papilloma Virus) -- can be easily spread between same sex partners.  Also, STD's which are spread through body fluids like HIV are important to know about because they can be easily passed through vaginal fluids.</P>

<P>Take a look at our STD guide and keep in mind that even if your partner is the same sex as you, it is still important to know what these STD's look like in order to protect yourself. </P>
<A NAME="10">
<a href="samesex.html#1">Chlamydia</a> <BR>
<a href="samesex.html#2">Genital Warts (HPV)</a><BR>
<a href="samesex.html#3">Gonorrhea</a><BR>
<a href="samesex.html#4">Herpes Simplex I</a><BR>
<a href="samesex.html#5">Herpes Simplex II</a><BR>
<a href="samesex.html#6">Human Immunodefiency Virus (HIV)</a><BR>
<a href="samesex.html#7">Syphilis</a><BR>
<a href="samesex.html#8">Trichimoniasis</a>

<HR><P>
<A NAME="1"><FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Chlamydia</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b>  Discharge from the penis, painful urination, redness around the tip of the penis. <P>
<b>Women:</b>  Can be asymptomatic for long periods of time;  may cause pain and cramping in the abdomen;  can result in serious damage -- even sterility if left untreated.<P>
<b>Avoid It:</b>  Use condoms because chlamydia is passed from a man to a woman in the man's semen.  <P>
<BR><center><a href="samesex.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR><P>
<A NAME="2"><FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Genital Warts -- Human Papiloma Virus (HPV)</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b> Fleshy wart-like "bumps", either internal (inside the urethra or anus) or external (around the genitals or anus); can obstruct the urinary tract causing bleeding during or after urination.<P>
<b>Women:</b> Fleshy wart-like "bumps", either internal (inside the vagina) or external (around the genitals or anus); can obstruct the cervical opening if left untreated. <P>
<b>Avoid It:</b>  Always use condoms during sexual intercourse or dental dams during oral sex and avoid coming into contact with warts that may be in other areas on the man's or woman's body (around the anus and the genital area).<P><BR><center><a href="samesex.html#10">Back To STD List</a></center><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME="3"><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Gonorrhea</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b>  Discharge from the penis, painful urination, can lead to arthritis (inflammation in the joints).<P>
<b>Women:</b>  Vaginal discharge, abnormal periods.<P>
<b>Avoid It:</b> Use condoms!  Gonorrhea is passed from a man to a woman in the man's semen or between women in the vaginal fluid.<P>
<BR><center><a href="samesex.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR>
<A NAME="4">
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Herpes -- Simplex I</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b>  Red, crusty sore on the mouth area and lips, can be painful -- a "cold sore."  <P>
<b>Women:</b>  Same as in men.<P>
<b>Avoid It:</b>  Though Simplex I is usually found on the mouth area and lips, it can be spread to the genital area.  Therefore, if you or your partner has a Herpes Simplex I sore, kissing and oral sex should be avoided.
<P><BR><center><a href="samesex.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR>
<A NAME="5"><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Herpes -- Simplex II</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b>  Red, crusty sore in or around the genital areas, can be painful.  <P>
<b>Women:</b>  Same as in men.  <P>
<b>Avoid It:</b> Use condoms and dental dams -- but don't forget that sometimes the sores can be in areas that the condoms or dental dams won't cover.  Though Simplex II is usually found on the genital areas, it can be spread to the mouth and lip areas. Therefore, if you or your partner has a Herpes Simplex II sore, do not come into contact with the sore during oral sex.<P>
<BR><center><a href="samesex.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR>
<A NAME="6"><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Human Immunodefiency Virus (HIV)</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b> Usually asymptomatic for many years. <P>
<b>Women:</b> Same as in men.<P>
<b>Avoid It:</b>  Always use condoms (or dental dams) -- even during oral or anal sex.  HIV can be passed through semen, vaginal fluids or blood. <P>
<BR><center><a href="samesex.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR>
<A NAME="7"><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Syphilis</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b> Painless, red,  sunken or "crater-like" sore the size of a dime;  usually found in the genital region.<P>
<b>Women:</b> Same as in men.  <P>
<b>Avoid It:</b>  Always use condoms and/or dental dams during vaginal, anal or oral sex  -- and avoid coming into contact with sores that may not be covered by the condom or dental dam.<P>
<BR><center><a href="samesex.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR>
<A NAME="8"><P>
<FONT SIZE=+1><strong>Trichomoniasis</strong></FONT><BR>
<b>Men:</b>  Can be asymptomatic; or can have inflammation of the penis, and lesions in the genital area.<P>
<b>Women:</b>  Can be asymptomatic; or may have a bad smelling discharge from the vagina; redness, swelling or itching in the vaginal area. <P>
<b>Avoid It:</b>  Always use condoms during sexual intercourse and dental dams during oral sex.  <P>
<BR><center><a href="samesex.html#10">Back To STD List</a><BR></center>
<HR>
