<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace: Rocket Science
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG SRC="images/wssmall.gif" BORDER=0><BR><HR>

<a href="bodshk.html">Back to BodyShock Main Page</a> | <a href="index.html">WomenSpace</a> | <a href="personal.html">Getting Personal</a> | <a href="yogirls.html">Yo! Girls</a> | <a href="grrlstore.html">The Grrl Store</a><BR>
<a href="extra.html">Extra! Extra!</a> | <a href="hotlinx.html">Hot Linx</a><BR>
<a href="../twp/pharmacy.html">The Women's Pharmacy</a></center>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE =+1>
<P>
<BR><BR>
<CENTER><img src="images/body.gif" BORDER=0><BR>
<P>Just because tampons sometimes look like rockets doesn't mean you have to be a Rocket Scientist to use them!  In fact, it's really pretty simple.  Check out the info below on the different kinds of tampons and see how we break it down for you into 5 easy steps ... no graduate degree required!</P>
<P>
<P>The first thing to know is that not all tampons are exactly alike.  Different brands have different features -- like different kinds of applicators.</CENTER>
</P><BR>
<P><img align=left src="images/cardboard.gif" BORDER=0><CENTER>For example, 
there are tampons that have <BR>cardboard applicators. The cool thing about <BR>this kind of tampon is that <BR>you can usually flush the applicator after you've used it.<BR><B>Tampax</B> is the name of a popular brand <BR>of tampons that have cardboard applicators.  </P></CENTER><BR><BR>
<P>
<img align=right src="images/plastic.gif" BORDER=0><CENTER><BR><BR>Another kind of tampon has a plastic applicator. <BR> Some girls say that plastic applicators help <BR>the tampon slide in more easily -- <BR>but you can't flush these! <BR> <b>Playtex</b> is the name of a tampon <BR>that has a plastic applicator.</P></CENTER><BR><BR>
<P><img align=left src="images/noapp.gif" BORDER=0><CENTER>And finally, there are tampons <BR>with no applicators at all -- you insert <BR>the cotton part of the tampon yourself.  <BR><b>ob</b> is the name of a popular brand of tampon <BR>that you use without an applicator.</P></CENTER><BR><BR><BR>
<HR>
Regardless of the type of tampon you use, they all work essentially the same ... the soft, cotton "plug" goes inside your vagina to catch the fluid your body releases when you have your period.<BR><BR>
<B>If you choose a tampon with an applicator, it works like this ...<BR><BR></B>
<b>1.</b>  Take the tampon out of the outer paper or plastic wrapping.  <BR>
<b>2.</b>  Use your finger to find the opening of your vagina. <BR>
<b>3.</b>  Slide the tampon applicator diagonally up inside your vagina as far as possible -- until you feel resistance. (The pointy end goes in first -- so that the string is left outside of your vagina.)<BR>
<b>4.</b>  Pull the cardboard or plastic applicator out so that the cotton is left inside your vagina.<BR><BR></FONT>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
<B>If you choose a tampon without an applicator, it works like this ...<BR><BR></B>
<b>1.</b>  Take the tampon out of the outer wrapping.<BR>
<b>2.</b>  Use your finger to find the opening of your vagina.<BR>
<b>3.</b>  Balance the cotton part of the tampon on your first or second finger.<BR>
<b>4.</b> Using your finger as a guide, slide the cotton diagonally up inside your vagina.<BR><BR></FONT>
<P><ul>Some helpful hints ...  before we get to Step #5.<BR>
*Try to relax the muscles in your vagina -- this will help the tampon slide in more easily.<BR><BR>
*If the tampon applicator doesn't slide in smoothly, put a small amount of lotion on the outside of the applicator before inserting it. <BR><BR>
*Once you've inserted the tampon, it should feel totally comfortable.  In fact, lots of times you don't feel anything at all.  If it doesn't feel comfortable, just remove it!<BR><BR>
*The tampon can not get "lost" up inside you!  It's impossible -- so don't worry about pushing it too far up!  Just make sure that you can easily retrieve the string to remove it later.<BR><BR>
*Your vagina actually sits inside your body at an angle ... so when you insert the tampon, try to angle it as if you're pushing it diagonally toward your back -- NOT straight up toward your brain!!</P><BR><BR></ul>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
<P>You can leave a tampon in for several hours.  (Check out the info on the box to see how long they recommend leaving it in.)  </P>
<P><B>After that time, you remove all three types of tampons exactly the same way ...<BR><BR></B>
<b>5.</b>  Grasp the string(s) that you left hanging outside your vagina and pull down gently until the cotton part of the tampon comes completely out ... then flush it!<BR><BR><BR></P>
<P>There you have it ... <b>5</b> easy steps to using tampons like the pros!  If you still have doubts -- or feel a little squeamish about the whole process -- check out our <a href="tampon.html">Tampon Chorus Line</a> and have a laugh on us!</FONT></P>

</FONT>
