<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace: Shaving
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="DEA7D4">
<BR><BR>
<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="daisystem2.gif">
<FONT SIZE =+1>
<P><BR><BR>
<CENTER>
Check Out Eight Models' Tips for Pretty Legs.  </CENTER><P><BR><BR><BR>
<HR><CENTER>Sponsored by <BR><IMG SRC="ladypers.gif"><BR>Twin Blade Disposable Razors</CENTER>
<HR>
<strong>Warm Water</strong><BR>
<blockquote>"Be sure to use very warm water.  I've found that warmer water opens your pores and makes shaving easier.  Shaving in the bathtub is ideal, but if I have to shave in the shower, I leave it to the very last so that my skin is a little bit more soft and pliable from the steam."</blockquote><P>
<strong>Shaving Gels</strong><BR>
<blockquote>"I always like to shave with plain soap and water, but I find I get much smoother results if I stick with a shaving gel, preferably one with a skin softener built in, like lanolin.  There's even a few that are specifically designed for women, and they're really good."</blockquote>
<P>
<strong>Razor Edge</strong><BR>
<blockquote>"The best advice I ever got on shaving was from my first modeling agent.  She told me to change my razor every few shaves.  A new razor gives you a clean, rust-free edge."</blockquote>
<P>
<strong>Shaving Direction</strong><BR>
<blockquote>"When I'm shaving my legs I always shave against the direction that the hair grows.  In other words, I pull the razor upwards.  But fo the bikini area or the underarms it's absolutely necessary to shave with the hair direction.  Otherwise, you'll get ingrown hairs and that's miserable."</blockquote>
<P>
<strong>Difficult Spots</strong><BR>
<blockquote>"It took me forever to figure out how to really shave my knees.  Eventually, I discovered that if I bent my knees I could get a smoother surface to run the razor over.  Then I make several small, careful strokes up to the knee cap.  Sometimes I have to pull the skin slightly to get a more shaveable surface."</blockquote><P>
<strong>Underarms</strong><BR>
<blockquote>"Shaving underarms is pretty tricky, but by no means impossible.  Best bet is to use a mirror to get a really good view of where your razor is going.  Sometimes I have to actually get out of the shower or tub to look into the mirror over the sink.  But it really makes a difference."</blockquote><P>
<strong>Get A Grip</strong><BR>
<blockquote>"Soapy hands in the shower means slippery razzors -- and that's just a nick waiting to happen.  I try to keep my hands rinsed clean of soap or shaving cream."</blockquote><P>
<strong>Lotion</strong><BR>
<blockquote>"Right after I get out of the shower, I put lotion on my legs ... I only dry them a little and that way the lotion really sinks in and softens.  Some prefer baby oil, but I like lotion."</blockquote>
</FONT>
<center><em><a href="shaving.html">More Info On Shaving ...</em></a><BR><BR>
