<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace: Birth Control Questionnaire
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="DEA7D4">

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="daisystem2.gif">
<FONT SIZE=+1><BR><BR>
Describing You...<BR><BR>
<P>
If you consider yourself to be a "creature of habit", birth control pills
(oral contraceptives) may be an excellent choice for you...   
<P>You must take
one pill each and every day.  Depending on the prescription, there is one
Pill for every day of the month -- including during your period. The Pills
that you take while you have your period are to help you keep track of
where you are in your cycle and remind you when it is time to begin a new
pack.

<P>
The Pills come pre-arranged in a package and must be taken in the sequence
in which they are lined up.  The package will help you remember which day
you are on -- but it's up to you to remember to look inside the package
each day and take the Pill.<P>
<P>
Birth control pills can prevent pregnancy up to 99% of the time -- but
only if you take the Pill every day -- and at the same time each day.  The
more closely you follow this rule the more confident you can be that you
are getting the Pill's highest effectiveness against pregnancy.<P>
<P>
Some medicatons such as antibiotics can interfere with the effectiveness of
the Pill.  Whenever you visit your health care provider, always let her or
him know that you are on the Pill.<P>
<P>
One last thing -- because the Pill works by preventing your ovaries from
releasing eggs (ovulation) -- you must take the Pill for at least one full
month before your body is fully accustomed to it.  Therefore, plan to factor this
month in when you are determining how long you must wait for the Pill to
take affect -- and use another form of birth control in the meantime.<P>
<P>
Although the Pill works well for a lot of women -- but plenty of others find that their bodies cannot tolerate them due to the hormones.  So if you're considering birth control pills, talk with your health care provider about their side effects. <P>
Birth control pills are great at preventing pregnancy -- but they don't
protect you against sexually transmitted diseases.  Always use condoms for this kind of protection!<P>
</FONT><HR>
<center><a href="bc1b.html#1>More Information About Other Methods</a>  |  <a href="bc.html#relate">Go back for second question</a></center>
