<DOCNO>WT12-B29-206</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA073-000478-B004-285</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.womenspace.com:80/fall/bc1b.html 199.224.6.50 19970208233757 text/html 8956
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 08 Feb 1997 23:34:24 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Set-Cookie: Apache=widener10572855444864485; path=/
Content-length: 8732
Last-modified: Wed, 07 Aug 1996 19:30:17 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace:  Birth Control Questionnaire
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="DEA7D4">

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="daisystem2.gif">
<FONT SIZE=+1><BR><BR>
Describing You...
<P>
If you are pretty good at remembering to do things each day -- you're
probably a candidate for using a birth control method like the Pill
(oral contraceptives).  However, the most important thing to realize is
that in order for the Pill to be the most effective,  you must take the
Pill every day -- and at the same time each day.  The more closely you
follow this rule the more confident you can be that you are getting the
Pill's highest effectiveness against pregnancy.<P>

<blockquote><strong>Effectiveness Rate:</strong>  Birth control pills can protect against pregnancy as much as 99% if used
correctly.<P></blockquote>
<P>
Depending on the prescription, there is one Pill for every day of the month
-- including during your period. The Pills that you take while you have
your period are to help you keep track of where you are in your cycle and
remind you when it is time to begin a new pack.<P>
<P>
The Pills come pre-arranged in a package and must be taken in the sequence
in which they are lined up.  The package will help you remember which day
you are on -- but it's up to you to remember to look inside the package
each day and take the Pill.  Therefore, you should try to associate taking
your pill with another routine part of your day -- like brushing your teeth
for bed or taking a shower in the morning.  It doesn't matter which
activity you choose -- or when you choose to do it -- as long as you do it
at the same time every day.<P>
<A NAME="1">
<strong>Other Methods:</strong>  If this seems like it may not be a realistic thing for you to remember, not
to worry!  There are several other methods that you can consider.  For
instance, there are methods of birth control that you use only when you
plan to have sex -- and then there are those methods which are more
"permanent" or "long term".<P>
<P>
Methods like condoms and spermicidal foams, gels, creams and suppositories
are easy birth control methods in that they can be purchased ahead of time.  But even this takes a little planning.<P>
<P>
<blockquote><strong> Effectivess Rate:</strong> Spermicides range in effectiveness from 79% to 97%. </blockquote><P>
Spermicides work best when
used with another method -- like a condom -- which also protects you from sexually transmitted diseases.<P>
<blockquote><strong> Effectivess Rate:</strong> The condom's effectiveness ranges between 88% and 98%.</blockquote>
<P>
The withdrawal method -- when the man pulls his penis out of the woman's vagina before he
ejaculates -- is one method which doesn't require a trip to the drugstore.  However,
it isn't a very effective method for preventing pregnancy. 
<blockquote><strong>Effectiveness Rate:</strong>  The withdrawal method can be up to 82% effective for the typical couple.<P></blockquote>

The "rhythm" method is another natural means of birth control.  It requires the woman to track her body temperature and menstrual cycle in order to predict when she will ovulate.  With this method for birth control, you abstain from having sex during the days surrounding ovulation.  Though this is a widely accepted method for birth control, it does not provide the highest levels of effectiveness -- because it's difficult to predict exactly when you ovulate.
<blockquote><strong> Effectivess Rate:</strong>  The rhythm method can be up to 80% effective. </blockquote>
<P>
Birth control methods such as a diaphragm, cervical cap or the sponge are
considered "barrier" methods because you place them inside your vagina to
cover your cervix.  They physically prevent the sperm from entering your
uterus. These options are pretty effective.  However, your health
care provider must fit you with a diaphragm or a cervical cap -- and both require that you
use a spermicidal foam or jelly along with them to receive the most
effectiveness against pregnancy.<P>
<P>
<blockquote><strong>Effectiveness Rates:</strong>  The diaphagm's effectiveness varies between 81% and 97%.  The cervical cap's effectiveness ranges from 73% to 92%.  The sponge's effectiveness varies between 75% and 83%.  </blockquote> <P>

Diaphragms and cervical caps work like this -- you place a
specified amount of the spermicidal jelly or cream inside the diaphragm or
the cervical cap before placing it inside your vagina.  The spermicide can
last for several hours -- therefore you could feasibly put in the diaphragm
or cervical cap with the spermicide way ahead of the time that you plan to
have sex. You have to leave the diaphragm and the cervical cap in for at
least 6 to 8 hours after the last time you have sex to prevent any sperm
that may still be alive in your vagina from going through your cervix.  If
you decide to have sex again during this time, you have to reinsert
additional spermicide.<P>
<P>
After 6 to 8 hours, you can remove, wash and store the diaphragm or the
cervical cap until you choose to use it again.<P>
<P>
The sponge is a very convenient "barrier" method to use.  The first great thing about the sponge is that you don't need a
prescription to use it -- you can purchase them at the drug store.   The
second great thing is that it is effective for 24 hours once you've
inserted it.  Like the diaphragm and the cerival cap, you have to leave it
in for at least 6 hours after the last time you have sex.<P>
<P>
Because there is a certain amount of planning and "maintenance" required
when using a diaphragm, a cervical cap and the sponge, some women feel that these are better methods to use when you have a partner with whom you communicate well. The reason for this is because there are time constraints involved -- and some say this decreases spontaneity.  Also, the fact that you have to reinsert spermicide each time you have sex with a diaphragm or a cervical cap means that a certain amount of communication with your partner is required.<P>
<P>
There are birth control methods that are "longer term" and/or more
"permanent" that are options for you.  The IUD is a device inserted into your uterus by your
health care provider which can be removed at a later point in time. 
You also have the option of contraceptive implants which are 
surgically inserted usually into the underside of your upper arm.  This method
releases hormones very similar to that of the Pill and can be very
effective against pregnancy for up to five years -- at which time you have
it removed and replaced if you want to continue with the method. 
<P>
A third,
longer term method is an injectable contraceptive.  With this method, you
receive an injection from your health care provider which can be effective
against pregnancy for up three months.   At that time, you have to return
to your health care provider to get an additional injection if you want to
continue with that method.<P>
<P>
<blockquote><strong>Effectiveness Rates:</strong>  The IUD, contraceptive implants and injectable contraceptives all can be as effective as 99%.  </blockquote>
<P>
Finally --  but certainly just as important -- you also have the option of
tubal ligation as a method of birth control.  Tubal ligation -- also called
"having your tubes tied" and "sterilization" --  is a surgical procedure in
which your fallopian tubes are either clamped or cut to prevent the eggs
from traveling from your ovaries to your uterus.  Most people consider this
method to be permanent -- although there have been women who have had the
procedure reversed.  Regardless, it is an extremely effective method
against pregnancy.<P>
<P>
<blockquote><strong>Effectiveness Rates:</strong>  Tubal ligation can be as effective as 99.8%.<P></blockquote>
<P>
Just keep in mind that all the methods mentioned above -- the spermicides,
diaphragms, cervical caps, IUDs, contraceptive implants, injectables and
tubal ligation -- do not protect you from STDs.  Condoms used alone or in
conjunction with one of these methods increases your protection against
both pregnancy and STDS.<P>
</FONT><a href="bc.html#relate">Go back for second question</a>
