<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace:  Birth Control Questionnaire
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="DEA7D4">

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="daisystem2.gif">
<FONT SIZE=+1><BR><BR>
Describing You...<BR><BR>
<P>
If you already realize that you are often forgetful, chances are you
aren't the best candidate for a method such as birth control pills.
However, this doesn't mean that you can't choose this method -- it just
means that you will have to make a conscious, concerted effort to remember
to take the Pill. <P>
<P>
For the Pill to be the most effective,  you must take the Pill every day --
and at the same time each day.  The more closely you follow this rule the
more confident you can be that you are getting the Pill's highest
effectiveness against pregnancy.<P>
<P>
If this sounds like it may not be a realistic thing for you to remember,
not to worry!  There are several other methods that you can consider.  For
instance, there are methods of birth  control that you use only when
you plan to have sex -- and there are also those methods which are more
"permanent" or "long term".<P>
<P>
Methods like condoms and spermicidal foams, gels, creams and suppositories
are easy birth control methods in that they can be easily purchased ahead of time.  But even this takes a little planning.<P>
<P>
<blockquote><strong> Effectivess Rate:</strong> Spermicides range in effectiveness from 79% to 97%. </blockquote><P> 
They work best when
used with another method -- like the condom -- which also protects you from most sexually transmitted
diseases.<P>
<blockquote><strong> Effectivess Rate:</strong>The condom's effectiveness ranges between 88% and 98%.</blockquote>
<P>
