<DOCOLDNO>IA073-000478-B004-336</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.womenspace.com:80/fall/bc2a.html 199.224.6.50 19970208233815 text/html 7333
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 08 Feb 1997 23:34:41 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Set-Cookie: Apache=widener10620855444881616; path=/
Content-length: 7109
Last-modified: Wed, 07 Aug 1996 19:30:18 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace:  Birth Control Questionnaire
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="DEA7D4">

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="daisystem2.gif">
<FONT SIZE=+1><BR><BR>
Your Relationship...<BR><BR><P>

If you've already made the decision to have sexual intercourse with your new partner, you
have a few things to consider:  <BR><a href="bc2a.html#1">(1) will you be having sexual intercourse
with this partner frequently?</a>; <BR><a href="bc2a.html
#2">(2) how well do you communicate with your
partner</a>; and <BR><a href="bc2a.html#3">(3) what is your partner's sexual history?</a>
<P>
<A NAME="1">
<b>(1)</b>  A consideration of the frequency with which you will have
intercourse is important because you may find that you
want a "longer-term" birth control option that is very effective against
pregnancy -- but that doesn't require a special trip to the drugstore each time you plan to have sexual intercourse.  

For longer-term methods which provide you with "every-day" protection against pregnancy,  the Pill is a great method -- but it
requires a certain degree of commitment on your part. 
You must remember to take the Pill everyday -- at the same time everyday.<P>
<P>
You also have the option of an injectable contraceptive -- which is a "shot" or
injection you receive from your health care provider.  Another option are 
contraceptive "capsules" that you have implanted by your health care
provider.<P>
<P>
<blockquote><strong>Length of Effectiveness:</strong>  Injectable contraceptives are effective for up to three months.
Contraceptive implants are effective for up to five years.</blockquote>
<P>
Although the Pill has an extremely low failure rate -- the biggest issue
to consider is that you must remember to take the Pill every single day.
The other two types of contraceptives -- both injectables and implants --
provide you with continuous protection. You don't have to "remember" to
take them -- they're already there!<P>
<P>
The IUD is a "longer-term" birth control method that can be very effective
against pregnancy for many years but can be removed at a later point.   Tubal ligation is
the most "long-term" method of birth control in that most people consider
it to be "permanent." Regardless, it is an extremely effective method
against pregnancy.<P>
<P>
Just keep in mind that all the methods mentioned above -- the Pill,
spermicides, diaphragms, cervical caps, IUDs, contraceptive implants,
injectables and tubal ligation -- do not protect you from STDs.  Condoms
used alone or in conjunction with one of these methods increases your
protection against both pregnancy and STDs.<P>
<P>
<A NAME="2">
<b>(2)</b>  Since neither you nor your partner have brought up the subject of birth
control yet -- it's important for you to consider what methods are
available to you -- and which methods are within your control.   For
instance, methods like the Pill are typically under the complete control of
the woman.  It's up to you to ensure that they are used correctly.  Other
methods like the diaphragm, cervical cap, sponge and spermicides generally
require some degree of communication between you and your partner in order
to use them effectively.  If you don't think that you have very good
communication with your partner -- these methods may or may not be your best birth
control option.<P>
<P>
BUT -- regardless of how well you communicate with your partner on the
topic of birth control or pregnancy -- it is extremely important for you to communicate with him about using a condom to prevent sexually transmitted diseases. 
<P>
<A NAME="3">
<b>(3)</b>  A third consideration to make when deciding on a method of birth
control is your partner's sexual history.  With any new partner, you have to
realize that despite how confident you are in your current relationship,
your new partner may have had sex (whether vaginal, anal or oral) with
another person at some point in the past that could put your at risk for an STD -- regardless of what he tells
you.<P>
<P>
Talking with your partner about sexually transmitted diseases may be
difficult  -- but you have to take precautions to protect yourself -- just
in case!<P>
<P>
What this means is that -- in addition to protection against pregnancy --
you also must protect yourself against sexually transmitted diseases.  In
general, condoms are an excellent choice because they
provide both forms of protection.  However, condoms can only work to
protect when you purchase the correct kind and when you use them correctly.<P>

Latex condoms are the best because they are the most durable and because
they do not allow the tiny organisms of some STDs to come through.  Condoms
made from such materials as lamb skin tend to be more fragile and do not
stop such viruses as HIV and Hepatitis B from going through.<P>

You should store condoms in a cool area.  If your boyfriend (partner) keeps them in
his wallet or in his back pocket, the condom material may "break down" due
to the heat.  Always make sure that the condom is still good by
checking the expiration date on the package.  Finally, never use lubricants
such as petroleum jelly with condoms because this can also "break down" the latex.  The
best lubricant choice is a water-based variety such as KY Jelly.<P>
<P>
Keep in mind that there are certain forms of STDs like Herpes or Syphilis which can be spread by touching an open sore.  Unfortunately, these sores can
sometimes be in places that condoms don't cover -- such as the areas around
the genitals and the anus.  Condoms alone cannot protect you from these
types of sores; therefore, you should look out for them and avoid
direct contact with them.<P>
<P>
Remember that condoms aren't just for sexual intercourse -- they should
also be used for oral or anal sex -- particularly when your partner has an STD or
you see any open sores on or around his penis.<P>
<P>
One last point to consider -- for many, many  years condoms were considered
the "male contraceptive" because the man wears them and often the man was
the one who purchased them.  Today, women not only take the initiative to
purchase "male" condoms themselves -- but they also have the option of
purchasing "female" condoms.  These condoms fit into the vagina and are
held in place by a flexible ring that remains outside the body to cover the
exposed areas of the woman's genitals.  The "female" condom gives women
more choices and more control over pregnancy and sexually transmitted
diseases.<P>
</FONT><a href="bc.html#buy">Go back for third question</a>
