<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace:  Birth Control Questionnaire
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="DEA7D4">

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="daisystem2.gif">
<FONT SIZE=+1><BR><BR>
Your Relationship...<BR><BR><P>

When choosing a method of birth control -- it is very important to consider
the reality of sexually transmitted diseases and learn how to prevent them.  If
you are sexually active with a partner whose 
sexual history you do not know well, you should go ahead and assume that this
person may have a sexually transmitted disease.  Condoms are your first
line of defense in this situation -- and they are an excellent choice for
both birth control and protection against STDs.  You can easily purchase
them yourself and they are fairly inexpensive.<P>
<P>
Purchasing condoms yourself  -- as opposed to relying on your partner to
have them -- is really the best way to go.  Until you have developed a
relationship in which you can communicate with your partner(s) about who
will purchase the birth control, you owe it to yourself to always be
prepared.<P>
<P>
Fully protecting yourself against STDs is the first step -- the second
thing to consider is the effectiveness of the birth control method.  Latex
condoms can be pretty effective in preventing pregnancy when you use them
correctly.<P>
<P>
<blockquote><strong> Effectivess Rate:</strong> The condom's effectiveness ranges between 88% and 98%.</blockquote>
<P>
However, you may decide that you want even more certainty in the type of
birth control method you choose.<P>
<P>
The Pill, contraceptive implants and contraceptive injections are all
excellent choices for high levels of effectiveness against pregnancy. Each
of these methods require a visit to your health care provider.<P>
<P>All of these methods work by manipulating the levels of the
hormones in your body which control ovulation.  Some women feel that these
methods may be "too much trouble" or "too long-term"  -- especially when
they aren't in long-term relationships. Some women choose not to use
these types of hormonal birth control methods because they have side-effects from the hormones.<P>
<P>
You also have the choice of a diaphragm or a cervical cap. However, it is important to keep in
mind that these methods require a certain amount of communication with your
partner in order to use them effectively every time.  Again, many women
feel that these methods may not be the best when in a new
relationship.<P>
<P>
Longer-term methods such as the IUD and more permanent methods such as
tubal ligation are also valid birth control options.  It is important to
realize that, in the case of tubal ligation, the method is considered permanent.  Therefore, over the short-term, this may not be the best choice of birth control methods.<P>
<P>
One last thing ... the higher the number of sexual partners you have, the
higher the likelihood of picking up a sexually transmitted disease.  Some
STDs -- like Chlamydia -- can go unnoticed for a long period of time in
women.  Even though Chlamydia can be "symptom-less", it can cause severe
damage to your body.  Take good care of yourself if you choose
to have more than one sexual partner  -- and always protect yourself by
using condoms.<P>
</FONT>
