<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace: Birth Control Questionnaire
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="DEA7D4">

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="daisystem2.gif">
<FONT SIZE=+1><BR><BR>
Your Relationship...
<BR><BR>
<P>
Because you and your partner are both great planners and communicators, you
have numerous birth control options available to you.  But before exploring
these options, you should take some time to think about how much you know
about your partner's sexual past.<P>
<P>
Regardless of how well you believe you know your partner, it is still
important to bring up the topic of your sexual histories -- and to consider the importance of 
using condoms as a protection against sexually transmitted diseases.   Take
advantage of how well you communicate with him about birth control -- and
determine your need to use condoms.<P>
<P>
In terms of birth control, first consider whether you feel more comfortable
with methods that you use only while you are having sex -- or methods
that require more planning but offer long-term protection.<P>
<P>
Such methods as condoms, spermicidal suppositories, foams, gels and
creams are easy birth control methods in that (1) they can be easily purchased ahead of time; (2) you use them only when you have sexual intercourse, and (3) when used with other methods like condoms or the Pill, they
can be very effective in preventing pregnancy.<P>
<P>
The withdrawal method in which the man pulls out his penis from the women's vagina before he
ejaculates is one method which doesn't require a special trip to the drugstore --
but also doesn't give very effective method for preventing pregnancy.
Failure rates for the withdrawal method can be as high as 18% for the
typical couple.<P>
<P>
Birth control methods such as a diaphragm, cervical cap and the sponge are
excellent methods for couples that communicate well together.  In order to
get the high effectiveness rates of the diaphragm and the cervical cap, you
must use a specified amount of spermicide with the device.  Each time you
have sex, you reinsert more spermicide -- and you must leave the
diaphragm and the cervical cap in for at least 6 to 8 hours after the last
time you have intercourse.  With this amount of planning, you can see that
it is best if you and your partner can work together in making sure that
you have used these methods correctly.<P>
<P>
The sponge works in much the same way -- except that the spermicide is
inside the sponge itself.  There is no need to reapply spermicide; however
you do need to leave the sponge in for at least 6 to 8 hours after the last
time you have sex.<P>
<P>
Birth control methods like the Pill, contraceptive implants and
contraceptive injections are all excellent choices for high levels of
effectiveness against pregnancy.  However, each of these methods require a
visit to a health care provider.   Because methods like the Pill work by
preventing your ovaries from releasing eggs (ovulation) -- you must take
the Pill for at least one full month before your body is accustomed to it.
Therefore, plan to factor this month in when you are determining how long
you must wait for the Pill to take affect -- and use another form of
contraceptive in the meantime.<P>
</FONT>
