<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace: Birth Control Questionnaire
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="DEA7D4">

<IMG ALIGN=LEFT SRC="daisystem2.gif">
<FONT SIZE=+1><BR>
Who will purchase ...<BR><BR>
<P>
If you plan to use a method of birth control such as condoms, spermicidal
jellies or suppositories, it's very simple for your partner to
purchase them -- because you don't need a prescription for any of these.
<P>
Each of these methods can cost anywhere from a nickel for a condom at a
public health center up to $10.00 or more for some jellies, creams
and suppositories.<P>
<P>
If your partner is in charge of purchasing these
products, you should consider what you to do if he should forget to buy
them.  If you discover that he does not have
some birth control while you are in the process of having sex ... will you
continue anyway?   -- will you stop and ask that he purchase something
before going any further?   -- will you purchase them yourself?
<P>
It is great if your partner shares in the expense of buying birth control
-- but you must weigh the benefits of this against the fact that you are
relying on him to protect <em>you.</em>  Though he may care about you very much --
you should always look out for yourself by purchasing back-up
contraceptives just in case he should forget.  That way, you both share in
the responsibility of your decision to have sexual intercourse.
<P>
If you choose one of the other methods we've discussed along the way (the
Pill, diaphragm, cervical cap, contraceptive implants, etc.), it is
important to look into the costs associated with using each one.  You'll
also want to factor in the cost of going to your health care provider to
get an examination for these types of birth control.<P>
<P>
If you have places near you such as a Planned Parenthood, a women's health or
student health clinic, you'll probably find that they can be much less expensive than other places -- if not free!  They provide excellent care and are a great resource for information about birth control and STDs.<P>
FYI -- Though the cost of birth control may seem expensive to you at times, it is certainly safer and less expensive than an unwanted pregnancy.  So take care of yourself by looking into all the birth control methods available.<P>


</FONT>
