<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace: Anorexia and Bulimia
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG SRC="images/wssmall.gif" BORDER=0><BR><HR>
<a href="personal.html">Back to Getting Personal Main Page</a> <BR><a href="index.html">WomenSpace</a> | <a href="bodshk.html">BodyShock</a> | <a href="yogirls.html">Yo! Girls</a> | <a href="grrlstore.html">The Grrl Store</a> | 
<a href="extra.html">Extra! Extra!</a> | <a href="hotlinx.html">Hot Linx</a><BR>
<a href="../twp/pharmacy.html">The Women's Pharmacy</a></center>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<img src="images/pers100.gif" BORDER=0><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
Category 4<BR>Bulimia<BR>Specific Warning Signs<BR><BR><BR>
<P>Two or more answers of "yes" to the statements in Category 4 point toward some classic symptoms of bulimia -- and probably should be discussed with a health care provider.</FONT></CENTER></P>
<P>Bulimia is an eating disorder characterized by many of the symptoms in Category 4 -- forcing yourself to throw up, extreme dieting on some days and gorging on others, excessive use of laxatives, feeling out of control around food.  These symptoms in combination -- and particularly that of binging and purging (throwing up) -- are specific warning signs of bulimia.  </P>
<P>Just as with anorexia nervosa, the health consequences of bulimia are severe -- and lots of young women suffer from it. But there are ways to fight this eating disorder -- and you can start by talking with your health care provider. </P>
<HR>
<center><a href="eatdis.html#5">Go back for Category 5</a><BR></center>
