<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
WomenSpace: Anorexia and Bulimia
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<center><IMG SRC="images/wssmall.gif" BORDER=0><BR><HR>
<a href="personal.html">Back to Getting Personal Main Page</a> <BR><a href="index.html">WomenSpace</a> | <a href="bodshk.html">BodyShock</a> | <a href="yogirls.html">Yo! Girls</a> | <a href="grrlstore.html">The Grrl Store</a> | 
<a href="extra.html">Extra! Extra!</a> | <a href="hotlinx.html">Hot Linx</a><BR>
<a href="../twp/pharmacy.html">The Women's Pharmacy</a></center>
<HR>
<CENTER>
<img src="images/pers100.gif" BORDER=0><BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
Category 5<BR>Bulimia<BR>Specific Alert Signs<BR><BR><BR>
<P>Answering "yes" to statements in Category  5 -- particularly if you can also answer "yes" to statements in Category 4 -- should be a red alert to you to talk with your health care provider.</FONT></CENTER></P>
<P>The symptoms in Category 5 are specific physical things that begin to happen to women who suffer from bulimia. A classic sign is that of cavities.  Throwing up results in the acidic fluids from your stomach passing over your teeth.  When you throw up excessively, this fluid eventually erodes the enamel on your teeth and makes you more likely to get cavities.  Other signs of excessive vomiting are a sore throat and hoarseness.</P>
<P>Finally, throwing up and excessive use of laxatives can leave your body dehydrated.  Dehydration can also lead to constipation -- therefore, it's easy for a person suffering from bulimia to get into a vicious cycle.</P>
<P>Bulimia is a very serious eating disorder that can severely impact your health.  If you think you have some of these classic symptoms and behaviors, see your health care provider for help!</P>

