<a href="../twp/pharmacy.html">The Women's Pharmacy</a></center>
<HR>
<FONT SIZE =+1>
<P><CENTER>
<img src="images/pers100.gif" BORDER=0><BR><BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=+1><BR>Question:  I prefer plain nylon hose without the extra panty.  Are there any positives and negatives to this?<BR><BR></P>
<BR><BR>
<P><B>You'd think that if there are problems with wearing <BR>too-tight stockings -- then wearing plain, nylon hose <BR>should be okay, right? Well, maybe ...</B></FONT></CENTER></P>
<P>The good thing about wearing loose, plain hose is simply to combat the problems with getting little air circulation around the pubic area.  When this area get plenty of air, there is less chance that the micro-organisms that cause yeast infections can thrive.  Wearing loose, plain hose may help with this battle if you are already susceptible to getting these infections.</P>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+1>
<P><CENTER><B>Then again, maybe not ...</B></CENTER></FONT></P>
<P>The problem with wearing plain nylon stockings is that many of them come without the cotton crotch panel area built into the panty.  These panels are excellent because cotton helps keep the pubic area dry -- and provides great protection against yeast infections.  So, loose, plain hose are fine -- but the one's with a cotton panel are the best.</P>
</FONT>
<center><a href="hosehealth.html">Back to the Questionnaire</a></center>
