<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Thunderbolts</TITLE></HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#000000" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#00FFFF" VLINK="#00FF00" ALINK="#FF0000"><IMG WIDTH=180 HEIGHT=50 BORDER=0 ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="images/stormnrs.gif"><hr><H3>News Items</H3><center><IMG WIDTH=288 HEIGHT=115 BORDER=0 ALT="Thunderbolts"ALIGN=TOP SRC="images/thunder.gif"></center><br><h3><em>Sons of Confederate Veterans File Lawsuit</em></h3><p> <b><a href="mailto:ana@stormfront.org">(ANA)</a></b>The Maryland chapter of the Sons of Confederate Veterans filed a federallawsuit yesterday (1/21/97) to keep the state from recalling speciallicense plates with the Confederate flag.  The group says the MarylandMotor Vehicle Administration's (MVA) recall violates their right to freespeech.  The recall was announced on January 2nd after the MVA said itreceived numerous complaints that the plates were offensive to blacks.  TheSons of Confederate Veterans are asking for an injunction stopping therecall and $1,000 in damages for each plate that is recalled.<p><em> Anton H., ANA Editor</em><hr width=85% align=center size=1 noshade><br><h3><em>Tight Security at Burmeister Trial</em></h3><p> <b><a href="mailto:ana@stormfront.org">(ANA)</a></b>The murder trial against former Fort Bragg soldier James Burmeister beganyesterday (1/21/97) under tight security.  Burmeister is accused ofshooting a black couple to death in December 1995.  Police said the murderswere racially motivated and it was reported that Burmeister is a skinhead.The state is seeking the death penalty in the case.  The judge ordered thateveryone must present identification every time they enter the courthouse.He also prohibited purses, briefcases, backpacks, bags and containers ofany kind.  Cell phones and pagers were also banned from the courthouse.<p><em> Anton H., ANA Editor</em><hr width=85% align=center size=1 noshade><br><h3><em>3 Arrested at Georgia Anti-King March</em></h3><p> <b><a href="mailto:ana@stormfront.org">(ANA)</a></b>Three people were arrested at a protest march in a mainly white county inGeorgia yesterday (1/20/97).  About 15 protesters waving Confederate andAmerican flags marched to the Forsyth county courthouse for a three-hourrally.  A spokesman for the sheriff's office said a member of theNationalist Movement was charged with simple assault and twocounter-demonstrators were charged with disorderly conduct.  The marchcelebrated the 10th anniversary of a Martin Luther King march by about 75people which drew over 2,500 counter-demonstrators and ended in rock andbottle throwing.<p><em> Anton H., ANA Editor</em><hr width=85% align=center size=1 noshade><br><h3><em>Hess' Son Speaks on German TV</em></h3><p> <b><a href="mailto:ana@stormfront.org">(ANA)</a></b>On Sunday (1/5/97) Wolf Ruediger Hess said on German television that his father, Rudolf Hess, was "absolutely innocent" and said he was killed by the English because he had proof that Britain wanted to continue World War II.  The program was broadcast on WDR, a privately-owned channel.  Also during the program Hess spoke of Hitler's government, saying "Seven million unemployed, empty public coffers, and after four years, everything was resolved.  [The government] in Bonn would be well inspired if they had someone with Hitler's ideas."  A spokeswoman for WDR said they were making no apologies for the broadcast because the chairman of the discussion reacted immediately in condemning Hess' views.  She also said about 30 to 40 complaints were received after the broadcast.<p><em> Anton H., ANA Editor</em><hr width=85% align=center size=1 noshade><br><h3><em>MD Special License Plate Angers Blacks</em></h3><p> <b><a href="mailto:ana@stormfront.org">(ANA)</a></b>Black leaders in Maryland are angered that the Confederate flag will be appearing on special license plates.  Maryland's Motor Vehicle Administration authorized the plates for members of the nonprofit group Sons of the Confederate Veterans (SCV).  Leroy W. Warren Jr. of the NAACP said "The state should not be selling those kinds of license plates.  There is no justifiable reason to remind people of the darkest days in this country's history."  Maryland State Senator Larry Young, who is also chairman of the Legislative Black Caucus, said "I'm taken aback.  I thought our climate was becoming progressive, but this situation shows obviously not."  A SCV member who requested the plate said "We did not choose to enter this program to evoke a controversy or fly a symbol into anybody's face.  It's a demonstration of pride just like any other institution would want to instill pride in their membership."  The Motor Vehicle Administration said officials did not find the design objectionable when they reviewed the application two years ago.  They also said they will now take another look.<p><em> Anton H., ANA Editor</em><hr width=85% align=center size=1 noshade><center><IMG WIDTH=468 HEIGHT=14 BORDER=0 ALIGN=MIDDLE SRC="images/barred.gif"></center><br><CENTER><IMG WIDTH=228 HEIGHT=305 BORDER=0 ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="images/bornwhit.gif"></CENTER><hr><hr><A HREF="defaultf.htm"><IMG WIDTH=35 HEIGHT=35 BORDER=0 ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="images/wplogos.gif">Return to main page</A> | <a href="current2.htm">Previous News Items</a> | <a href="mailto:dblack@jbx.com">E-mail Stormfront</a> | <a href="lform.htm">Post to the letters page</a></body></html>
