<P><IMG SRC="images/stormgreen.gif"  ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="images/barus.gif"  ALIGN=TOP></P>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER><FONT COLOR="#0000A0">Louis Beam Stirs Up a Tempest</FONT></H1>

<P><IMG SRC="images/bookcov.jpg" HSPACE=10 VSPACE=5 HEIGHT=244 WIDTH=160 ALIGN=LEFT></P>

<P><B>by Bob Matthews</B></P>

<P>Morris Dees has written a book that purports to be about America's militia
movement entitled <B><I>Gathering Storm</I></B> with a subtitle of <I>America's
Militia Threat</I>. Though the title would make one think it is about the
militia, it is in fact a book largely about Louis Beam, a long-time patriot,
writer, and speaker. The militia movement is mentioned as a by-product
of the attack on Beam.</P>

<P>Dees wastes no time launching his verbal ICBM's at Beam. From the first
sentence to the last page Beam is castigated for his speeches against what
is wrong in America today. Beam's speech at Estes Park, Co. in 1992 plays
a central part of the book. Page one, line one (quoted without Dees' own
distracting commentary) begins thusly:</P>

<UL>
<P>Louis Beam minced no words.</P>

<P>&quot;I warn you calmly, coldly, and wit<TT>h</TT>out reservation that
over the next ten years you will come to hate government more than anything
in your life. The federal government in north Idaho has demonstrated brutally,
horribly, and with great terror how it will enforce its claim that we are
religious fanatics and enemies of the state. We must in one voice, cry
out that we will not tolerate their stinking, murdering, lying, corrupt
government.</P>

<P>Men, in the name of our Father, we are called upon to make a decision,
a decision that you will make in the quietness of your heart, in the still
places of the night.</P>

<P>As you lie on your bed and you look up at the ceiling tonight, you must
answer the question: Will it be liberty or will it be death? As for me,
give me liberty or give me death!&quot;</P>
</UL>

<P>Dees claims that Beam evokes the image of Adolf Hitler speaking to the
assembled millions in pre-war Germany. Reassembling Beam's speech from
the dissection performed by Dees leaves us with something like the following
paragraph, this time with Dees' interjections included.</P>

<UL>
<P>&quot;We bear the torch of light, of justice, of liberty, and we will
be heard,&quot; Beam shouted over the cheers of his audience. &quot;We
will not yield this country to the forces of darkness, oppression, and
tyranny. I cannot compromise with such men, they are men without principle.
I cannot reason with such men, they are men without reason. But I can warn
them, and it is a warning they must take to heart. I and many others in
this country, many in this room tonight , will not roll over and play dead
for your New World Order.&quot; The amens, hallelujahs, and applause that
erupted from the audience made Beam's closing words almost inaudible.</P>
</UL>

<P>Dees believes that &quot;There is nothing harmless about Louis Beam.
Charismatic, intelligent, and well spoken, Beam moves people... He was,
and is, far and away the most dangerous...of leaders.&quot; [I spare the
reader of this review the name calling Dees engages in at this point in
the book]</P>

<P>One thing is for sure. Beam knows the government. In the course of the
speech he makes a forbidding prediction that has sadly come true.</P>

<UL>
<P>&quot;The attack on the Weaver family by federal assassins was an attack
upon every family in the United States. This time the federal terrorists,
masquerading as officers, came for Randy Weaver. Next time they may come
for you... If federal terrorism goes unchallenged, then no one in this
nation is safe. Government terrorism, if ignored, does not go away, but
gets worse. Like a lion having tasted the blood of human victims, they
will come for more, new victims.&quot;</P>
</UL>

<P>Less than a year later black-booted thugs would pour from a cattle truck
in Waco, resulting in the horrible death of nearly a hundred people by
bullets and fire.</P>

<P>It is clear from a quick reading of <B><I>Gathering Storm</I></B> that
Beam's main crime and reason for being targeted by Dees is his ability
to appeal to the hearts of men in his speeches. Those who have heard him
speak often refer to him as the &quot;Patrick Henry&quot; of the American
Right. So is it Hitler or Henry? This is a decision that will be made by
those who listen to him speak. Has Adolf Hitler come to America with a
Texas drawl, or has Patrick Henry returned to once again urge his countrymen
to rebel against government tyranny?</P>

<P>You be the judge. A tape of this speech can be ordered from Stormfront
publications.</P>

<PRE>Stormfront
PO Box 6637
West Palm Beach FL 33405
$29.95 postpaid</PRE>

