<H1>Pat Buchanan Stuns Establishment</H1>

<p><em>by Don Black</em></center>


<p>Pat Buchanan has stunned the political and media Establishment with his victory in New Hampshire's presidential primary. Four years ago, his quixotic presidential bid was tolerated as a useful foil to the short-lived David Duke campaign. Now,  however, as Rabbi Avi Weiss shrieks in today's <em>Palm Beach Jewish Journal</em>, he's "an anti-Semite out of control."

<p>The Buchanan campaign has been discussed at some length on the Stormfront-L mailing list over the past six months, with some posters enthusiastically supporting Buchanan, while others believe he's just another Establishment shill. Regardless of his underlying philosophy and motives, however, Buchanan is now shaking the <em>status quo</em> to its core.

<p>I first noticed Buchanan in 1982, when he described the black riots in Washington, D.C. which followed an aborted Klan demonstration I had originally organized. The anticipated KKK march had created so much consternation among federal authorities that the Supreme Court had actually moved up an appeal I had filed challenging my previous conviction for violating the Neutrality Act. The Court denied <em>certiori</em> and I was ordered to report to a Mexican-dominated prison in Texas, rather than lead a demonstration in opposition to illegal Mexican immigration in the nation's capital. Though some Klansmen still showed up, the march was cancelled. The real story was the aftermath, which the national media portrayed as righteous indignation to Klan "hatred." Buchanan, however,  told the truth,  "When it comes to hatred, to violence, to racism, the Knights of the KKK can't hold a candle to the thuggish and criminal elements in the black community in Washington, D.C." Hmmm....

<p>After that, his columns and comments on CNN's <em>Crossfire</em> become a refreshing alternative to the "mainstream" media's usual drivel. He railed against "affirmative action" and other anti-White programs long before it was fashionable to do so. He decried the pernicious affects of Third World immigration on the city and the country where he grew up. Against his fellow conservatives' multi-nationalism and interventionism, he stood up for an America First foreign policy. He called Capitol Hill "Israeli occupied territory." When opinion polls were giving George Bush a ninety percent approval rating for his planned intervention in the Persian Gulf, Buchanan wrote, "There are only two groups beating the drums for war in the Middle East--the Israeli Defense Ministry and its amen corner in the U.S." And then, in a comment that Jews seem particularly sensitive to,  he said the war would be fought by "kids with names like McAllister, Murphy, Gonzales and Leroy Brown."

<p>In 1987 he spoke out against the impending deportation of Karl Linnas to the U.S.S.R., whom the Soviets has accused of "Nazi war crimes" in Estonia. He lost that battle. Linnas was deported by the U.S. and summarily executed by the Soviets. He then became the champion of retired Cleveland auto worker John Demjanjuk, whom Israel was accusing of "war crimes." Demjanjuk was extradited to Israel and, after a show trial held in a movie theater, sentenced to hang. Buchanan was vindicated this time, though, when the Israeli Supreme Court was forced to release Demjanjuk when new evidence was released by the Russians after the collapse of the U.S.S.R.

<p>Then Buchanan announced his candidacy for the Republican nomination for president in 1992 against George Bush, who was then considered unbeatable. Considering his previous statements, he was treated surprisingly gently by the media and other politicians. Since David Duke was also running in some Republican presidential primaries, many Duke supporters believed Buchanan's sole purpose was to siphon votes from the less "respectable" Duke. Whatever his motives,  he certainly undermined the Duke candidacy. During the latter part of his flagging campaign, he would crow at every fundraising gathering about having "buried David Duke in the bayou."

<p>With Duke now back in a U.S. Senate race, and with the Establishment's handpicked presidential candidate Bob Dole now wounded, "Loose Cannon" Buchanan, as some of his detractors have started calling him, now poses a  real threat. We can expect some real fireworks in the next few months.

<p>I can remember the outrage and panic in 1980 when Texas' former governor John Connally announced he would run for president. Connally had done no more than call America a "Christian nation" and suggest that Israel withdraw from the West Bank. One columnist in a major Jewish newspaper responded by implying that Connally should be assassinated if he should come "anywhere near" the White House. The media used Connally's own wheeler-dealer image to qucikly put an end to his candidacy, and then federal authorities tried to ensure he would never again pose a threat by indicting him on fabricated criminal charges, which he would later beat. (In an ironic twist, the Texas oilman who was his principal campaign fundraiser would be convicted on trumped up racketeering charges and would become my prison roommate and a close friend in 1984.)  

<p>Unlike Connally, Buchanan's populist message resonates with White working people. They know from personal experience that NAFTA and GATT, and exporting jobs to Mexico, are not in their best interests. As this "transition to a global economy" causes their incomes to continue to decline, they become even angrier about paying higher taxes to support a welfare underclass. They've experienced the anti-White racism called "affirmative action." They've seen many parts of their country turned into Third World cesspools because of the government's immigartion policy.  Pat Buchanan's campaign will continue its phenomenol growth because he is the only candidate taking their side.

<p>Despite Buchanan's courageous statements and despite the hatred he has engendered from our enemies, should we consider him one of us? Is he a White Nationalist? Well...not exactly. Buchanan's worldview is rooted in his traditional Catholic background. This accounts for his love of Western culture and his sense of justice, and his willingness to fight the enemies of these, whether they be America-last Zionists or Third World immigrants. This doesn't mean he's racially conscious. He apparently doesn't fully appreciate the central importance of race in the "culture war" he talks about. His sister Bay seems to be even more oblivous to the concept of Race, and she seems to be a major influence on her brother.

<p>Should we support him? In my opinion, yes. My first priority this election year is the David Duke Senate campaign. David does understand the real issues. But for those who want to be part of a national campaign, this is one worth considering. 

<p>Will Buchanan support us? No, of course not, though I suspect he will be forced to adopt a more tolerant attitude toward supporters who are members or former members of racialist organizations. There are just too many of them and the media would love to spend the rest of the campaign finding them. He can not be expected to embrace us,  however. He's no longer exhorting from the sidelines; he wants to be president. Nevertheless, I believe  that he is a trailblazer. He will make White Americans more aware of the real issues and of  their real enemies, and he will pave the way for other,  more racially oriented, candidates at all levels.



