<head>
<title>Up Front 18--Light at the End of the Tunnel </title>
</head>
<BODY background="images/upfront!bkg.gif">

<IMG WIDTH=72 HEIGHT=77 HSPACE=15 BORDER=0 ALIGN=BOTTOM SRC="images/upfront!s.gif">
<center><IMG WIDTH=470 HEIGHT=6 BORDER=0 ALIGN=TOP SRC="images/gradlin2.gif"></center>
<h1>Light at the End of The Tunnel</h1>
<h2> Act of Bravery Leads to Assault Conviction</h2>
<p><strong>By Gerry Lincoln</strong>
<p><i>with files from Jean Morrison</i>

<p>Following numerous acquittals over the past eighteen months on
various political harassment charges, Wolfgang Droege faced the
final hurdle during a four-day trial in February.
<p>Droege, along with Peter Mitrevski, was charged in June 1993
following a late-night brawl with leftists in Toronto's west end.
Droege faced one count of aggravated assault and one of "weapons
dangerous" - a heavy-duty flashlight. Mitrevski was similarly
charged with "weapons dangerous" for being in possession of a
wooden stick which he had wrested from the grasp of a wild-eyed
anti-racist during the melee.
<p>The brawl was the culmination of an orgy of violence initiated by
members of a group of radical leftists, feminists and militant
lesbians known as the ARA (Anti-Racist Action) on the evening of
June 11. A howling mob of these moronic misfits had descended on
the rented home of Gary Schipper, trashing it while police looked
on.
<p>At the exhortation of Grant Bristow - and it didn't take much
urging - about forty Front supporters headed to Sneaky Dee's, a
renowned leftist hangout, to show the "anti-racists" that they
would not be intimidated.
<p>After staying for one drink, just long enough to make their point,
the HF members left in a group.
<p>But somehow 17-year-old Adrian Galinas became separated from his
friends and found himself facing a mob of about forty jeering
leftists. Police looked the other way, Galinas testified, as he was
kicked and beaten by the out-of-control rabble.
<p>Beaten and bloodied, the young man approached an officer, telling
him that he needed medical attention. He was informed by the
disdainful cop, "the hospital's that way. I suggest you start
walking."
<p>Meanwhile, Droege, Mitrevski and Max French had been circling the
block in an effort to make sure that everyone had evacuated the
area safely. They spotted what Max French referred to as a
"homicide in progress." Abandoning his vehicle in the middle of the
street and grabbing his flashlight, Droege and his friends jumped
into the fray.
<p>He was immediately accosted by a six-foot-six, bottle-wielding
dunderhead with a leering, slack-jawed grin and a vacant stare. The
ponytail-bedecked lout struck Droege a smashing blow to the side of
the head. Droege retaliated with a precisely-aimed wallop with his
flashlight to his antagonist's jaw - a blow which sent "Baby Huey"
into dreamland.
<p>At his trial, it was to become a point of contention whether
Droege had struck his assailant once or twice.
<hr>
<p>Over twenty months had passed since that crazy night of June 11th
1993. In sharp contrast to earlier court appearances, police
outnumbered both HF and leftist supporters as Droege and Mitrevski
made their way into the Federal Court building on Toronto's
University Avenue.
<p>Droege's lawyer, Harry Doan, began by asking judge David McCombs to
delay the case until CSIS spy Grant Bristow could be located to
testify. 
<p>"He's absolutely vital. He was there," Doan stated.
<p>To back up the defence claim, they played a portion of the <i>Best of
Bristow</i> tape, where Bristow urges supporters to confront their
opponents head on. 
<p>This evidence failed to convince the judge of
the need for Bristow to testify, but it did spark interest in the
latest HF video release. Outside the courthouse, sales of <i>In His
Own Words: The Best of Bristow</i> were brisk.
<p>George Wootten, Peter Mitrevski's lawyer added, "we've tried to
locate him," and speculated that Bristow is possibly in some sort
of witness protection program. The judge denied their request for
an adjournment and ordered the trial to proceed.
<p>The first Prosecution (Crown) witness was Detective Constable Paul
Cummins of the Metro Police, who testified that Wolfgang Droege was
the man he saw beating anti-racist Malcolm Sheppard with a
flashlight. Cummins stated under oath that Droege had hit the
victim after he had already fallen to the ground. Droege vehemently
denied the allegation, claiming he only hit the man once. The
officer testified that he arrested Mr. Droege shortly thereafter.
Other police evidence indicated that the anti-racists were well-
armed with empty liquor bottles and other potential weapons.
<p>On the second day, ARA supporter Malcolm Sheppard took the witness
stand. Sheppard, who stated he is a Grade 12 student, is a hulking
22-year-old with an admitted learning disability. (No kidding!)
<p>Defence lawyer Harry Doan, while cross-examining Sheppard, asked
incredulously, "You're 22 and in Grade Twelve?"
<p>"What can I say? I'm a slow learner," Sheppard responded
flippantly.
<p>In a surprise turn of events, the next witness to give evidence
was a strange individual named Darren Fox.
<p>The prosecution attorney announced that Fox feared retribution and
would be testifying in disguise. He also wanted to testify behind
a screen.
<p>Doan countered, "He can testify with a bag over his head for all
I care." Judge McCombs ruled that a wig would be fine.
<p>And what a wig it was!
<p>An unshaven Fox entered the courtroom, wearing a trenchcoat that
would have made Columbo look like a fashion model. His "wig" - a dilapidated 
Marilyn Monroe-style hairpiece thatlooked as though it had been left outdoors 
at the mercy of the elements for at least a couple of weeks - caused the entire court
to convulse with laughter.
<p>"That certainly is a wig," Judge McCombs remarked.
<p>When asked to describe his occupation, Fox mumbled incoherently,
raising his voice only when saying the words "law enforcement."
Asked to repeat his answer, it turns out he is employed as a
"private parking enforcement officer." His employment was never
confirmed, one way or the other.
<p>Fox testified that he saw a man beating a defenceless individual
with a flashlight. "He has a goatee," he muttered, "not very
attractive."
<p>"What did you say," the judge asked, "did you say not very
attractive?"
<p>Darren Fox replied uncomfortably, "I mean the tie ...(pause)...the
tie he's wearing."
<p>After another police officer testified regarding Mitrevski's
activities, it was the defence team's turn.
<p>Max French took the stand, telling the court how he and his
comrades had been driving away from Sneaky Dee's when he came upon
what he described as a "homicide in progress."
<p>Following French`s testimony, most of the anti-racists left the
courtroom, allowing, as one observer noted, "a breath of fresh air
to enter the premises."
<hr>
<p>The ill-behaved contingent of leftist rabble had behaved boorishly
from the onset. In contrast to most of the HF people who were
neatly attired for the occasion, the ARA bunch, with one exception,
presented a sorry spectacle.
<p>The most presentable among them, a left-wing activist named Kevin
Thomas, had been having a conversation with an out-of-town print
journalist, when the hideous Katrin Clouse, a loathsome creature
with the mouth of an unflushed toilet, approached and demanded of
the bewildered author, "why don't you fuck off?"
<p>He was stunned by her remark. "Oh boy." he said, "they sure are
hateful. What did I do?"
<p>His crime? He had been seen shaking Wolfgang Droege's hand and
chatting with Heritage Front supporters in a friendly manner.
<p>"He's now diseased! He shook Wolfgang's hand," the foul-mouthed
Clouse continued to shriek, to anyone who would listen.
<p>An amused Wolfgang grinned when told of her puerile outburst.
<p>Back at the CIUT studios, Kevin Thomas and his amigos devoted half
their Upper Cut radio show to news of the ongoing trial. His most
cutting remark was a comment that Wolfgang seems to be getting a
little "wide" lately.
<p>Once again, Wolfgang chuckled.
<hr>
<p>Next, young Adrian Galinas took the stand, essentially repeating
testimony he had given in the earlier trial of Chris Newhook. He
told of fearing for his life as he was attacked by the out-of-control 
mob and rabid anti-racists. The clean-cut youth also
related how, when he had asked police for assistance, he had been
pointed in the direction of a hospital and told to "start walking."
<p>Droege took the stand in his own defence. Not given to short
answers, he described at length events leading to the melee and
the subsequent skirmish which led to his arrest. As evidence, he
introduced his bloodied shirt and pictures of his injuries.
<p>Up next, Peter Mitrevski described much the same scene, and told
the court how he had wrestled a stick from his attacker, only to be
charged with the possession of that stick as a weapon later.
<p>George Burdi, of RaHoWa, confirmed that HF members had gone to
Sneaky Dee's at Bristow's insistence to "save face." The prosecutor
suggested that Front members were spoiling for a fight. Burdi
retorted, "Our five or six security men were the biggest and
strongest of the bunch. If we were looking for a fight, we wouldn't
have left."
<hr>
<p>With all the evidence in, it was time for summations.
<p>The Crown Attorney, reflecting on Droege's testimony, stated, "All
his answers were speeches. I don't know if I ever did get a
straight answer to some of my questions. Just speeches!"
<p>Justice McCombs, commenting on Mitrevski's case, remarked, "I'm
quite sure a person, having taken a stick from his attacker,
wouldn't take it and then lay it down on the sidewalk."
<p>While <i>Toronto Sun</i> reporter Bill Dunphy had earlier told
Droege outside the courtroom, "I found his [Darren Fox's] testimony
quite credible," apparently McCombs disagreed. He referred to Fox
as "bizarre" and questioned his mental stability.
<p>While admonishing Mitrevski for his failure to recognize the
seriousness of the proceedings, the judge nevertheless acquitted
the duo of the "weapons dangerous" charge.
<p>Droege's conviction for aggravated assault seemed to hinge on
whether or not he had struck Sheppard more than once. The judge
chose to believe police testimony.
<p>Sentencing is set for March 9th.
<P>

<hr noshade>
