<H3><i>Race Bias #2</i></H3>

<h1>Minority Recruiting Service</h1><p>

In much of the racial dialogue in the U.S., integrationists
dispute the simple fact of anti-White bias in the system. Of
course, the media generally propagate our national myths--myths 
intended to hide the ball from the majority.  But there is
one major daily newspaper that is overwhelmingly subscriber
supported (and not supported by ad revenue). So it is no surprise
that this well known paper reports the facts. <b>All</b> the facts.<p>

A tidbit on private racial preference schemes from
Yggdrasil:<p>

<hr>

<b><i>Business and Race</i></b><p>

By Leon E. Wynter<p>
08/22/91<i>Wall Street Journal</i> (J), PAGE B1<p>

<b>Privacy, Recession Help Job Service Find Work</b><p>

HEADHUNTER William Ellis says the recession has helped him
start a novel computerized recruiting service.<p>

Interspace Interactive, New York, sells corporate
subscribers an on-line catalog of potential hires -- with
minorities accounting for some 60% of his 3,000-person
listing. Though companies are doing more firing than hiring,
Mr. Ellis says the recession helped make the service
marketable to employers by providing him with an ample pool
of candidates, who pay $25 a year to be listed.<p>

Interspace's electronic service, which has placed 15
people in three months, doesn't provide candidates' names or
current employers without their permission in each case. Mr.
Ellis says privacy gets him better candidates who don't want
their names widely circulated.<p>

Corporate clients, including Citicorp and Sony, pay $1,500
a year for the service, but commissions are only 15% of a new
hire's salary, compared with an industry standard of 25% to
30%.<p>

